{"title_page": "Peredur Lynch", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n'''Peredur I. Lynch''' (born 13 January 1963) is a [[Wales|Welsh]] academic specialising in Welsh literary history.\n\nLynch spent much of his early life in [[Carrog]] in northern Wales and obtained a degree at [[Bangor University]].<ref name=WA>{{Cite web |title=About the Editors |work= The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |url=http://www.encyclopaediaofwales.com/english/peredur-lynch |accessdate=25 April 2010 |ref=WA }}</ref> He has won a number of [[Eisteddfod]] Chairs, beginning with the [[Urdd National Eisteddfod]] Chair at Maesteg in 1979. His ''[[awdl]]'' was received so well that in 1980 he was lauded as \"one of the great potentials of Welsh poetry\".<ref>{{Cite journal |journal=Poetry Wales |volume=16 |year=1980 |page=72 }}</ref>\n\nLynch, however, became best known for his academic career and his scholarly work on Welsh literary history. In 1985, he became a Research Fellow at the [[University of Wales]] Centre for Advanced Welsh and Celtic Studies in Aberystwyth (1985-1990), moved to [[Swansea University|Swansea]] to become lecturer in Welsh and in 1995 returned to his alma mater (Bangor), where he was also appointed as lecturer in Welsh.<ref name=WA /> In 2003 he became head of the Welsh Department at Bangor (2003-2006), and in 2005 was appointed to a professor's chair.<ref name=WA /><ref name=Bangor>{{Cite web |title=Professor Peredur I. Lynch BA PhD |url=http://www.bangor.ac.uk/ysgolygymraeg/staff/peredur.php.en |publisher=Bangor University }}</ref>\n\nHis scholarly contributions have focused on medieval and early modern Welsh poetry, notably that of the [[Gogynfeirdd]] or Poets of the Princes.<ref name=Bangor /> He assisted [[J. E. Caerwyn Williams]] in preparing an edition of Gogynfeirdd poetry, the first to be published for Cyfres Beirdd y Tywysogion ('The Poets of the Princes series'), and made further contributions to the series. On the topic of prophecy in Welsh poetry, he has both led a research project (2002-2005) and read a paper in the 2004 J. E. Caerwyn and Gwen Williams Memorial Lecture.<ref name=Bangor /> He is one of the editors of the ''[[Welsh Academy]] Encyclopaedia of Wales''.<ref name=WA /><ref name=Bangor />\n\nIn 2001, Lynch published ''Cywion Nell'', a Welsh adaptation of [[Robert Barnard]]'s 1981 novel ''Mother's Boys''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Adnabod Awdur: Peredur Lynch |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cymru/adloniant/llyfrau/awdur/010503peredur.shtml |publisher=BBC |date=May 2001 }}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n;Academic\n*1994. Ed., with J.E. Caerwyn Williams. ''Gwaith [[Meilyr Brydydd]] a'i Ddisgynyddion''. Cyfres Beirdd y Tywysogion I. Cardiff: University of Wales Press.\n*2000. \"Court Poetry, Power and Politics\". In ''The Welsh King and his Court'', ed. T.M. Charles\u2013Edwards, et al. Cardiff: University of Wales Press. pp.&nbsp;167\u201390.\n*2008. Ed. with John Davies, Nigel Jenkins and Menna Baines. ''The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales''. Cardiff: University of Wales Press. {{ISBN|978-0-7083-1953-6}}.\n*2007. ''Proffwydoliaeth a'r Syniad o Genedl''. Bangor: University of Wales, Bangor. {{ISBN|978-1-84220-103-9}}\n\n;Other\n*2001. ''Cywion Nell''. {{ISBN|978-0-948469-71-8}}.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite web |title=About the Editors: Peredur I. Lynch |work= The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |url=http://www.encyclopaediaofwales.com/english/peredur-lynch |accessdate=25 April 2010 |ref=WA}}\n*{{Cite web |title=Professor Peredur I. Lynch BA PhD |url=http://www.bangor.ac.uk/ysgolygymraeg/staff/peredur.php.en |publisher=Bangor University }}\n*{{Cite journal |journal=Poetry Wales |volume=16 |year=1980 |page=72 }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lynch, Peredur}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century British poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:People from Montgomeryshire]]\n[[Category:Welsh scholars and academics]]\n[[Category:Welsh-language poets]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Bangor University]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n'''Peredur I. Lynch''' (born 13 January 1963) is a [[Wales|Welsh]] academic specialising in Welsh literary history.\n\nLynch spent much of his early life in [[Carrog]] in northern Wales and obtained a degree at [[Bangor University]].<ref name=WA>{{Cite web |title=About the Editors |work= The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |url=http://www.encyclopaediaofwales.com/english/peredur-lynch |accessdate=25 April 2010 |ref=WA }}</ref> He has won a number of [[Eisteddfod]] Chairs, beginning with the [[Urdd National Eisteddfod]] Chair at Maesteg in 1979. His ''[[awdl]]'' was received so well that in 1980 he was lauded as \"one of the great potentials of Welsh poetry\".<ref>{{Cite journal |journal=Poetry Wales |volume=16 |year=1980 |page=72 }}</ref>\n\nLynch, however, became best known for his academic career and his scholarly work on Welsh literary history. In 1985, he became a Research Fellow at the [[University of Wales]] Centre for Advanced Welsh and Celtic Studies in Aberystwyth (1985-1990), moved to [[Swansea University|Swansea]] to become lecturer in Welsh and in 1995 returned to his alma mater (Bangor), where he was also appointed as lecturer in Welsh.<ref name=WA /> In 2003 he became head of the Welsh Department at Bangor (2003-2006), and in 2005 was appointed to a professor's chair.<ref name=WA /><ref name=Bangor>{{Cite web |title=Professor Peredur I. Lynch BA PhD |url=http://www.bangor.ac.uk/ysgolygymraeg/staff/peredur.php.en |publisher=Bangor University }}</ref>\n\nHis scholarly contributions have focused on medieval and early modern Welsh poetry, notably that of the [[Gogynfeirdd]] or Poets of the Princes.<ref name=Bangor /> He assisted [[J. E. Caerwyn Williams]] in preparing an edition of Gogynfeirdd poetry, the first to be published for Cyfres Beirdd y Tywysogion ('The Poets of the Princes series'), and made further contributions to the series. On the topic of prophecy in Welsh poetry, he has both led a research project (2002-2005) and read a paper in the 2004 J. E. Caerwyn and Gwen Williams Memorial Lecture.<ref name=Bangor /> He is one of the editors of the ''[[Welsh Academy]] Encyclopaedia of Wales''.<ref name=WA /><ref name=Bangor />\n\nIn 2001, Lynch published ''Cywion Nell'', a Welsh adaptation of [[Robert Barnard]]'s 1981 novel ''Mother's Boys''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Adnabod Awdur: Peredur Lynch |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cymru/adloniant/llyfrau/awdur/010503peredur.shtml |publisher=BBC |date=May 2001 }}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n;Academic\n*1994. Ed., with J.E. Caerwyn Williams. ''Gwaith [[Meilyr Brydydd]] a'i Ddisgynyddion''. Cyfres Beirdd y Tywysogion I. Cardiff: University of Wales Press.\n*2000. \"Court Poetry, Power and Politics\". In ''The Welsh King and his Court'', ed. T.M. Charles\u2013Edwards, et al. Cardiff: University of Wales Press. pp.&nbsp;167\u201390.\n*2008. Ed. with John Davies, Nigel Jenkins and Menna Baines. ''The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales''. Cardiff: University of Wales Press. {{ISBN|978-0-7083-1953-6}}.\n*2007. ''Proffwydoliaeth a'r Syniad o Genedl''. Bangor: University of Wales, Bangor. {{ISBN|978-1-84220-103-9}}\n\n;Other\n*2001. ''Cywion Nell''. {{ISBN|978-0-948469-71-8}}.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite web |title=About the Editors: Peredur I. Lynch |work= The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |url=http://www.encyclopaediaofwales.com/english/peredur-lynch |accessdate=25 April 2010 |ref=WA}}\n*{{Cite web |title=Professor Peredur I. Lynch BA PhD |url=http://www.bangor.ac.uk/ysgolygymraeg/staff/peredur.php.en |publisher=Bangor University }}\n*{{Cite journal |journal=Poetry Wales |volume=16 |year=1980 |page=72 }}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lynch, Peredur}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century British poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:People from Montgomeryshire]]\n[[Category:Welsh scholars and academics]]\n[[Category:Welsh-language poets]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Bangor University]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peredur_Lynch"}
{"title_page": "Pete Doherty", "text_new": "{{About|the musician|other people with the same name}}\n{{short description|English musician, writer, actor, poet and artist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n<!--BEFORE ADDING TO THIS PAGE, PLEASE ENSURE YOU REFERENCE CORRECTLY. INLINE CITATIONS ARE IN USE. COPY AND PASTE FROM A PREVIOUS REFERENCE AND EDIT IT TO FIT YOUR SOURCE. INFORMATION SURROUNDING PETE DOHERTY IS OFTEN RUMOUR AND PLACING SOURCES IN THE ARTICLE WILL HELP MAINTAIN THE INTEGRITY OF WIKIPEDIA. YOUR ASSISTANCE IS APPRECIATED.-->\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Pete Doherty\n| image               = Peter.Doherty.jpg\n| caption             = Doherty in 2012\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Peter Doherty\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1979|03|12}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Trendell |first1=Andrew |title=Pete Doherty celebrates birthday by singing 'What A Waster' live with his dad {{!}} NME |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/pete-doherty-celebrates-birthday-singing-waster-live-dad-2015816 |website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM |accessdate=24 December 2019 |date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Hexham]], Northumberland, England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         =\n| genre               = [[Indie rock]], [[post-punk revival]], [[garage rock revival]]\n| occupation          = Musician, songwriter, actor, poet, writer, artist\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar, bass guitar, harmonica, melodica, piano, organ\n| label               = [[Parlophone]], [[EMI]]\n| years_active        = 1997\u2013present\n| associated_acts     = [[The Libertines]], [[Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres]], [[Babyshambles]], [[Peter Wolfe (musician)|Peter Wolfe]], [[Littl'ans]], [[The Streets]]\n|website              = {{URL|http://albionrooms.com/}}\n}} \n'''Peter Doherty''',<ref>Cortassa, Guia and Mattia Villa. [http://www.ondarock.it/popmuzik/peterdoherty.htm \"Libertines \u2013 Babyshambles \u2013 Peter Doherty: Storia di un libertino\"], OndaRock.</ref><ref>[https://www.alfemminile.com/stars/pete-doherty/pete-doherty-star2354.html \"Pete Doherty\"], Allfemminile.</ref><ref>Golby, J. [https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/vbj8pb/five-questions-about-pete-doherty-aggressively-eating-a-breakfast], Vice</ref> known professionally as '''Pete Doherty''',{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}  is an English musician, songwriter, actor, poet, writer, and artist.<ref>[http://www.sputnikmusic.com/bands/Peter-Doherty/8496/ Peter Doherty]. sputnikmusic.com</ref> He is best known for being co-frontman of [[The Libertines]], which he formed with [[Carl Bar\u00e2t]] in 1997. His other musical projects are [[indie rock|indie]] band [[Babyshambles]] and [[Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres]].\n\n==Early life==\nPete Doherty was born in [[Hexham]], Northumberland, to a military family. His father, Peter John Doherty, was a major in the [[Royal Signals]], while his mother, Jacqueline Michels, was a lance-corporal in [[Queen Alexandra's Royal Army Nursing Corps]]. His paternal grandfather was an Irish immigrant from [[Cheekpoint]] in [[County Waterford]]; his maternal grandfather was Jewish, the son of immigrants from France and Russia.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|title=Family detective: Pete Doherty|first=Nick|last=Barratt|date=24 November 2006|accessdate=27 September 2007|publisher=Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1435134/Family-detective-Pete-Doherty.html|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref name=\"ref1109\">{{cite news|last=Shennan|first=Paddy|title=I wanted to hit Pete when I found out about the drugs; Says Babyshambles stars Scouse mum Paddy Shennan reports on a Liverpool mother's love for her drug addict son who also happens to be one of Britain's biggest rock stars says Baby shambles star's Scouse mum|publisher=Liverpool Echo|date=18 September 2006|url=http://icliverpool.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100regionalnews/tm_objectid=17772329%26method=full%26siteid=50061%26headline=i-wanted-to-hit-pete-when-i-found-out-about-the-drugs---says-babyshambles-star-s-scouse-mum-name_page.html|accessdate=1 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"scotsman\">{{cite news|title=Lament for a lost boy|first=Jackie|last=McGlone|date=3 September 2006|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=The Scotsman|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/lament-for-a-lost-boy-1-1414959}}</ref> He was raised Catholic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,,1381347,00.html|title=The Guardian profile: Pete Doherty|first=Patrick|last=Barkham|date=31 December 2004|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 May 2011|location=London}}</ref> He grew up at a number of army garrisons across Britain and Europe, with his sisters Amy Jo and Emily.<ref name=\"ref1109\"/> Doherty was the second of the three children.<ref name=\"ref1109\"/> It was while living in [[Dorset]], aged 11, that Doherty began playing guitar, originally in an attempt to impress a female classmate, Emily Baker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/tabloid-hell/39897|title=Pete Doherty reunited with childhood sweetheart \u2013 Tabloid Hell|publisher=Nme.com|accessdate=2013-02-05}}</ref> He achieved 11 [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSEs]],<ref name=\"The BBC\">{{cite news|title=What a Shambles!|first=Laura|last=Wetton|date=31 August 2005|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=BBC|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2005/08/31/blast05_what_a_shambles_feature.shtml}}</ref> 7 of which were A* grades, at [[Nicholas Chamberlaine School|Nicholas Chamberlaine Comprehensive School]] in [[Bedworth]], [[North Warwickshire]], and four passes at [[GCE Advanced Level|A-Level]], two at grade A.<ref name=\"Dorset Echo\">{{cite news|title=Wild man of pop 'a model student'|date=24 August 2005|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=Dorset Echo|url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/archive/2005/08/24/Dorset+Archive/5409337.Wild_man_of_pop__a_model_student_}}</ref> At the age of 16, he won a poetry competition and embarked on a tour of Russia organised by the [[British Council]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4690288.stm|title=Pete Doherty timeline|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=12 May 2011|date=7 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nAfter his A-levels, he moved to his grandmother's flat in London \u2013 where he said he felt 'destined' to be \u2013 and got a job filling graves in [[Willesden]] Cemetery, although most of his time was spent reading and writing while sitting on gravestones.<ref name=\"University details\">{{cite news|title=Pete's Dragons|first=Kathy|last=Brewis|date=14 May 2006|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2099-2173961.html|location=London, UK}}</ref> In a clip later made famous by YouTube, an 18-year-old Doherty can be seen in an interview with MTV, on the day of the release of [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]' [[Be Here Now (album)|''Be Here Now'']] album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22318-be-here-now/|title=Oasis Be Here Now Album Review|work=Pitchfork|first=Laura|last=Snapes|date=8 October 2016|accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref> He attended [[Queen Mary, University of London|Queen Mary]], a college of the [[University of London]], to study English literature, but left the course after his first year.<ref name=\"University details\"/> After leaving university, he moved into a London flat with friend and fellow musician [[Carl Bar\u00e2t]], who had been a classmate of Doherty's older sister at [[Brunel University]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===The Libertines===\n{{Main|The Libertines}}\nDoherty and Bar\u00e2t formed a band called the Libertines in the late 1990s, although it was not until 2002, with the release of their debut album ''[[Up the Bracket]]'', that they began to achieve widespread mainstream success.\n\nThe group achieved critical and commercial success and gained a dedicated cult following, with Doherty, in particular, being praised by fans and critics alike as one of the most promising songwriters to emerge on the British music scene for some time. However, Doherty's increasing drug problems led to his estrangement from the band. In 2003, he was jailed for burgling Bar\u00e2t's flat.<ref name=\"BurglingCarl\">{{cite news|title=Musician admits burgling bandmate's flat|date=12 August 2003|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3142801.stm}}</ref><ref name=\"PrisonCarl\">{{cite news|title=Libertines singer sent to prison|date=8 September 2003|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3090862.stm}}</ref> The two initially fell out over this incident, but made amends whilst Doherty was in prison. He was originally sentenced to 6 months, but his sentence was cut to 2 months. Upon his release, Doherty immediately reunited with Bar\u00e2t and the rest of the band to play a gig in the Tap 'n' Tin pub in [[Chatham, Kent]]; known among Libertine fans as \"The Freedom Gig\".<ref name=\"RejoinLibsKent\">{{cite news|title=Libertines reunite at freedom gig|date=9 October 2003|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3178394.stm}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his rejoining of the band, Doherty sought treatment for his drug addiction. He attended the alternative detox centre [[Wat Tham Krabok]], a temple in Thailand, famous for its rehabilitation programme for [[Crack cocaine|crack]] and heroin users. He left after three days and returned to England.<ref name=\"Rehab Fiasco\">{{cite news|title=Annihilation beckons the dark star of rock|author=Smith, David|author2=Smith, Zoe|date=4 July 2004|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=The Observer|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,,1253753,00.html|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref name=\"Pete Leaves Rehab\">{{cite web|title=Pete Flees Rehab Again|date=14 June 2004|work=NME|url=http://www.nme.com/news/108813.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220023006/http://www.nme.com/news/108813.htm|archivedate=20 February 2006}}</ref> As a consequence of this, The Libertines cancelled appearances that they were due to make at the [[Isle of Wight Festival|Isle of Wight]] and [[Glastonbury Festival|Glastonbury]] festivals.<ref name=\"FestCancelled\">{{cite news|title=Libertines cancel festival dates|date=9 June 2004|accessdate=12 May 2007 |publisher=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3792065.stm}}</ref>\n\nHowever, while post-production work was taking place on the [[The Libertines (album)|second Libertines album]] in June 2004, Doherty was again asked to leave the band. The band cited Doherty's continuing drug addiction as the reason for his dismissal but emphasised their willingness to take him back once he had addressed his addiction. Although Bar\u00e2t had previously stated that The Libertines were merely on hiatus, pending Doherty's recovery, the group effectively disbanded with Doherty's departure at the end of 2004.<ref name=\"BoundTogether\"/> The remaining members became involved in other projects (see [[Yeti (band)|Yeti]] and [[Dirty Pretty Things (band)|Dirty Pretty Things]]). On 12 April 2007, Pete Doherty and Carl Bar\u00e2t played 13 songs together at the second of Doherty's \"An Evening with Pete Doherty\" gigs at the [[Hackney Empire]], London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-libertines/27681|title=The Libertines reunite at Hackney gig|accessdate=13 April 2007|date=12 April 2007|work=NME}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 The Libertines reformed for appearances at the [[Reading and Leeds Festivals]]. They performed on 27 August at Leeds Festival and on 28 August at Reading Festival.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2010/aug/28/libertines-leeds-festival-2010|title=The Libertines rekindle the good old days at Leeds festival 2010|first=Sam|last=Wolfson|date=28 August 2010|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 May 2011|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=120&title=the_libertines_at_reading_festival_2010_&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1|title=The Libertines at Reading Festival 2010 \u2013 Review|first=David|last=Moynihan|date=29 August 2010|work=NME|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref> The festival appearances were preluded by two gigs at the [[HMV Forum]] on 24 and 25 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/58078/The-Libertines-Make-Thrilling-Comeback-At-London-Gig|title=The Libertines Make Thrilling Comeback at London Gig |first=Jason|last=Gregory|date=25 August 2010|publisher=gigwise.com|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref>\nIn November 2014 the band signed a record deal with Virgin EMI Records and released their third album, Anthems for Doomed Youth, on 11 September 2015.\n\nThe Libertines played an arena tour across the UK in January 2016, followed by a European tour and then dates in South America.\n\n===Collaborations===\nPrior to the disbanding of The Libertines, Doherty collaborated with local poet [[Peter Wolfe (musician)|Wolfman]]. Together they recorded the single \"[[For Lovers]]\", which entered the top 10, charting at number 7,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2004-04-24/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120911192535/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2004-04-24/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 September 2012 |title=Archive Chart |date=24 April 2004 |publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=29 May 2011 }}</ref> in April 2004. Despite the success of the single, which was nominated for a prestigious [[Ivor Novello Awards|Ivor Novello Award]] for songwriting,<ref name=\"Ivor Novello Awards report\">{{cite news\n | title=Geldof to follow up Live Aid and 'turn the world'\n | date=27 May 2005\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n |work=The Guardian\n | url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/live8/story/0,,1500501,00.html\n| location=London\n| first=Owen\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref> Doherty and Wolfman received relatively little money, having already sold the publishing rights for a small sum in a pub.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone profile\">{{cite news\n | title=Over the Edge with Pete Doherty\n | first=Mark\n | last=Binelli\n | date=24 March 2006\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n |work=Rolling Stone\n | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/9519813/over_the_edge_with_pete_doherty\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331102356/http://rollingstone.com/news/story/9519813/over_the_edge_with_pete_doherty\n | archivedate = 31 March 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nLater in 2004, Doherty provided guest vocals to the song \"Down to the Underground\" by the British group [[Client (band)|Client]]. The song was released in June 2004 as a B-side to the group's single \"[[In It for the Money (song)|In It for the Money]]\"<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Pete finds new client!\n | date=29 April 2004\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n |work=NME\n | url=http://www.nme.com/news/client/16803\n}}</ref> and appears on their second album ''[[City (Client album)|City]]''.\n\nIn 2005 Doherty collaborated with the British rock band [[Littl'ans]] on the single \"[[Their Way (song)|Their Way]]\".<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Doherty records with The Littl'ans\n | date=19 September 2005\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n | publisher=contactmusic.com\n | url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/doherty%20records%20with%20the%20littlans\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Doherty was featured on the charity single \"[[Janie Jones (song)|Janie Jones]]\", which was released to raise funds for [[Strummerville]]. A number of artists and bands, such as [[Dirty Pretty Things (band)|Dirty Pretty Things]], [[We Are Scientists]], [[The Kooks]] and [[The Holloways]], also featured on the track.\n\nIn August 2006 it was announced that Doherty was recording with [[The Streets]] frontman Mike Skinner on a new version of \"[[Prangin' Out]]\", from Skinner's album ''[[The Hardest Way to Make an Easy Living]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Pete Doherty and The Streets record drugs anthem\n | date=9 August 2006\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n |work=NME\n | url=http://www.nme.com/news/streets/23863\n}}</ref>\n[[File:Petedoherty.jpg|thumbnail|upright|Pete Doherty in 2005]]\n\nIn 2015 he recorded the theme tune to the [[Sky 1]] sitcom ''[[After Hours (UK TV series)|After Hours]]''.\n\n===Babyshambles===\n[[File:PeteDoherty-Madrid2008.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Saturday Night Fiber]] festival, Madrid 2008]]\n{{Main|Babyshambles}}\nDoherty founded Babyshambles towards the end of his time with The Libertines. The group has released three studio albums: ''[[Down in Albion]]'', in November 2005, ''[[Shotter's Nation]]'', in October 2007, and [[Sequel to the Prequel|Sequel To The Prequel]], in September 2013. The band's touring schedule and releases have occasionally been disrupted by Doherty's ongoing legal problems. The line-up of the band has changed several times: drummer [[Gemma Clarke]] left the band due to Doherty's drug problems and was replaced by [[Adam Ficek]], and guitarist and co-songwriter [[Patrick Walden]] has also left the band and was replaced by [[Mick Whitnall]]. In August 2006, Babyshambles signed up with major record label [[Parlophone]], on which they released ''[[The Blinding EP]]'' on 9 December 2006.<ref name=\"Parlophone\">{{cite news|title=Babyshambles speak about new deal\n | date=15 September 2006|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=[[NME]].com|url=http://www.nme.com/news/babyshambles/24344\n}}</ref> In January 2007, they signed a long term record deal with Parlophone.<ref name=\"Parlophone_deal\">{{cite news\n | title=Babyshambles sign 'long term' record deal|date=18 January 2007\n | accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=[[NME]].com|url=http://www.nme.com/news/babyshambles/25926\n}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007 Babyshambles played their first arena tour, taking in dates at the [[MEN Arena]] in Manchester, the [[Nottingham Arena]], [[Bournemouth International Centre]], London's [[Wembley Arena]] and Birmingham's [[National Indoor Arena]].<ref>{{cite news\n | title=The boys are hitting the road later this year...\n | date=16 March 2007\n | publisher=MTV.co.uk\n | url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/babyshambles/news/39978-babyshambles-announce-arena-tour\n | accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, the band's third album ''[[Sequel to the Prequel]]'' was released.\n\n===Solo work and guerrilla gigs===\nDoherty has been working on new acoustic material, similar to the wealth of his unreleased songs that can already be downloaded on the internet.<ref>NME Magazine \u2013 various issues</ref> On his own, and often with his band, he has continued [[The Libertines]]' tradition of performing on short notice [[guerrilla gig]]s in small venues.<ref name=\"Freedom Gig\">{{cite news\n | title=Pete Doherty plays 'freedom gig'\n | date=9 February 2006\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n |work=NME\n | url=http://www.nme.com/news/22178\n}}</ref> On New Year's Eve 2005, Doherty held a guerrilla gig in his [[North London]] flat where he showcased some of his solo works, many of which later leaked onto the internet.<ref name=\"BoundTogether\">{{cite book\n  | last = Thornton\n  | first = Anthony\n  |author2=Roger Sargent\n  | title = [[The Libertines Bound Together]]\n  | publisher = [[Hachette Book Group USA|Little, Brown Book Group]]\n  | year=  2006\n  | page = 263\n  | isbn = 0-316-73234-6}}</ref> 31 March and 1 April 2006 Doherty was performing two surprising solo gigs, his first in mainland Europe, at the NonStop Kino pornographic cinema and venue in [[Graz]], Austria, after he failed to turn up for an earlier arrangement in January. For this occasion he produced, at the suggestion of Bettina Aichbauer, friend of Doherty and owner of the NonStop Kino, a film with the title ''Spew It Out Your Soul'' which he showed on-screen during his performance.<ref name=\"Graz\">{{cite news\n |title      = \u00dcberraschungsgast in Graz\n |first      = Arthur\n |last       = Ein\u00f6der\n |date       = 1 April 2006\n |accessdate = 12 May 2007\n |publisher  = [[FM4]]\n |url        = http://fm4.orf.at/connected/212627\n}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\nOn 12 July 2008, Doherty played a solo gig at the [[Royal Albert Hall]]. It was his biggest solo show so far. The concert was originally scheduled for 26 April, but had to be rescheduled to a later date due to Doherty being sentenced to 14 weeks in prison for breaching probation on 8 April.<ref name=\"gdalb\">{{cite news| url=http://music.guardian.co.uk/live/story/0,,2290716,00.html |work=The Guardian  | location=London | title=Pete Doherty | first=Betty | last=Clarke | date=14 July 2008 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> The solo show did not get the best ratings but was all in all still well received. Jon Swaine of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' criticised that \"whole chunks of the set &hellip; passed by as listless noodling, with neither Doherty nor the audience appearing to know quite how to behave\" and that \u2013 without a full band \u2013 Doherty seemed out of place at such a big venue.<ref name=\"dt\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2008/07/14/bmpete114.xml | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=Pete Doherty's bloom lost in space | first=Jon | last=Swaine | date=14 July 2008 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> Betty Clarke of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described Doherty as \"focused\" and \"on good form\".<ref name=\"gdalb\"/> Friend and collaborator [[Peter Wolfe (musician)|Peter Wolfe]] had a guest appearance on stage when Doherty performed \"[[For Lovers]]\". Swaine stated Wolfe ruined the song with \"some especially tuneless backing vocals\".<ref name=\"dt\"/> The gig was forced to an abrupt end during the encore due to a stage invasion by the fans.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gigwise.com/news/44573/Pete-Doherty-Royal-Albert-Hall-Show-Hit-By-Stage-Invasion |title=Pete Doherty Royal Albert Hall Show Hit By Stage Invasion |first=Scott |last=Colothan |date=14 July 2008 |publisher=Gigwise |accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 January 2009, NME.COM announced that Doherty's solo album, entitled ''[[Grace/Wastelands]]'' would be released on 16 March, preceded by a single, \"[[Last of the English Roses]]\", on 9 March. The website also revealed the track listing of the album and credits. In 2009 Doherty was made an honorary patron of the [[University Philosophical Society]].\n\nWhilst performing a solo gig at the [[Grimsby]] Auditorium in March 2009, Doherty declared Grimsby a \"shit-hole\" midway through his set after being continuously pelted with coins and drinks by a harsh crowd.<ref>This is Grimsby. \"Beer Throwing was 'Disgusting'\". 15 April 2009. http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/beer-throwing-disgusting/story-11530778-detail/story.html{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Retrieved 7 June 2017.</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Doherty released a new single entitled \"Flags of the Old Regime\" through Walk Tall Recordings. All proceeds of single went to The [[Amy Winehouse Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wb0qz_tGGrs |title=Peter Doherty \u2013 Flags of the Old Regime [official video] |publisher=YouTube |date=2015-02-19 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Peter was joined on his 'Eudaimonia' tour by Drew McConnell (bass), Miki Beavis (violin), Katia de Vidas (keyboard), Stephany Kaberian (accordion) and Rafa (drums).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-gig-channel.com/#!Peter-Doherty-Eudaimonia-Tour-Is-A-Celebration-Of-A-New-Life/c112t/573f49030cf28f6d2bcebc97|title=The Gig Channel|website=The Gig Channel|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> He was also joined by [[Jack Jones (musician and poet)|Jack Jones]] of [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]] on guitar, who was support on the tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/features/107143/pete-doherty-2016-tour-diary-by-trampolene-jack-jones-libertines-poet|title=On the road with Peter Doherty \u2013 a tour diary by Trampolene {{!}} Gigwise|last=Trendell|first=Andrew|website=gigwise.com|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> He shared new track \u2018The Whole World Is Our Playground' on 4 May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neverenoughnotes.co.uk/2016/05/pete-doherty-announces-band-members-and-support-for-eudaimonia-tour-dates |last1=Stott|first1=Alex|title=Pete Doherty announces band members and support for Eudaimonia tour dates|accessdate=4 May 2016|publisher=Never Enough Notes}}</ref>\n\nIn early December 2016, Doherty released the album ''Hamburg Demonstrations'', which had been recorded in the city over a six month period, using mostly session musicians.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/12/album-review-peter-doherty-hamburg-demonstrations/|title=Album Review: Peter Doherty \u2013 Hamburg Demonstrations|date=2016-12-05|newspaper=Consequence of Sound|access-date=2017-01-17|language=en-US}}</ref> It was produced by [[Johann Scheerer]] and received favourable reviews.<ref>{{Citation|title=Hamburg Demonstrations by Peter Doherty|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/hamburg-demonstrations/peter-doherty|accessdate=2017-01-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Peter Doherty & the Puta Madres ===\n{{Main|Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres}}\nIn November 2016 [[Jack Jones (musician and poet)|Jack Jones]] was announced as lead guitarist in Doherty's new band The Puta Madres, joining Drew McConnell (bass), Miki Beavis (violin), Katia de Vidas (keyboard) and Rafa (drums), who had previously been his touring band. Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres played a gig in Argentina, followed by a week of shows in France including two nights for the reopening of the [[Bataclan (theatre)|Bataclan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/bataclan-anniversary-peter-doherty-carl-barat-libertines-review-sting-paris-attacks-a7422046.html|title=Peter Doherty at the Bataclan - review|date=2016-11-17|newspaper=The Independent|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-20}}</ref> They played [[The Forum, London|Kentish Town Forum]] in London and Manchester Albert Hall in December 2016 and several dates across Europe in February and March 2017.\n\nFollowing European and South American tours and festival appearances, the band recorded their debut album in France during the summer of 2018. The band played a short tour of the UK in February 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/peter-doherty-the-puta-madres-announce-debut-album-and-share-new-single-2439348|title=Peter Doherty & The Puta Madres announce debut album and share new single|last=Reilly|first=Nick|date=2019-01-28|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\nThe self-titled album was released on 26 April 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/peter-doherty-puta-madres-album-review-jack-jones-carl-barat-tour-dates-a8885751.html|title=Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres sound more befuddled than bohemian \u2013 review|date=2019-04-25|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref> and after instore signings the band set off on a UK and European tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fredperry.com/subculture/article-peter-doherty-the-puta-madres?+The+Puta+Madres+Blog&+The+Puta+Madres+Blog|title=Peter Doherty & The Puta Madres Announce eponymous debut album & tour|website=www.fredperry.com|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n===Painting and writing===\nIn June 2006, Doherty announced that he had signed a deal with Orion Books to publish his journals, in which he had recorded poetry, drawings, and photos over the course of his career.<ref name=\"Book deal\">{{cite news\n | title=Pete Doherty Journals to Be Published\n | date=22 June 2006\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n | publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]\n | url=http://www.spin.com/features/news/2006/06/060622_petedoherty/\n}}</ref> Most of Doherty's journals are freely available on the internet.<ref name=\"AlbionArks\">{{cite web\n |title       = Books of Albion\n |url         = http://www.albionarks.com/books\n |publisher   = albionarks.com\n |accessdate  = 25 October 2006\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061010091621/http://www.albionarks.com/books/\n |archivedate = 10 October 2006\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> The book, titled ''The Books of Albion: The Collected Writings of Peter Doherty'', was released on 21 June 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.orionbooks.co.uk/HB-40521/Journals.htm |title=The Books of Albion-The Collected Writings of Peter Doherty by Peter Doherty \u2013 9780752885919- Orion Books |accessdate=17 June 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070318071643/http://www.orionbooks.co.uk/HB-40521/Journals.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 18 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 May 2007, Doherty exhibited his paintings for the first time. The art exhibition took place at London's Bankrobber Gallery and was on show for one month. The collection featured 14 paintings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/05/16/pete_doherty_s_bloodworks_exhibition_ope |title=Pete Doherty's Bloodworks Exhibition Opens in London |date=16 May 2007 |publisher=Starpulse Entertainment News Blog |accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nAn exhibition of Doherty's paintings titled, \"Art of the Albion\", took place at the Galerie Chappe in Paris from 25 April to 25 May 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/42662/pete-doherty-launches-new-blood-exhibition-in-paris |title=Pete Doherty Launches New Blood Exhibition in Paris |first=Jason |last=Gregory |date=25 April 2008 |publisher=Gigwise |accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref> The exhibit caused controversy due to artworks made with Doherty's own blood. According to newspapers, anti-drug campaigners were enraged and accused Doherty of glamorising illegal substance abuse.<ref name=\"indiatimes\">{{cite news| url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Personal_Finance/Art_/Art_exhibition_by_Doherty_causes_controversy/rssarticleshow/2987458.cms |work=The Times of India  | title=Art exhibition by Doherty causes controversy |date=27 April 2008 |accessdate=9 May 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110230034/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Personal_Finance/Art_/Art_exhibition_by_Doherty_causes_controversy/rssarticleshow/2987458.cms | archivedate=10 January 2009}}</ref> Art experts were similarly unimpressed. David West, the owner of London's [[Decima gallery]], for example, slammed his work: \"It's not got any artistic merit. He's using his blood to make them interesting, but when you look at them they're what any four-year-old can do.\"<ref name=\"indiatimes\"/>\n\n=== Muse ===\nIn February 2015, artist [[Nick Reynolds (sculptor)|Nick Reynolds]] exhibited a life-size sculpture of a crucified Doherty at the [[St Marylebone Parish Church|St Marylebone parish church]] in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/feb/18/lifesize-pete-doherty-crucifixion-sculpture-unveiled-in-church-missing-tom-fund|title=Lifesize Pete Doherty crucifixion sculpture to be unveiled in church|last=music|first=Guardian|date=2015-02-18|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 September 2015, [[conceptual artist]] [[Andy Picci]] staged an art project in which he pranked a group of paparazzi, dressed up as Doherty and duly found himself splashed over the cover of the [[Le Parisien|Parisien]] newspaper, which had taken him for the real thing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.vogue.fr/vogue-hommes/fashion/story/andy-picci-artist-identity-social-media-age-era-pete-doherty-who-are-you-richard-prince-cindy-sherman-nabilla-benattia-comme-des-garcons/3895|title=Artist Andy Picci is questioning identity in the age of social media|last=Larvin|first=Hugo Compain, translated by Hannah|work=Vogue English|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/the-rakes-progress-last-week-in-gossip-107/|title=The Rake\u2019s progress: last week in gossip {{!}} Apollo Magazine|date=2018-06-07|work=Apollo Magazine|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Modelling===\nFollowing in the footsteps of model and ex-fianc\u00e9e [[Kate Moss]], Doherty became the face of [[Roberto Cavalli]]'s Fall 2007/2008 fashion advertising campaign. The photos gained praise for depicting a much cleaner and more handsome Doherty. The '50s-style photographs have been compared to images of [[Marlon Brando]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1555571/Doherty-becomes-fashion-contender-for-Moss.html|title=Doherty becomes fashion contender for Moss|last=Alexander|first=Hilary|date=27 June 2007|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=29 June 2007|location=London|authorlink=Hilary Alexander}}</ref>\n\n===Acting===\nOn 9 December 2010 it was reported that Doherty would be taking the lead role opposite [[Charlotte Gainsbourg]] in ''[[Confession of a Child of the Century]]'', [[Sylvie Verheyde]]'s film adaption of [[Alfred de Musset]]'s autobiographical novel ''La Confession d'un Enfant du Si\u00e8cle''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/film-role-for-peter-doherty-2154999.html | location=London |work=The Independent  | first=Rob | last=Sharp | title=Film role for Peter Doherty | date=9 December 2010}}</ref> The film was screened at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>Catherine Shoard, [https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/may/21/confessions-child-century-review Cannes 2012: Confession of a Child of the Century] at guardian.co.uk</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nIn interviews, Doherty has listed his favourite books as [[George Orwell]]'s ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four|1984]]'', ''[[Brighton Rock (novel)|Brighton Rock]]'' by [[Graham Greene]], ''[[Our Lady of the Flowers]]'' by [[Jean Genet]], ''[[Les Fleurs du mal|Flowers of Evil]]'' by [[Charles Baudelaire]] and the complete works of [[Oscar Wilde]].<ref name=\"q+a2003\">{{cite web\n| url = http://libertines.twinkling-star.com/libertinesde.html\n| title = libertines.de Q&A with Pete\n| accessdate =27 March 2007\n|date=April 2003\n| publisher = libertines.de, archived by libertines.twinkling-star.com\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305100455/http://libertines.twinkling-star.com/libertinesde.html\n| archivedate = 5 March 2008\n}}</ref> He has also mentioned [[Emily Dickinson]] and [[Tony Hancock]] as influences; Doherty and his father were once members of the Tony Hancock Appreciation Society. Doherty mentions Hancock, and makes an allusion to his famous phrase 'Stone me!', in an early song entitled \"You're My Waterloo\". However, numerous literary and musical allusions occur throughout Doherty's ongoing ''Books of Albion''. He places particular importance on the [[Romantic poetry|Romantic poets]] and on existential philosophers such as [[Albert Camus]] and [[Miguel de Unamuno]]. Doherty has also alluded to work by the [[Marquis de Sade]] and [[Thomas de Quincey]]. On the Babyshambles album ''[[Down in Albion]]'', there is a track entitled \"\u00c0 rebours\", which is significantly influenced by [[\u00c0 rebours|the novel of the same name]] by [[Joris-Karl Huysmans]].<ref name=\"MotherInterview\">{{cite news|title=For Pete's sake|first=Janice|last=Turner|accessdate=12 May 2007|date=19 August 2006|work=[[The Times|Times]] Saturday Magazine|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,27869-2319045.html|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Emily Dickinson? She's hardcore'|date=3 October 2006|work=The Guardian|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,,1886267,00.html|author=Barton, Laura|author2=Petridis, Alex|accessdate=26 March 2007|location=London}}</ref>\n\nDoherty has supported up-and-coming British bands, such as indie bands [[The Paddingtons]]<ref name=\"Rolling Stone profile\"/> and [[The View (band)|The View]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/entertainment-catch-all/2007/10/13/the-razz-doherty-view-on-rockers-86908-19944827|title=Pete Doherty Tells How He Gave The View Their Break|accessdate=2 November 2007|last=Lyons|first=Beverley|authorlink=Beverley Lyons|author2=Sutherland, Laura|date=13 October 2007|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230015151/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/entertainment-catch-all/2007/10/13/the-razz-doherty-view-on-rockers-86908-19944827|archivedate=30 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nDoherty is also known to be a devoted follower of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] football club. As a youth (1995\u201396) he wrote a fanzine dedicated to the club, entitled \"All Quiet on the [[Western Avenue (London)|Western Avenue]]\".<ref name=\"MotherInterview\"/>\n\nA frequent lyrical theme for Doherty is [[Albion]], the ancient name for Great Britain. Doherty also uses 'Albion' as the name of a ship sailing to a utopia called [[Arcadia (utopia)|Arcadia]], a place without rules or authority. Doherty and Bar\u00e2t shared a flat in London, at 112a Teesdale Street, [[Bethnal Green]], affectionately known as 'The Albion Rooms', despite being rather run down. Doherty named his diaries, in which he writes poems and other thoughts, the ''[[Books of Albion]]''.<ref name=\"The Books of Albion\">{{cite news\n | title=The Books of Albion\n | date=26 June 2006\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n | publisher=Babyshambles.net\n | url=http://www.babyshambles.net/books.asp\n}}</ref>\n\n==Drug abuse and legal problems==\nDoherty has been repeatedly arrested for drug offences and offences arising from drug use, such as [[driving under the influence]], car theft,<ref name=\"spin2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.spin.com/articles/grand-theft-auto-babyshambles|title=Grand Theft Auto: Babyshambles|work=Spin|accessdate=7 May 2008|date=28 February 2006}}</ref> and driving with a suspended [[driving licence|licence]].<ref name=\"reutersuk1\">{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUKL2015065120070820|title=Pete Doherty arrested after V Festival|agency=Reuters UK|accessdate=7 May 2008|date=20 August 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"spin1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.spin.com/articles/pete-doherty-arrested-again|title=Pete Doherty Arrested, Again|work=Spin|accessdate=7 May 2008|date=7 May 2007}}</ref> He has pleaded guilty to possession of [[crack cocaine]], heroin, cannabis and [[ketamine]].<ref name=\"reutersuk1\"/> His addictions have resulted in jail time and multiple trips to rehabilitation facilities.<ref name=\"spin1\"/> Drugs had been so important at some points in his life that in his younger days Doherty worked as a drug dealer to pay for his drug habit, as he admitted to author Peter Welsh in his biography.<ref>{{cite book|last=Welsh|first=Peter|title=Kids in the Riot: High and Low with the Libertines|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|year=2005|isbn=978-1-84449-716-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/kidsinriothighlo0000wels}}</ref> Doherty stated that he had been a [[rent boy]], and that during that time he robbed one of his male clients.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/story/doherty-i-was-a-gay-rent-boy-and-drug-dealer|title=Pete Doherty: I was a gay rent boy and drug dealer|date=17 April 2005|publisher=contactmusic.com|accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, while Doherty's first band [[The Libertines]] was performing in Japan without him, he broke into Carl Bar\u00e2t's flat and stole various items, including an old guitar and a laptop computer. On 7 September Doherty was sentenced by Judge Roger Davies to six months in prison; the sentence was eventually shortened to two months on appeal with the judge commenting, \"We feel that a custodial sentence was justified in this case but sufficient credit was not given for his timely plea of guilty which it should have been. We have reduced his sentence to two months which will allow for his almost immediate release.\" Doherty was released from jail on 8 October 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3142801.stm|publisher=BBC News|title=Musician admits burgling bandmate's flat|date=12 August 2003|accessdate=19 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/libertines/15033|work=NME|title=Pete Libertine Goes to Jail|date=8 September 2003|accessdate=28 November 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3149610.stm|publisher=BBC News|title=Libertines singer's sentence cut|date=29 September 2003|accessdate=6 January 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xfm.co.uk/Article.asp?b=news&id=13717|publisher=[[xfm]]|title=Libertine Reunited with Liberated Pete|date=9 October 2003|accessdate=19 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 February 2005, Doherty was arrested after an altercation with documentary filmmaker [[Max Carlish]], who was making a [[rockumentary]] about the singer and sold photos of a heroin-smoking Doherty to the tabloids. Doherty and his friend Alan Wass had been charged with robbery and blackmail. On 7 February, he was released on bail after his record company [[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]] put up \u00a3150,000 in bonds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xfm.co.uk/Article.asp?b=news&id=65780|title=Pete Doherty Gets Conditional Bail|date=4 February 2005|publisher=xfm|accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antimusic.com/news/05/feb/item18.shtml|title=Pete Doherty Released From Jail|date=8 February 2005|publisher=antimusic.com|accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref> All charges against him were later dropped by the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] due to a lack of evidence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/apr/12/arts.artsnews|work=The Guardian|location=London|title=Pete Doherty's charges dropped|first=Owen|last=Bowcott|date=12 April 2005|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2007, a photo was published in several newspapers of Doherty allegedly forcing his pet cat to inhale from a crack pipe.<ref name=\"sfgate1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/dailydish/detail?blogid=7&entry_id=20100|work=San Francisco Chronicle|title=Doherty 'Forced Cat to Smoke Crack'|date=7 September 2007|accessdate=11 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpost1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2007/09/07/pete-doherty-photographed_1_n_63409.html|publisher=The Huffington Post|title=Pete Doherty Photographed Allegedly Giving His Kitten Crack|date=9 September 2007|accessdate=11 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 2008, Doherty was jailed for 14 weeks by a court for breaching a probation order after a string of brushes with the law for drugs and driving offences. On 18 April 2008, he was moved to a private area of [[Wormwood Scrubs (HM Prison)|Wormwood Scrubs prison]] after learning that fellow inmates were planning to attack him, therefore making it safer for the singer. On 6 May 2008, he was released after his sentence was cut in half and a further 18 days were remitted due to a government plan to reduce overcrowding. He also had another two days off for being in police custody (after serving just over 4 weeks of a 14-week sentence). He described prison life as \"a lot of gangsters and [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]]\" and showed a certificate confirming he had passed a [[drugs test]] while inside.<ref name=\"afp111\">{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Sky-News-Archive/Article/20080641315053|title=Rocker Pete Doherty Freed From Prison|accessdate=9 May 2011|date=6 May 2008|publisher=Sky News}}</ref>\n\nDoherty made another attempt to fight his drug addiction in September 2007, when he underwent rehab for six weeks at [[Clouds House]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/7023339.stm|title=Doherty gets chance to kick drugs|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 September 2008|date=2 October 2007}}</ref> However, he relapsed in November 2007 following his appearance at the [[MTV Europe Music Awards 2007]] in Munich.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7082897.stm|title=Doherty owns up to drug relapse|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 September 2008|date=7 November 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, Doherty was arrested in [[Gloucester]] and charged with driving dangerously, while drunk, and in possession of heroin. He was released on a \u00a350,000 bail<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisgloucestershire.co.uk/gloucestershireheadlines/Doherty-released-50K-bail/article-1073630-detail/article.html|title=Doherty released on \u00a350K bail|first=Jenni|last=Silver|publisher=thisisgloucestershire.co.uk|accessdate=21 December 2009|date=13 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213153319/http://www.thisisgloucestershire.co.uk/gloucestershireheadlines/Doherty-released-50K-bail/article-1073630-detail/article.html|archivedate=13 December 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and after 'guilty' pleas were entered, was asked to return to court on 21 December for sentencing. He was spared jail but was ordered to pay \u00a32,050 in fines, and was banned from driving for 18 months, despite the court hearing Doherty had 21 previous drug offences and six motoring offences. Following his release from court, he was escorted by officers to the nearest police station and re-arrested for possession of a controlled substance,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/crime/article6964514.ece|title=Pete Doherty rearrested after being convicted of driving and drug offences|first=Simon de|last=Bruxelles|work=The Times|accessdate=9 May 2011|date=22 December 2009|location=London}}</ref> later revealed to be heroin.<ref name=\"news.sky.com\">{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Showbiz-News/Singer-Pete-Doherty-Charged-With-Possession-Of-Heroin-Following-His-Arrest-After-A-Court-Appearance/Article/200912415506340|first=Neal|last=Walker|publisher=Sky News Online|title=Doherty Drug Charge After Court Appearance|accessdate=22 December 2009|date=22 December 2009}}</ref> The following day, 22 December, it emerged that Doherty could be charged with offences linked to a hit-and-run incident, which left a pedestrian in a critical condition. His manager, Andrew Boyd, appeared in court charged with a number of offences relating to the incident.<ref name=\"news.sky.com\"/> While Doherty was in Gloucester court on 21 December, heroin fell out of his coat pocket. He was arrested for possession and was convicted for this offence at the same court on 27 January 2010. He was fined \u00a3750 and ordered to pay \u00a385 court costs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/7083165/Pete-Doherty-fined-for-walking-into-court-with-heroin-in-pocket.html|title=Pete Doherty fined for walking into court with heroin in pocket|date=27 January 2010|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=9 May 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2010, Lowestoft magistrates fined Doherty \u00a3500 and banned him from driving for 12 months for allowing his [[Daimler AG|Daimler]] car to be used uninsured by his manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisiswiltshire.co.uk/news/headlines/5057410.marlborough_s_Pete_Doherty-banned_from_driving|title=Marlborough's Pete Doherty banned from driving|date=12 March 2010|publisher=thisiswiltshire.co.uk|accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref> On 19 March 2010, he was arrested on [[Misuse of Drugs Act 1971|suspicion of supplying controlled drugs]]. He was reported to be on bail until April 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/7496059/Pete-Doherty-arrested-over-drug-death-of-Robin-Whitehead.html|title=Pete Doherty arrested over drug death of Robyn Whitehead|date=22 March 2010|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=9 May 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010 Doherty was refused entry into the United States after spending 10 hours in detention in [[JFK Airport]], despite having a visa.<ref>{{cite web|last=Peck|first=Derek|title=New York Minute {{!}} Irina Lazareanu: Just a Kid from Canada|url=http://www.anothermag.com/current/view/268/Irina_Lazareanu_Just_a_Kid_from_Canada|publisher=AnOther|accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pete Doherty never made it out of the airport.|url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/archives/2010/06/pete_doherty_ne.html|publisher=Brooklyn Vegan|accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 October 2010, Doherty was summoned to court for cocaine possession. In March 2011 he pleaded guilty to possession, and was granted unconditional bail until sentencing on 20 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/pete-doherty/56009|title=Pete Doherty facing jail again after pleading guilty to cocaine possession|date=9 April 2011|work=NME}}</ref> On 20 May, Doherty was sentenced to 6 months in jail for possession of cocaine, following the inquiry into the death of Robin Whitehead.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singer Pete Doherty jailed for cocaine possession|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-13451440|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=20 May 2011|date=20 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Doherty was admitted to the [[Hope Rehab Centre]] in Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sean Michaels |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/nov/13/pete-doherty-returns-to-thai-rehab-centre |title=Pete Doherty returns to Thai rehab centre &#124; Music |publisher=The Guardian |date=2014-11-14 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref> He announced plans to start a foundation with the centre to help struggling addicts.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-libertines/81040 |title=NME News Pete Doherty 'wishes to help other addicts' as he spends last month in Thai rehab facility |publisher=Nme.Com |date=2014-11-12 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, it was announced that Doherty had successfully completed his rehab treatment. However, in August 2017 it was revealed that he had been found with heroin in his car while travelling through Italy. He was also found to be driving with an invalid licence. Doherty received a fine.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-libertines/82009 |title=NME News Pete Doherty leaves rehab after completing treatment in Thailand |publisher=Nme.Com |date=2015-01-03 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\nSince moving to Margate in 2017 Doherty has been arrested by Kent police on numerous occasions. January 2019 he was held for 48 hours and questioned. Charges of drug possession and several driving-related offences were later dropped.\n\nIn November 2019 Doherty was arrested in Paris, France on drugs possession charges.\n\n==Family and personal life==\nDoherty's mother, Jacqueline, is a nurse, who published a book about life with Doherty and his drug problems with the title ''Pete Doherty: My Prodigal Son''.<ref name=\"MotherInterview\"/> Doherty's father, Peter John Doherty, is a retired major in the British army.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=121&title=before_they_were_famous_amy_winehouse_pe&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1|title=Before They Were Famous|first=Luke|last=Lewis|accessdate=1 September 2008|date=1 September 2008|work=NME}}</ref>\n\nAfter numerous attempts to persuade him to make a serious attempt at rehabilitation, in early 2005 Doherty's father decided he was tired of broken promises and vowed not to see his son again until he was clean of drugs.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} The sensitivity surrounding the issue became apparent in the [[BBC Two]] ''[[Arena (UK TV series)|Arena]]'' documentary about Doherty, on 12 November 2006, which included footage of him talking about this aspect of his personal life. He was visibly upset and had to politely ask the interviewer at one point to stop filming. In October 2007, Doherty explained in an interview with the [[BBC Radio 4]] show ''Front Row'' that he had briefly reconciled with his father after three years when his father visited him in rehab, but were estranged again over drugs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7042330.stm|title=Doherty 'at drugs turning point'|accessdate=2 November 2007|date=12 October 2007|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nDoherty has had a tumultuous relationship with [[Kate Moss]], frequently covered by the press. They met in January 2005 at Moss' 31st birthday party and had an on-off relationship for several years. Moss had also taken to singing at some of Doherty's shows.<ref name=\"on stage with Moss\">{{cite news|title=Kate Moss and Pete Doherty Reignite Romance in Ireland|date=26 September 2006|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=Fox News|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,215858,00.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070504051102/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,215858,00.html|archive-date=4 May 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 11 April 2007, Doherty announced Moss as his fianc\u00e9e during the first of his solo gigs at the [[Hackney Empire]], London, at which Moss also performed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/opinion/main.jhtml?xml=/opinion/2007/04/15/do1509.xml|title=Kate and Pete, babies and shambles|accessdate=15 April 2007|last=McCartney|first=Jenny|date=15 April 2007|work=Sunday Telegraph|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1501119/story.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=10434394|title=Moss is now 'fiancee'|accessdate=15 April 2007|date=16 April 2007|work=The New Zealand Herald}}</ref> Doherty planned to marry Moss during the summer 2007.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=Pete Doherty cleans up act to marry Kate Moss|publisher=[[CTV Television Network|CTV]]|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070621/Pete_Doherty_070621/20070621?hub=Entertainment|date=21 June 2007|accessdate=23 June 2007}}</ref> Since July 2007, Moss and Doherty have broken up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a116966/doherty-speaks-about-moss-split.html|title=Doherty speaks about Moss split|first=Beth|last=Hilton|date=30 July 2008|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, Doherty was briefly engaged to fashion model [[Irina L\u0103z\u0103reanu]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20128263,00.html |title=Report: Pete Doherty Engaged to Model \u2013 Not Kate Moss |accessdate=2 November 2007 |last=Silverman |first=Stephen M. |date=3 October 2007 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref>\n\nDoherty has a son, Astile (born 2003),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/story/pete-doherty-quizzed-by-son-on-drug-use_3791336|title=Pete Doherty quizzed by son on drug use |publisher=contactmusic.com |accessdate=18 October 2014}}</ref> with singer [[Lisa Moorish]].<ref name=\"scotsman\"/><ref name=\"MotherInterview\"/>\nDoherty's second child, a daughter, was born in December 2011 to South African model Lindi Hingston.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pete Doherty: I'm A Dad Again|date=1 November 2012|work=Huffington Post|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/02/17/pete-doherty-father_n_1283762.html|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, ''Rolling Stone'' reporter Claire Hoffman asked [[Amy Winehouse]] about her relationship with Doherty. Winehouse replied: \"We're just good friends\", and added: \"I asked Pete to do a concept EP, and he made this face, he looked at me like I'd pooed on the floor. He wouldn't do it. We're just really close\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Up All Night With Amy Winehouse: Rolling Stone's 2008 Story|page=Page 3 of 3|date=10 July 2008|work=Rolling Stone|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/up-all-night-with-amy-winehouse-rolling-stones-2008-story-20110723?page=3|author=Hoffman, Claire|accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nDoherty is a [[socialist]], stating that \"I do have utopian fantasies. A lot of them are more - I wouldn't say spiritual, but they relate more to the imagination and the individual. But for me socialism is a way of trying to put far-fetched ideas into everyday use, trying to find a way to bridge the gap between that fantasy and reality, and reaching out across that gap to the people who can actually do something to make the change.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://socialistreview.org.uk/284/charming-man-interview-pete-doherty|title=This Charming Man: An Interview with Pete Doherty|year=2004}}</ref>\n\nDoherty is also a supporter of English football team [[Queens Park Rangers]].\n\n==Musical equipment==\nDoherty prefers vintage equipment. Many of his vintage guitars and amplifiers have been destroyed in various domestic incidents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/pete-doherty-on-gear-203176?cpn=RSS&source=MRNEWS |title=Pete Doherty on gear... |first=Chris |last=Vinnicombe |date=14 April 2009 |publisher=Musicradar.com |accessdate=30 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Guitars===\n*[[Epiphone Coronet]] \u2013 Doherty often used the rare one pick-up model (\u2018New York Coronet\u2019 made in 1957) in the early years of the Libertines, as well as in some later gigs. It is affectionately known as \u2018heavy horse\u2019 also Doherty\u2019s username in online band related forums. His father held the guitar \u2018hostage\u2019 during 8 years of Doherty\u2019s chaos and carnage, allowing it to be used in recent Puta Madres album recording sessions. \n*[[Gibson ES-330]] \u2013 One of Doherty's first known guitars. Used throughout the early Libertines gigs.\n*[[Epiphone Casino]] \u2013 Used with Babyshambles at recent concerts.\n*[[Rickenbacker 360]] \u2013 Used a lot in Babyshambles, live and in the studio.\n*[[Gibson ES-335]] \u2013 Used during the later years of the Libertines.\n*Epiphone Olympic \u2013 Another rare one pick-up Epiphone. Seen on the cover of the \"I Get Along\" single (The Libertines).\n\n===Amplifiers===\n*[[Vox AC30]]\n*[[Matchless Amplifiers|Matchless amplifier]]{{Which|date=August 2009}}\n*[[Marshall amplification|Marshall amplifier]]{{Which|date=August 2009}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|The Libertines discography|Babyshambles discography}}\n\n;Solo albums\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n!colspan=\"13\"| Peak chart positions\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=\"150\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<br /><small>([[List of music recording sales certifications|sales thresholds]])</small>\n|-\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[UK Albums Chart|UK]]</small><br /><ref name=\"UK charts\">{{cite web|url=https://acharts.co/album/42443|title=Pete Doherty|publisher=aCharts|accessdate=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[France|FRA]]</small><br /><ref name=aus>Australian ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]]) peaks:\n*Top 50 peaks: {{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Tricky|title=australian-charts.com > Tricky in Australian Charts|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=12 September 2016}}\n*Top 100 peaks to December 2010: {{cite book|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|title=Australia's Music Charts 1988\u20132010|year=2011|publisher=Moonlight Publishing|location=Mt. Martha, VIC, Australia}}\n*\"Aftermath\", \"Black Steel\", \"The Hell E.P.\", \"Christiansands\" and \"Makes Me Wanna Die\": {{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/11R0bwv.gif|title=Response from ARIA re: chart inquiry, received 12 September 2016|accessdate=12 September 2016|publisher=Imgur.com}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[ARIA Charts|AUS]]</small><br /><ref name=\"Pete Doherty\">{{cite web| url=https://acharts.co/album/42443|title=Pete Doherty|publisher=aCharts|accessdate=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Switzerland|SWI]]</small><br /><ref name=\"Pete Doherty\"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.7782&volume=61&issue=2&issue_dt=February%2013%201995&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=0t22h9dmaasqufav51q9mj5l21| title=''Second Coming'' Canadian position| publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]| accessdate=2009-02-11| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007022628/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.7782&volume=61&issue=2&issue_dt=February%2013%201995&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=0t22h9dmaasqufav51q9mj5l21| archive-date=7 October 2012| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Media Control Charts|GER]]<br /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/STONE+ROSES%2CTHE/?type=longplay |title=German album positions |publisher=musicline.de |accessdate=2010-02-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525103001/http://musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/STONE+ROSES,THE/?type=longplay |archive-date=25 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref></small>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Irish Albums Chart|IRL]]<br /><ref name=\"IRL\">{{cite web| url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=The+Stone+Roses |title=Irish chart positions |publisher=irish-charts.com |accessdate=2010-02-18}}</ref></small>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Oricon|AUT]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/artists/h/95351/| title=Search for: Stone Roses| publisher=oricon.co.jp| accessdate=2009-02-16}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Megacharts|NLD]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://dutchcharts.nl/search.asp?search=Stone+Roses&cat=a| title=Search for: The Stone Roses| publisher=DutchCharts.nl| accessdate=2007-08-22}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"|<small>[[Belgium|BEL]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web | url=https://charts.nz/search.asp?search=Stone+Roses&cat=a | title=New Zealand album positions | publisher = charts.nz |accessdate=11 February 2009 }}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Norway|NOR]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://norwegiancharts.com/search.asp?search=Stone+Roses&cat=a| title=Search for: The Stone Roses| publisher=NorwegianCharts.com| accessdate=2007-08-22}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Swedish Singles Chart|SWE]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/search.asp?search=Stone+Roses&cat=a| title=Search for: The Stone Roses| publisher=SwedishCharts.com| accessdate=2007-08-25}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[RPM (magazine)|CAN]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://hitparade.ch/search.asp?search=Stone+Roses&cat=a| title=Suche nach: The Stone Roses| publisher=HitParade.ch| accessdate=2007-08-22}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Billboard 200|US]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web| url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=the stone roses|chart=all}}  | title=The Stone Roses Artist Chart History: Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| accessdate=2007-07-26}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Grace/Wastelands]]'\n* Label: [[Silvertone Records (1980)|Silvertone]] <small>(#502)</small>\n* Released: 16 March 2009\n* Format: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Compact Cassette|cassette]], [[LP record|LP]], [[Minidisc|MD]]\n| align=\"center\"| 17\n| align=\"center\"| 7\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| align=\"center\"| 20\n| align=\"center\"| 28\n| align=\"center\"| 11\n| align=\"center\"| 83\n| align=\"center\"| 7\n| align=\"center\"| 38\n| align=\"center\"| 13\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Hamburg Demonstrations]]''\n* Label: Clouds Hill <small>(#24503)</small>\n* Released: 2 December 2016\n* Format: CD, cassette, LP, digital\n| align=\"center\"| 61\n| align=\"center\"| 96\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| 48\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| 67\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"|\n|-\n|2019\n|Peter Doherty & The Puta Madres\n|25\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| 36\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n;Singles\n* \"[[Last of the English Roses]]\" (9 March 2009) UK No. 67\n* \"[[Broken Love Song]]\" (3 August 2009)\n* \"Flags of the Old Regime\" (9 March 2015)\n* \"I Don't Love Anyone (But You're Not Just Anyone)\" (27 September 2016)\n\n;As featured artist\n\n* \"[[For Lovers]]\" ([[Peter Wolfe (musician)|Wolfman]] featuring Pete Doherty) (12 April 2004) UK No. 7\n* \"[[Their Way (song)|Their Way]]\" ([[Littl'ans]] featuring Pete Doherty) (17 October 2005) UK No. 22\n* \"[[Prangin' Out]]\" ([[The Streets]] featuring Pete Doherty) (25 September 2006) UK No. 25\n\n;Other appearances\n* ''Down to the Underground'' ([[Client (band)|Client]], featuring Pete Doherty). Taken from the ''[[City (Client album)|City]]'' album.\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Confession of a Child of the Century]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Amy (2015 film)|Amy]]'' (2015)\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|title=[[Books of Albion|The Books of Albion: The Collected Writings of Peter Doherty]]|date=2007|publisher= [[Orion Books]]|isbn= 0-7528-8591-X}}\n*{{cite book|date=2014|author=Doherty, Peter|title=From Albion to Shangri-La: Journals and Tour Diaries 2008 - 2013'|editor= [[Nina Antonia|Antonia, Nina]]|publisher= Thin Man Press|location= London|isbn= 978-0-9562473-9-1}}\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* ''2004'': Doherty was voted to be joint No. 1 in [[NME's Cool List|''NME''{{'}}s 2004 Cool List]], along with fellow Libertine Carl Bar\u00e2t. The following year he was placed at No. 6,<ref name=\"NMECoolList2005\">{{cite news|title=Who made it into the NME Cool List 2005?|date=22 November 2005|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=NME|url=http://www.nme.com/news/arctic-monkeys/21580}}</ref> and on 10 May 2006 was voted No. 2 in their poll depicting 50 of rock's greatest heroes.<ref name=\"50 Greatest Heroes\">{{cite news|title=Your biggest rock 'n' roll hero revealed|date=10 May 2006|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=NME|url=http://www.nme.com/news/nirvana/23019}}</ref>\n* ''2008'': On 28 February 2008, Doherty won the \"Hero of the Year\" award at the 2008 [[Shockwave NME Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/nme-awards/34780|title=Shockwaves NME Awards 2008: Pete Doherty named Hero of the Year|date=28 February 2008|work=NME|accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref>\n* ''2009'': On 25 February 2009, Doherty won the \"Best Solo Artist\" award at the 2009 Shockwave NME Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/pete-doherty/43035|title=Pete Doherty voted Best Solo Artist at Shockwaves NME Awards|date=25 February 2009|work=NME|accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|En-Pete_Doherty.ogg|2007-06-15}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{official website|http://albionrooms.com/}}\n* [http://lyricsmusic.name/pete-doherty-lyrics/ Pete Doherty lyrics]\n* [https://www.discogs.com/artist/219403-Pete-Doherty Pete Doherty on Discogs]\n\n{{The Libertines}}\n{{Babyshambles}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doherty, Pete}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queen Mary University of London]]\n[[Category:British socialists]]\n[[Category:British people convicted of burglary]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Northumberland]]\n[[Category:English guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English people convicted of drug offences]]\n[[Category:People of French-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English rock singers]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Parlophone artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Northumberland]]\n[[Category:NME Awards winners]]\n[[Category:People from Hexham]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:Rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:The Libertines members]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Babyshambles members]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the musician|other people with the same name}}\n{{short description|English musician, writer, actor, poet and artist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n<!--BEFORE ADDING TO THIS PAGE, PLEASE ENSURE YOU REFERENCE CORRECTLY. INLINE CITATIONS ARE IN USE. COPY AND PASTE FROM A PREVIOUS REFERENCE AND EDIT IT TO FIT YOUR SOURCE. INFORMATION SURROUNDING PETE DOHERTY IS OFTEN RUMOUR AND PLACING SOURCES IN THE ARTICLE WILL HELP MAINTAIN THE INTEGRITY OF WIKIPEDIA. YOUR ASSISTANCE IS APPRECIATED.-->\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Pete Doherty\n| image               = Peter.Doherty.jpg\n| caption             = Doherty in 2012\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Peter Doherty\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1979|03|12}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Trendell |first1=Andrew |title=Pete Doherty celebrates birthday by singing 'What A Waster' live with his dad {{!}} NME |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/pete-doherty-celebrates-birthday-singing-waster-live-dad-2015816 |website=NME Music News, Reviews, Videos, Galleries, Tickets and Blogs {{!}} NME.COM |accessdate=24 December 2019 |date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[Hexham]], Northumberland, England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         =\n| genre               = [[Indie rock]], [[post-punk revival]], [[garage rock revival]]\n| occupation          = Musician, songwriter, actor, poet, writer, artist\n| instrument          = Vocals, guitar, bass guitar, harmonica, melodica, piano, organ\n| label               = [[Parlophone]], [[EMI]]\n| years_active        = 1997\u2013present\n| associated_acts     = [[The Libertines]], [[Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres]], [[Babyshambles]], [[Peter Wolfe (musician)|Peter Wolfe]], [[Littl'ans]], [[The Streets]]\n|website              = {{URL|http://albionrooms.com/}}\n}} \n'''Peter Doherty'''<ref>Cortassa, Guia and Mattia Villa. [http://www.ondarock.it/popmuzik/peterdoherty.htm \"Libertines \u2013 Babyshambles \u2013 Peter Doherty: Storia di un libertino\"], OndaRock.</ref><ref>[https://www.alfemminile.com/stars/pete-doherty/pete-doherty-star2354.html \"Pete Doherty\"], Allfemminile.</ref><ref>Golby, J. [https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/vbj8pb/five-questions-about-pete-doherty-aggressively-eating-a-breakfast], Vice</ref>, known professionally as '''Pete Doherty''',{{cn|date=November 2019}}  is an English musician, songwriter, actor, poet, writer, and artist.<ref>[http://www.sputnikmusic.com/bands/Peter-Doherty/8496/ Peter Doherty]. sputnikmusic.com</ref> He is best known for being co-frontman of [[The Libertines]], which he formed with [[Carl Bar\u00e2t]] in 1997. His other musical projects are [[indie rock|indie]] band [[Babyshambles]] and [[Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres]].\n\n==Early life==\nPete Doherty was born in [[Hexham]], Northumberland, to a military family. His father, Peter John Doherty, was a major in the [[Royal Signals]], while his mother, Jacqueline Michels, was a lance-corporal in [[Queen Alexandra's Royal Army Nursing Corps]]. His paternal grandfather was an Irish immigrant from [[Cheekpoint]] in [[County Waterford]]; his maternal grandfather was Jewish, the son of immigrants from France and Russia.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|title=Family detective: Pete Doherty|first=Nick|last=Barratt|date=24 November 2006|accessdate=27 September 2007|publisher=Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1435134/Family-detective-Pete-Doherty.html|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref name=\"ref1109\">{{cite news|last=Shennan|first=Paddy|title=I wanted to hit Pete when I found out about the drugs; Says Babyshambles stars Scouse mum Paddy Shennan reports on a Liverpool mother's love for her drug addict son who also happens to be one of Britain's biggest rock stars says Baby shambles star's Scouse mum|publisher=Liverpool Echo|date=18 September 2006|url=http://icliverpool.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100regionalnews/tm_objectid=17772329%26method=full%26siteid=50061%26headline=i-wanted-to-hit-pete-when-i-found-out-about-the-drugs---says-babyshambles-star-s-scouse-mum-name_page.html|accessdate=1 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"scotsman\">{{cite news|title=Lament for a lost boy|first=Jackie|last=McGlone|date=3 September 2006|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=The Scotsman|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/lament-for-a-lost-boy-1-1414959}}</ref> He was raised Catholic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,,1381347,00.html|title=The Guardian profile: Pete Doherty|first=Patrick|last=Barkham|date=31 December 2004|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 May 2011|location=London}}</ref> He grew up at a number of army garrisons across Britain and Europe, with his sisters Amy Jo and Emily.<ref name=\"ref1109\"/> Doherty was the second of the three children.<ref name=\"ref1109\"/> It was while living in [[Dorset]], aged 11, that Doherty began playing guitar, originally in an attempt to impress a female classmate, Emily Baker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/tabloid-hell/39897|title=Pete Doherty reunited with childhood sweetheart \u2013 Tabloid Hell|publisher=Nme.com|accessdate=2013-02-05}}</ref> He achieved 11 [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSEs]],<ref name=\"The BBC\">{{cite news|title=What a Shambles!|first=Laura|last=Wetton|date=31 August 2005|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=BBC|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/nottingham/content/articles/2005/08/31/blast05_what_a_shambles_feature.shtml}}</ref> 7 of which were A* grades, at [[Nicholas Chamberlaine School|Nicholas Chamberlaine Comprehensive School]] in [[Bedworth]], [[North Warwickshire]], and four passes at [[GCE Advanced Level|A-Level]], two at grade A.<ref name=\"Dorset Echo\">{{cite news|title=Wild man of pop 'a model student'|date=24 August 2005|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=Dorset Echo|url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/archive/2005/08/24/Dorset+Archive/5409337.Wild_man_of_pop__a_model_student_}}</ref> At the age of 16, he won a poetry competition and embarked on a tour of Russia organised by the [[British Council]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4690288.stm|title=Pete Doherty timeline|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=12 May 2011|date=7 August 2007}}</ref>\n\nAfter his A-levels, he moved to his grandmother's flat in London \u2013 where he said he felt 'destined' to be \u2013 and got a job filling graves in [[Willesden]] Cemetery, although most of his time was spent reading and writing while sitting on gravestones.<ref name=\"University details\">{{cite news|title=Pete's Dragons|first=Kathy|last=Brewis|date=14 May 2006|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2099-2173961.html|location=London, UK}}</ref> In a clip later made famous by YouTube, an 18-year-old Doherty can be seen in an interview with MTV, on the day of the release of [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]' [[Be Here Now (album)|''Be Here Now'']] album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22318-be-here-now/|title=Oasis Be Here Now Album Review|work=Pitchfork|first=Laura|last=Snapes|date=8 October 2016|accessdate=12 March 2017}}</ref> He attended [[Queen Mary, University of London|Queen Mary]], a college of the [[University of London]], to study English literature, but left the course after his first year.<ref name=\"University details\"/> After leaving university, he moved into a London flat with friend and fellow musician [[Carl Bar\u00e2t]], who had been a classmate of Doherty's older sister at [[Brunel University]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===The Libertines===\n{{Main|The Libertines}}\nDoherty and Bar\u00e2t formed a band called the Libertines in the late 1990s, although it was not until 2002, with the release of their debut album ''[[Up the Bracket]]'', that they began to achieve widespread mainstream success.\n\nThe group achieved critical and commercial success and gained a dedicated cult following, with Doherty, in particular, being praised by fans and critics alike as one of the most promising songwriters to emerge on the British music scene for some time. However, Doherty's increasing drug problems led to his estrangement from the band. In 2003, he was jailed for burgling Bar\u00e2t's flat.<ref name=\"BurglingCarl\">{{cite news|title=Musician admits burgling bandmate's flat|date=12 August 2003|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3142801.stm}}</ref><ref name=\"PrisonCarl\">{{cite news|title=Libertines singer sent to prison|date=8 September 2003|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3090862.stm}}</ref> The two initially fell out over this incident, but made amends whilst Doherty was in prison. He was originally sentenced to 6 months, but his sentence was cut to 2 months. Upon his release, Doherty immediately reunited with Bar\u00e2t and the rest of the band to play a gig in the Tap 'n' Tin pub in [[Chatham, Kent]]; known among Libertine fans as \"The Freedom Gig\".<ref name=\"RejoinLibsKent\">{{cite news|title=Libertines reunite at freedom gig|date=9 October 2003|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3178394.stm}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his rejoining of the band, Doherty sought treatment for his drug addiction. He attended the alternative detox centre [[Wat Tham Krabok]], a temple in Thailand, famous for its rehabilitation programme for [[Crack cocaine|crack]] and heroin users. He left after three days and returned to England.<ref name=\"Rehab Fiasco\">{{cite news|title=Annihilation beckons the dark star of rock|author=Smith, David|author2=Smith, Zoe|date=4 July 2004|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=The Observer|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,,1253753,00.html|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref name=\"Pete Leaves Rehab\">{{cite web|title=Pete Flees Rehab Again|date=14 June 2004|work=NME|url=http://www.nme.com/news/108813.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060220023006/http://www.nme.com/news/108813.htm|archivedate=20 February 2006}}</ref> As a consequence of this, The Libertines cancelled appearances that they were due to make at the [[Isle of Wight Festival|Isle of Wight]] and [[Glastonbury Festival|Glastonbury]] festivals.<ref name=\"FestCancelled\">{{cite news|title=Libertines cancel festival dates|date=9 June 2004|accessdate=12 May 2007 |publisher=BBC News|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3792065.stm}}</ref>\n\nHowever, while post-production work was taking place on the [[The Libertines (album)|second Libertines album]] in June 2004, Doherty was again asked to leave the band. The band cited Doherty's continuing drug addiction as the reason for his dismissal but emphasised their willingness to take him back once he had addressed his addiction. Although Bar\u00e2t had previously stated that The Libertines were merely on hiatus, pending Doherty's recovery, the group effectively disbanded with Doherty's departure at the end of 2004.<ref name=\"BoundTogether\"/> The remaining members became involved in other projects (see [[Yeti (band)|Yeti]] and [[Dirty Pretty Things (band)|Dirty Pretty Things]]). On 12 April 2007, Pete Doherty and Carl Bar\u00e2t played 13 songs together at the second of Doherty's \"An Evening with Pete Doherty\" gigs at the [[Hackney Empire]], London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-libertines/27681|title=The Libertines reunite at Hackney gig|accessdate=13 April 2007|date=12 April 2007|work=NME}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 The Libertines reformed for appearances at the [[Reading and Leeds Festivals]]. They performed on 27 August at Leeds Festival and on 28 August at Reading Festival.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2010/aug/28/libertines-leeds-festival-2010|title=The Libertines rekindle the good old days at Leeds festival 2010|first=Sam|last=Wolfson|date=28 August 2010|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 May 2011|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=120&title=the_libertines_at_reading_festival_2010_&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1|title=The Libertines at Reading Festival 2010 \u2013 Review|first=David|last=Moynihan|date=29 August 2010|work=NME|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref> The festival appearances were preluded by two gigs at the [[HMV Forum]] on 24 and 25 August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/58078/The-Libertines-Make-Thrilling-Comeback-At-London-Gig|title=The Libertines Make Thrilling Comeback at London Gig |first=Jason|last=Gregory|date=25 August 2010|publisher=gigwise.com|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref>\nIn November 2014 the band signed a record deal with Virgin EMI Records and released their third album, Anthems for Doomed Youth, on 11 September 2015.\n\nThe Libertines played an arena tour across the UK in January 2016, followed by a European tour and then dates in South America.\n\n===Collaborations===\nPrior to the disbanding of The Libertines, Doherty collaborated with local poet [[Peter Wolfe (musician)|Wolfman]]. Together they recorded the single \"[[For Lovers]]\", which entered the top 10, charting at number 7,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2004-04-24/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120911192535/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2004-04-24/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 September 2012 |title=Archive Chart |date=24 April 2004 |publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=29 May 2011 }}</ref> in April 2004. Despite the success of the single, which was nominated for a prestigious [[Ivor Novello Awards|Ivor Novello Award]] for songwriting,<ref name=\"Ivor Novello Awards report\">{{cite news\n | title=Geldof to follow up Live Aid and 'turn the world'\n | date=27 May 2005\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n |work=The Guardian\n | url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/live8/story/0,,1500501,00.html\n| location=London\n| first=Owen\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref> Doherty and Wolfman received relatively little money, having already sold the publishing rights for a small sum in a pub.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone profile\">{{cite news\n | title=Over the Edge with Pete Doherty\n | first=Mark\n | last=Binelli\n | date=24 March 2006\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n |work=Rolling Stone\n | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/9519813/over_the_edge_with_pete_doherty\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331102356/http://rollingstone.com/news/story/9519813/over_the_edge_with_pete_doherty\n | archivedate = 31 March 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nLater in 2004, Doherty provided guest vocals to the song \"Down to the Underground\" by the British group [[Client (band)|Client]]. The song was released in June 2004 as a B-side to the group's single \"[[In It for the Money (song)|In It for the Money]]\"<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Pete finds new client!\n | date=29 April 2004\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n |work=NME\n | url=http://www.nme.com/news/client/16803\n}}</ref> and appears on their second album ''[[City (Client album)|City]]''.\n\nIn 2005 Doherty collaborated with the British rock band [[Littl'ans]] on the single \"[[Their Way (song)|Their Way]]\".<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Doherty records with The Littl'ans\n | date=19 September 2005\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n | publisher=contactmusic.com\n | url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/doherty%20records%20with%20the%20littlans\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Doherty was featured on the charity single \"[[Janie Jones (song)|Janie Jones]]\", which was released to raise funds for [[Strummerville]]. A number of artists and bands, such as [[Dirty Pretty Things (band)|Dirty Pretty Things]], [[We Are Scientists]], [[The Kooks]] and [[The Holloways]], also featured on the track.\n\nIn August 2006 it was announced that Doherty was recording with [[The Streets]] frontman Mike Skinner on a new version of \"[[Prangin' Out]]\", from Skinner's album ''[[The Hardest Way to Make an Easy Living]]''.<ref>{{cite news\n | title=Pete Doherty and The Streets record drugs anthem\n | date=9 August 2006\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n |work=NME\n | url=http://www.nme.com/news/streets/23863\n}}</ref>\n[[File:Petedoherty.jpg|thumbnail|upright|Pete Doherty in 2005]]\n\nIn 2015 he recorded the theme tune to the [[Sky 1]] sitcom ''[[After Hours (UK TV series)|After Hours]]''.\n\n===Babyshambles===\n[[File:PeteDoherty-Madrid2008.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Saturday Night Fiber]] festival, Madrid 2008]]\n{{Main|Babyshambles}}\nDoherty founded Babyshambles towards the end of his time with The Libertines. The group has released three studio albums: ''[[Down in Albion]]'', in November 2005, ''[[Shotter's Nation]]'', in October 2007, and [[Sequel to the Prequel|Sequel To The Prequel]], in September 2013. The band's touring schedule and releases have occasionally been disrupted by Doherty's ongoing legal problems. The line-up of the band has changed several times: drummer [[Gemma Clarke]] left the band due to Doherty's drug problems and was replaced by [[Adam Ficek]], and guitarist and co-songwriter [[Patrick Walden]] has also left the band and was replaced by [[Mick Whitnall]]. In August 2006, Babyshambles signed up with major record label [[Parlophone]], on which they released ''[[The Blinding EP]]'' on 9 December 2006.<ref name=\"Parlophone\">{{cite news|title=Babyshambles speak about new deal\n | date=15 September 2006|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=[[NME]].com|url=http://www.nme.com/news/babyshambles/24344\n}}</ref> In January 2007, they signed a long term record deal with Parlophone.<ref name=\"Parlophone_deal\">{{cite news\n | title=Babyshambles sign 'long term' record deal|date=18 January 2007\n | accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=[[NME]].com|url=http://www.nme.com/news/babyshambles/25926\n}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2007 Babyshambles played their first arena tour, taking in dates at the [[MEN Arena]] in Manchester, the [[Nottingham Arena]], [[Bournemouth International Centre]], London's [[Wembley Arena]] and Birmingham's [[National Indoor Arena]].<ref>{{cite news\n | title=The boys are hitting the road later this year...\n | date=16 March 2007\n | publisher=MTV.co.uk\n | url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/babyshambles/news/39978-babyshambles-announce-arena-tour\n | accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, the band's third album ''[[Sequel to the Prequel]]'' was released.\n\n===Solo work and guerrilla gigs===\nDoherty has been working on new acoustic material, similar to the wealth of his unreleased songs that can already be downloaded on the internet.<ref>NME Magazine \u2013 various issues</ref> On his own, and often with his band, he has continued [[The Libertines]]' tradition of performing on short notice [[guerrilla gig]]s in small venues.<ref name=\"Freedom Gig\">{{cite news\n | title=Pete Doherty plays 'freedom gig'\n | date=9 February 2006\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n |work=NME\n | url=http://www.nme.com/news/22178\n}}</ref> On New Year's Eve 2005, Doherty held a guerrilla gig in his [[North London]] flat where he showcased some of his solo works, many of which later leaked onto the internet.<ref name=\"BoundTogether\">{{cite book\n  | last = Thornton\n  | first = Anthony\n  |author2=Roger Sargent\n  | title = [[The Libertines Bound Together]]\n  | publisher = [[Hachette Book Group USA|Little, Brown Book Group]]\n  | year=  2006\n  | page = 263\n  | isbn = 0-316-73234-6}}</ref> 31 March and 1 April 2006 Doherty was performing two surprising solo gigs, his first in mainland Europe, at the NonStop Kino pornographic cinema and venue in [[Graz]], Austria, after he failed to turn up for an earlier arrangement in January. For this occasion he produced, at the suggestion of Bettina Aichbauer, friend of Doherty and owner of the NonStop Kino, a film with the title ''Spew It Out Your Soul'' which he showed on-screen during his performance.<ref name=\"Graz\">{{cite news\n |title      = \u00dcberraschungsgast in Graz\n |first      = Arthur\n |last       = Ein\u00f6der\n |date       = 1 April 2006\n |accessdate = 12 May 2007\n |publisher  = [[FM4]]\n |url        = http://fm4.orf.at/connected/212627\n}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\nOn 12 July 2008, Doherty played a solo gig at the [[Royal Albert Hall]]. It was his biggest solo show so far. The concert was originally scheduled for 26 April, but had to be rescheduled to a later date due to Doherty being sentenced to 14 weeks in prison for breaching probation on 8 April.<ref name=\"gdalb\">{{cite news| url=http://music.guardian.co.uk/live/story/0,,2290716,00.html |work=The Guardian  | location=London | title=Pete Doherty | first=Betty | last=Clarke | date=14 July 2008 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> The solo show did not get the best ratings but was all in all still well received. Jon Swaine of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' criticised that \"whole chunks of the set &hellip; passed by as listless noodling, with neither Doherty nor the audience appearing to know quite how to behave\" and that \u2013 without a full band \u2013 Doherty seemed out of place at such a big venue.<ref name=\"dt\">{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2008/07/14/bmpete114.xml | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=Pete Doherty's bloom lost in space | first=Jon | last=Swaine | date=14 July 2008 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> Betty Clarke of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described Doherty as \"focused\" and \"on good form\".<ref name=\"gdalb\"/> Friend and collaborator [[Peter Wolfe (musician)|Peter Wolfe]] had a guest appearance on stage when Doherty performed \"[[For Lovers]]\". Swaine stated Wolfe ruined the song with \"some especially tuneless backing vocals\".<ref name=\"dt\"/> The gig was forced to an abrupt end during the encore due to a stage invasion by the fans.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gigwise.com/news/44573/Pete-Doherty-Royal-Albert-Hall-Show-Hit-By-Stage-Invasion |title=Pete Doherty Royal Albert Hall Show Hit By Stage Invasion |first=Scott |last=Colothan |date=14 July 2008 |publisher=Gigwise |accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 January 2009, NME.COM announced that Doherty's solo album, entitled ''[[Grace/Wastelands]]'' would be released on 16 March, preceded by a single, \"[[Last of the English Roses]]\", on 9 March. The website also revealed the track listing of the album and credits. In 2009 Doherty was made an honorary patron of the [[University Philosophical Society]].\n\nWhilst performing a solo gig at the [[Grimsby]] Auditorium in March 2009, Doherty declared Grimsby a \"shit-hole\" midway through his set after being continuously pelted with coins and drinks by a harsh crowd.<ref>This is Grimsby. \"Beer Throwing was 'Disgusting'\". 15 April 2009. http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/beer-throwing-disgusting/story-11530778-detail/story.html{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Retrieved 7 June 2017.</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Doherty released a new single entitled \"Flags of the Old Regime\" through Walk Tall Recordings. All proceeds of single went to The [[Amy Winehouse Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wb0qz_tGGrs |title=Peter Doherty \u2013 Flags of the Old Regime [official video] |publisher=YouTube |date=2015-02-19 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Peter was joined on his 'Eudaimonia' tour by Drew McConnell (bass), Miki Beavis (violin), Katia de Vidas (keyboard), Stephany Kaberian (accordion) and Rafa (drums).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-gig-channel.com/#!Peter-Doherty-Eudaimonia-Tour-Is-A-Celebration-Of-A-New-Life/c112t/573f49030cf28f6d2bcebc97|title=The Gig Channel|website=The Gig Channel|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> He was also joined by [[Jack Jones (musician and poet)|Jack Jones]] of [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]] on guitar, who was support on the tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/features/107143/pete-doherty-2016-tour-diary-by-trampolene-jack-jones-libertines-poet|title=On the road with Peter Doherty \u2013 a tour diary by Trampolene {{!}} Gigwise|last=Trendell|first=Andrew|website=gigwise.com|access-date=2016-06-08}}</ref> He shared new track \u2018The Whole World Is Our Playground' on 4 May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neverenoughnotes.co.uk/2016/05/pete-doherty-announces-band-members-and-support-for-eudaimonia-tour-dates |last1=Stott|first1=Alex|title=Pete Doherty announces band members and support for Eudaimonia tour dates|accessdate=4 May 2016|publisher=Never Enough Notes}}</ref>\n\nIn early December 2016, Doherty released the album ''Hamburg Demonstrations'', which had been recorded in the city over a six month period, using mostly session musicians.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2016/12/album-review-peter-doherty-hamburg-demonstrations/|title=Album Review: Peter Doherty \u2013 Hamburg Demonstrations|date=2016-12-05|newspaper=Consequence of Sound|access-date=2017-01-17|language=en-US}}</ref> It was produced by [[Johann Scheerer]] and received favourable reviews.<ref>{{Citation|title=Hamburg Demonstrations by Peter Doherty|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/hamburg-demonstrations/peter-doherty|accessdate=2017-01-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Peter Doherty & the Puta Madres ===\n{{Main|Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres}}\nIn November 2016 [[Jack Jones (musician and poet)|Jack Jones]] was announced as lead guitarist in Doherty's new band The Puta Madres, joining Drew McConnell (bass), Miki Beavis (violin), Katia de Vidas (keyboard) and Rafa (drums), who had previously been his touring band. Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres played a gig in Argentina, followed by a week of shows in France including two nights for the reopening of the [[Bataclan (theatre)|Bataclan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/bataclan-anniversary-peter-doherty-carl-barat-libertines-review-sting-paris-attacks-a7422046.html|title=Peter Doherty at the Bataclan - review|date=2016-11-17|newspaper=The Independent|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-20}}</ref> They played [[The Forum, London|Kentish Town Forum]] in London and Manchester Albert Hall in December 2016 and several dates across Europe in February and March 2017.\n\nFollowing European and South American tours and festival appearances, the band recorded their debut album in France during the summer of 2018. The band played a short tour of the UK in February 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/peter-doherty-the-puta-madres-announce-debut-album-and-share-new-single-2439348|title=Peter Doherty & The Puta Madres announce debut album and share new single|last=Reilly|first=Nick|date=2019-01-28|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\nThe self-titled album was released on 26 April 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/peter-doherty-puta-madres-album-review-jack-jones-carl-barat-tour-dates-a8885751.html|title=Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres sound more befuddled than bohemian \u2013 review|date=2019-04-25|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref> and after instore signings the band set off on a UK and European tour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fredperry.com/subculture/article-peter-doherty-the-puta-madres?+The+Puta+Madres+Blog&+The+Puta+Madres+Blog|title=Peter Doherty & The Puta Madres Announce eponymous debut album & tour|website=www.fredperry.com|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n===Painting and writing===\nIn June 2006, Doherty announced that he had signed a deal with Orion Books to publish his journals, in which he had recorded poetry, drawings, and photos over the course of his career.<ref name=\"Book deal\">{{cite news\n | title=Pete Doherty Journals to Be Published\n | date=22 June 2006\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n | publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]\n | url=http://www.spin.com/features/news/2006/06/060622_petedoherty/\n}}</ref> Most of Doherty's journals are freely available on the internet.<ref name=\"AlbionArks\">{{cite web\n |title       = Books of Albion\n |url         = http://www.albionarks.com/books\n |publisher   = albionarks.com\n |accessdate  = 25 October 2006\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061010091621/http://www.albionarks.com/books/\n |archivedate = 10 October 2006\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> The book, titled ''The Books of Albion: The Collected Writings of Peter Doherty'', was released on 21 June 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.orionbooks.co.uk/HB-40521/Journals.htm |title=The Books of Albion-The Collected Writings of Peter Doherty by Peter Doherty \u2013 9780752885919- Orion Books |accessdate=17 June 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070318071643/http://www.orionbooks.co.uk/HB-40521/Journals.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 18 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 May 2007, Doherty exhibited his paintings for the first time. The art exhibition took place at London's Bankrobber Gallery and was on show for one month. The collection featured 14 paintings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/05/16/pete_doherty_s_bloodworks_exhibition_ope |title=Pete Doherty's Bloodworks Exhibition Opens in London |date=16 May 2007 |publisher=Starpulse Entertainment News Blog |accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nAn exhibition of Doherty's paintings titled, \"Art of the Albion\", took place at the Galerie Chappe in Paris from 25 April to 25 May 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/42662/pete-doherty-launches-new-blood-exhibition-in-paris |title=Pete Doherty Launches New Blood Exhibition in Paris |first=Jason |last=Gregory |date=25 April 2008 |publisher=Gigwise |accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref> The exhibit caused controversy due to artworks made with Doherty's own blood. According to newspapers, anti-drug campaigners were enraged and accused Doherty of glamorising illegal substance abuse.<ref name=\"indiatimes\">{{cite news| url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Personal_Finance/Art_/Art_exhibition_by_Doherty_causes_controversy/rssarticleshow/2987458.cms |work=The Times of India  | title=Art exhibition by Doherty causes controversy |date=27 April 2008 |accessdate=9 May 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090110230034/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/Personal_Finance/Art_/Art_exhibition_by_Doherty_causes_controversy/rssarticleshow/2987458.cms | archivedate=10 January 2009}}</ref> Art experts were similarly unimpressed. David West, the owner of London's [[Decima gallery]], for example, slammed his work: \"It's not got any artistic merit. He's using his blood to make them interesting, but when you look at them they're what any four-year-old can do.\"<ref name=\"indiatimes\"/>\n\n=== Muse ===\nIn February 2015, artist [[Nick Reynolds (sculptor)|Nick Reynolds]] exhibited a life-size sculpture of a crucified Doherty at the [[St Marylebone Parish Church|St Marylebone parish church]] in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/feb/18/lifesize-pete-doherty-crucifixion-sculpture-unveiled-in-church-missing-tom-fund|title=Lifesize Pete Doherty crucifixion sculpture to be unveiled in church|last=music|first=Guardian|date=2015-02-18|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 September 2015, [[conceptual artist]] [[Andy Picci]] staged an art project in which he pranked a group of paparazzi, dressed up as Doherty and duly found himself splashed over the cover of the [[Le Parisien|Parisien]] newspaper, which had taken him for the real thing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.vogue.fr/vogue-hommes/fashion/story/andy-picci-artist-identity-social-media-age-era-pete-doherty-who-are-you-richard-prince-cindy-sherman-nabilla-benattia-comme-des-garcons/3895|title=Artist Andy Picci is questioning identity in the age of social media|last=Larvin|first=Hugo Compain, translated by Hannah|work=Vogue English|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/the-rakes-progress-last-week-in-gossip-107/|title=The Rake\u2019s progress: last week in gossip {{!}} Apollo Magazine|date=2018-06-07|work=Apollo Magazine|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Modelling===\nFollowing in the footsteps of model and ex-fianc\u00e9e [[Kate Moss]], Doherty became the face of [[Roberto Cavalli]]'s Fall 2007/2008 fashion advertising campaign. The photos gained praise for depicting a much cleaner and more handsome Doherty. The '50s-style photographs have been compared to images of [[Marlon Brando]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1555571/Doherty-becomes-fashion-contender-for-Moss.html|title=Doherty becomes fashion contender for Moss|last=Alexander|first=Hilary|date=27 June 2007|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=29 June 2007|location=London|authorlink=Hilary Alexander}}</ref>\n\n===Acting===\nOn 9 December 2010 it was reported that Doherty would be taking the lead role opposite [[Charlotte Gainsbourg]] in ''[[Confession of a Child of the Century]]'', [[Sylvie Verheyde]]'s film adaption of [[Alfred de Musset]]'s autobiographical novel ''La Confession d'un Enfant du Si\u00e8cle''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/film-role-for-peter-doherty-2154999.html | location=London |work=The Independent  | first=Rob | last=Sharp | title=Film role for Peter Doherty | date=9 December 2010}}</ref> The film was screened at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>Catherine Shoard, [https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/may/21/confessions-child-century-review Cannes 2012: Confession of a Child of the Century] at guardian.co.uk</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nIn interviews, Doherty has listed his favourite books as [[George Orwell]]'s ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four|1984]]'', ''[[Brighton Rock (novel)|Brighton Rock]]'' by [[Graham Greene]], ''[[Our Lady of the Flowers]]'' by [[Jean Genet]], ''[[Les Fleurs du mal|Flowers of Evil]]'' by [[Charles Baudelaire]] and the complete works of [[Oscar Wilde]].<ref name=\"q+a2003\">{{cite web\n| url = http://libertines.twinkling-star.com/libertinesde.html\n| title = libertines.de Q&A with Pete\n| accessdate =27 March 2007\n|date=April 2003\n| publisher = libertines.de, archived by libertines.twinkling-star.com\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305100455/http://libertines.twinkling-star.com/libertinesde.html\n| archivedate = 5 March 2008\n}}</ref> He has also mentioned [[Emily Dickinson]] and [[Tony Hancock]] as influences; Doherty and his father were once members of the Tony Hancock Appreciation Society. Doherty mentions Hancock, and makes an allusion to his famous phrase 'Stone me!', in an early song entitled \"You're My Waterloo\". However, numerous literary and musical allusions occur throughout Doherty's ongoing ''Books of Albion''. He places particular importance on the [[Romantic poetry|Romantic poets]] and on existential philosophers such as [[Albert Camus]] and [[Miguel de Unamuno]]. Doherty has also alluded to work by the [[Marquis de Sade]] and [[Thomas de Quincey]]. On the Babyshambles album ''[[Down in Albion]]'', there is a track entitled \"\u00c0 rebours\", which is significantly influenced by [[\u00c0 rebours|the novel of the same name]] by [[Joris-Karl Huysmans]].<ref name=\"MotherInterview\">{{cite news|title=For Pete's sake|first=Janice|last=Turner|accessdate=12 May 2007|date=19 August 2006|work=[[The Times|Times]] Saturday Magazine|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,27869-2319045.html|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Emily Dickinson? She's hardcore'|date=3 October 2006|work=The Guardian|url=http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,,1886267,00.html|author=Barton, Laura|author2=Petridis, Alex|accessdate=26 March 2007|location=London}}</ref>\n\nDoherty has supported up-and-coming British bands, such as indie bands [[The Paddingtons]]<ref name=\"Rolling Stone profile\"/> and [[The View (band)|The View]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/entertainment-catch-all/2007/10/13/the-razz-doherty-view-on-rockers-86908-19944827|title=Pete Doherty Tells How He Gave The View Their Break|accessdate=2 November 2007|last=Lyons|first=Beverley|authorlink=Beverley Lyons|author2=Sutherland, Laura|date=13 October 2007|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230015151/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/entertainment-catch-all/2007/10/13/the-razz-doherty-view-on-rockers-86908-19944827|archivedate=30 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nDoherty is also known to be a devoted follower of [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] football club. As a youth (1995\u201396) he wrote a fanzine dedicated to the club, entitled \"All Quiet on the [[Western Avenue (London)|Western Avenue]]\".<ref name=\"MotherInterview\"/>\n\nA frequent lyrical theme for Doherty is [[Albion]], the ancient name for Great Britain. Doherty also uses 'Albion' as the name of a ship sailing to a utopia called [[Arcadia (utopia)|Arcadia]], a place without rules or authority. Doherty and Bar\u00e2t shared a flat in London, at 112a Teesdale Street, [[Bethnal Green]], affectionately known as 'The Albion Rooms', despite being rather run down. Doherty named his diaries, in which he writes poems and other thoughts, the ''[[Books of Albion]]''.<ref name=\"The Books of Albion\">{{cite news\n | title=The Books of Albion\n | date=26 June 2006\n | accessdate=12 May 2007\n | publisher=Babyshambles.net\n | url=http://www.babyshambles.net/books.asp\n}}</ref>\n\n==Drug abuse and legal problems==\nDoherty has been repeatedly arrested for drug offences and offences arising from drug use, such as [[driving under the influence]], car theft,<ref name=\"spin2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.spin.com/articles/grand-theft-auto-babyshambles|title=Grand Theft Auto: Babyshambles|work=Spin|accessdate=7 May 2008|date=28 February 2006}}</ref> and driving with a suspended [[driving licence|licence]].<ref name=\"reutersuk1\">{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUKL2015065120070820|title=Pete Doherty arrested after V Festival|agency=Reuters UK|accessdate=7 May 2008|date=20 August 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"spin1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.spin.com/articles/pete-doherty-arrested-again|title=Pete Doherty Arrested, Again|work=Spin|accessdate=7 May 2008|date=7 May 2007}}</ref> He has pleaded guilty to possession of [[crack cocaine]], heroin, cannabis and [[ketamine]].<ref name=\"reutersuk1\"/> His addictions have resulted in jail time and multiple trips to rehabilitation facilities.<ref name=\"spin1\"/> Drugs had been so important at some points in his life that in his younger days Doherty worked as a drug dealer to pay for his drug habit, as he admitted to author Peter Welsh in his biography.<ref>{{cite book|last=Welsh|first=Peter|title=Kids in the Riot: High and Low with the Libertines|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|year=2005|isbn=978-1-84449-716-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/kidsinriothighlo0000wels}}</ref> Doherty stated that he had been a [[rent boy]], and that during that time he robbed one of his male clients.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/story/doherty-i-was-a-gay-rent-boy-and-drug-dealer|title=Pete Doherty: I was a gay rent boy and drug dealer|date=17 April 2005|publisher=contactmusic.com|accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, while Doherty's first band [[The Libertines]] was performing in Japan without him, he broke into Carl Bar\u00e2t's flat and stole various items, including an old guitar and a laptop computer. On 7 September Doherty was sentenced by Judge Roger Davies to six months in prison; the sentence was eventually shortened to two months on appeal with the judge commenting, \"We feel that a custodial sentence was justified in this case but sufficient credit was not given for his timely plea of guilty which it should have been. We have reduced his sentence to two months which will allow for his almost immediate release.\" Doherty was released from jail on 8 October 2003.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/london/3142801.stm|publisher=BBC News|title=Musician admits burgling bandmate's flat|date=12 August 2003|accessdate=19 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/libertines/15033|work=NME|title=Pete Libertine Goes to Jail|date=8 September 2003|accessdate=28 November 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/3149610.stm|publisher=BBC News|title=Libertines singer's sentence cut|date=29 September 2003|accessdate=6 January 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xfm.co.uk/Article.asp?b=news&id=13717|publisher=[[xfm]]|title=Libertine Reunited with Liberated Pete|date=9 October 2003|accessdate=19 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 February 2005, Doherty was arrested after an altercation with documentary filmmaker [[Max Carlish]], who was making a [[rockumentary]] about the singer and sold photos of a heroin-smoking Doherty to the tabloids. Doherty and his friend Alan Wass had been charged with robbery and blackmail. On 7 February, he was released on bail after his record company [[Rough Trade Records|Rough Trade]] put up \u00a3150,000 in bonds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xfm.co.uk/Article.asp?b=news&id=65780|title=Pete Doherty Gets Conditional Bail|date=4 February 2005|publisher=xfm|accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antimusic.com/news/05/feb/item18.shtml|title=Pete Doherty Released From Jail|date=8 February 2005|publisher=antimusic.com|accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref> All charges against him were later dropped by the [[Crown Prosecution Service]] due to a lack of evidence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/apr/12/arts.artsnews|work=The Guardian|location=London|title=Pete Doherty's charges dropped|first=Owen|last=Bowcott|date=12 April 2005|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2007, a photo was published in several newspapers of Doherty allegedly forcing his pet cat to inhale from a crack pipe.<ref name=\"sfgate1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/dailydish/detail?blogid=7&entry_id=20100|work=San Francisco Chronicle|title=Doherty 'Forced Cat to Smoke Crack'|date=7 September 2007|accessdate=11 March 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpost1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2007/09/07/pete-doherty-photographed_1_n_63409.html|publisher=The Huffington Post|title=Pete Doherty Photographed Allegedly Giving His Kitten Crack|date=9 September 2007|accessdate=11 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 2008, Doherty was jailed for 14 weeks by a court for breaching a probation order after a string of brushes with the law for drugs and driving offences. On 18 April 2008, he was moved to a private area of [[Wormwood Scrubs (HM Prison)|Wormwood Scrubs prison]] after learning that fellow inmates were planning to attack him, therefore making it safer for the singer. On 6 May 2008, he was released after his sentence was cut in half and a further 18 days were remitted due to a government plan to reduce overcrowding. He also had another two days off for being in police custody (after serving just over 4 weeks of a 14-week sentence). He described prison life as \"a lot of gangsters and [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]]\" and showed a certificate confirming he had passed a [[drugs test]] while inside.<ref name=\"afp111\">{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Sky-News-Archive/Article/20080641315053|title=Rocker Pete Doherty Freed From Prison|accessdate=9 May 2011|date=6 May 2008|publisher=Sky News}}</ref>\n\nDoherty made another attempt to fight his drug addiction in September 2007, when he underwent rehab for six weeks at [[Clouds House]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/london/7023339.stm|title=Doherty gets chance to kick drugs|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 September 2008|date=2 October 2007}}</ref> However, he relapsed in November 2007 following his appearance at the [[MTV Europe Music Awards 2007]] in Munich.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7082897.stm|title=Doherty owns up to drug relapse|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 September 2008|date=7 November 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, Doherty was arrested in [[Gloucester]] and charged with driving dangerously, while drunk, and in possession of heroin. He was released on a \u00a350,000 bail<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisgloucestershire.co.uk/gloucestershireheadlines/Doherty-released-50K-bail/article-1073630-detail/article.html|title=Doherty released on \u00a350K bail|first=Jenni|last=Silver|publisher=thisisgloucestershire.co.uk|accessdate=21 December 2009|date=13 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213153319/http://www.thisisgloucestershire.co.uk/gloucestershireheadlines/Doherty-released-50K-bail/article-1073630-detail/article.html|archivedate=13 December 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and after 'guilty' pleas were entered, was asked to return to court on 21 December for sentencing. He was spared jail but was ordered to pay \u00a32,050 in fines, and was banned from driving for 18 months, despite the court hearing Doherty had 21 previous drug offences and six motoring offences. Following his release from court, he was escorted by officers to the nearest police station and re-arrested for possession of a controlled substance,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/crime/article6964514.ece|title=Pete Doherty rearrested after being convicted of driving and drug offences|first=Simon de|last=Bruxelles|work=The Times|accessdate=9 May 2011|date=22 December 2009|location=London}}</ref> later revealed to be heroin.<ref name=\"news.sky.com\">{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Showbiz-News/Singer-Pete-Doherty-Charged-With-Possession-Of-Heroin-Following-His-Arrest-After-A-Court-Appearance/Article/200912415506340|first=Neal|last=Walker|publisher=Sky News Online|title=Doherty Drug Charge After Court Appearance|accessdate=22 December 2009|date=22 December 2009}}</ref> The following day, 22 December, it emerged that Doherty could be charged with offences linked to a hit-and-run incident, which left a pedestrian in a critical condition. His manager, Andrew Boyd, appeared in court charged with a number of offences relating to the incident.<ref name=\"news.sky.com\"/> While Doherty was in Gloucester court on 21 December, heroin fell out of his coat pocket. He was arrested for possession and was convicted for this offence at the same court on 27 January 2010. He was fined \u00a3750 and ordered to pay \u00a385 court costs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/7083165/Pete-Doherty-fined-for-walking-into-court-with-heroin-in-pocket.html|title=Pete Doherty fined for walking into court with heroin in pocket|date=27 January 2010|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=9 May 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2010, Lowestoft magistrates fined Doherty \u00a3500 and banned him from driving for 12 months for allowing his [[Daimler AG|Daimler]] car to be used uninsured by his manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisiswiltshire.co.uk/news/headlines/5057410.marlborough_s_Pete_Doherty-banned_from_driving|title=Marlborough's Pete Doherty banned from driving|date=12 March 2010|publisher=thisiswiltshire.co.uk|accessdate=9 May 2011}}</ref> On 19 March 2010, he was arrested on [[Misuse of Drugs Act 1971|suspicion of supplying controlled drugs]]. He was reported to be on bail until April 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/crime/7496059/Pete-Doherty-arrested-over-drug-death-of-Robin-Whitehead.html|title=Pete Doherty arrested over drug death of Robyn Whitehead|date=22 March 2010|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=9 May 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010 Doherty was refused entry into the United States after spending 10 hours in detention in [[JFK Airport]], despite having a visa.<ref>{{cite web|last=Peck|first=Derek|title=New York Minute {{!}} Irina Lazareanu: Just a Kid from Canada|url=http://www.anothermag.com/current/view/268/Irina_Lazareanu_Just_a_Kid_from_Canada|publisher=AnOther|accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Pete Doherty never made it out of the airport.|url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/archives/2010/06/pete_doherty_ne.html|publisher=Brooklyn Vegan|accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 October 2010, Doherty was summoned to court for cocaine possession. In March 2011 he pleaded guilty to possession, and was granted unconditional bail until sentencing on 20 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/pete-doherty/56009|title=Pete Doherty facing jail again after pleading guilty to cocaine possession|date=9 April 2011|work=NME}}</ref> On 20 May, Doherty was sentenced to 6 months in jail for possession of cocaine, following the inquiry into the death of Robin Whitehead.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singer Pete Doherty jailed for cocaine possession|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-13451440|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=20 May 2011|date=20 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, Doherty was admitted to the [[Hope Rehab Centre]] in Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sean Michaels |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/nov/13/pete-doherty-returns-to-thai-rehab-centre |title=Pete Doherty returns to Thai rehab centre &#124; Music |publisher=The Guardian |date=2014-11-14 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref> He announced plans to start a foundation with the centre to help struggling addicts.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-libertines/81040 |title=NME News Pete Doherty 'wishes to help other addicts' as he spends last month in Thai rehab facility |publisher=Nme.Com |date=2014-11-12 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, it was announced that Doherty had successfully completed his rehab treatment. However, in August 2017 it was revealed that he had been found with heroin in his car while travelling through Italy. He was also found to be driving with an invalid licence. Doherty received a fine.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-libertines/82009 |title=NME News Pete Doherty leaves rehab after completing treatment in Thailand |publisher=Nme.Com |date=2015-01-03 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\nSince moving to Margate in 2017 Doherty has been arrested by Kent police on numerous occasions. January 2019 he was held for 48 hours and questioned. Charges of drug possession and several driving-related offences were later dropped.\n\nIn November 2019 Doherty was arrested in Paris, France on drugs possession charges.\n\n==Family and personal life==\nDoherty's mother, Jacqueline, is a nurse, who published a book about life with Doherty and his drug problems with the title ''Pete Doherty: My Prodigal Son''.<ref name=\"MotherInterview\"/> Doherty's father, Peter John Doherty, is a retired major in the British army.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=121&title=before_they_were_famous_amy_winehouse_pe&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1|title=Before They Were Famous|first=Luke|last=Lewis|accessdate=1 September 2008|date=1 September 2008|work=NME}}</ref>\n\nAfter numerous attempts to persuade him to make a serious attempt at rehabilitation, in early 2005 Doherty's father decided he was tired of broken promises and vowed not to see his son again until he was clean of drugs.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} The sensitivity surrounding the issue became apparent in the [[BBC Two]] ''[[Arena (UK TV series)|Arena]]'' documentary about Doherty, on 12 November 2006, which included footage of him talking about this aspect of his personal life. He was visibly upset and had to politely ask the interviewer at one point to stop filming. In October 2007, Doherty explained in an interview with the [[BBC Radio 4]] show ''Front Row'' that he had briefly reconciled with his father after three years when his father visited him in rehab, but were estranged again over drugs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7042330.stm|title=Doherty 'at drugs turning point'|accessdate=2 November 2007|date=12 October 2007|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nDoherty has had a tumultuous relationship with [[Kate Moss]], frequently covered by the press. They met in January 2005 at Moss' 31st birthday party and had an on-off relationship for several years. Moss had also taken to singing at some of Doherty's shows.<ref name=\"on stage with Moss\">{{cite news|title=Kate Moss and Pete Doherty Reignite Romance in Ireland|date=26 September 2006|accessdate=12 May 2007|publisher=Fox News|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,215858,00.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070504051102/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,215858,00.html|archive-date=4 May 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 11 April 2007, Doherty announced Moss as his fianc\u00e9e during the first of his solo gigs at the [[Hackney Empire]], London, at which Moss also performed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/opinion/main.jhtml?xml=/opinion/2007/04/15/do1509.xml|title=Kate and Pete, babies and shambles|accessdate=15 April 2007|last=McCartney|first=Jenny|date=15 April 2007|work=Sunday Telegraph|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1501119/story.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=10434394|title=Moss is now 'fiancee'|accessdate=15 April 2007|date=16 April 2007|work=The New Zealand Herald}}</ref> Doherty planned to marry Moss during the summer 2007.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|title=Pete Doherty cleans up act to marry Kate Moss|publisher=[[CTV Television Network|CTV]]|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070621/Pete_Doherty_070621/20070621?hub=Entertainment|date=21 June 2007|accessdate=23 June 2007}}</ref> Since July 2007, Moss and Doherty have broken up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/news/a116966/doherty-speaks-about-moss-split.html|title=Doherty speaks about Moss split|first=Beth|last=Hilton|date=30 July 2008|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, Doherty was briefly engaged to fashion model [[Irina L\u0103z\u0103reanu]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20128263,00.html |title=Report: Pete Doherty Engaged to Model \u2013 Not Kate Moss |accessdate=2 November 2007 |last=Silverman |first=Stephen M. |date=3 October 2007 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref>\n\nDoherty has a son, Astile (born 2003),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/story/pete-doherty-quizzed-by-son-on-drug-use_3791336|title=Pete Doherty quizzed by son on drug use |publisher=contactmusic.com |accessdate=18 October 2014}}</ref> with singer [[Lisa Moorish]].<ref name=\"scotsman\"/><ref name=\"MotherInterview\"/>\nDoherty's second child, a daughter, was born in December 2011 to South African model Lindi Hingston.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pete Doherty: I'm A Dad Again|date=1 November 2012|work=Huffington Post|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/02/17/pete-doherty-father_n_1283762.html|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, ''Rolling Stone'' reporter Claire Hoffman asked [[Amy Winehouse]] about her relationship with Doherty. Winehouse replied: \"We're just good friends\", and added: \"I asked Pete to do a concept EP, and he made this face, he looked at me like I'd pooed on the floor. He wouldn't do it. We're just really close\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Up All Night With Amy Winehouse: Rolling Stone's 2008 Story|page=Page 3 of 3|date=10 July 2008|work=Rolling Stone|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/up-all-night-with-amy-winehouse-rolling-stones-2008-story-20110723?page=3|author=Hoffman, Claire|accessdate=23 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nDoherty is a [[socialist]], stating that \"I do have utopian fantasies. A lot of them are more - I wouldn't say spiritual, but they relate more to the imagination and the individual. But for me socialism is a way of trying to put far-fetched ideas into everyday use, trying to find a way to bridge the gap between that fantasy and reality, and reaching out across that gap to the people who can actually do something to make the change.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://socialistreview.org.uk/284/charming-man-interview-pete-doherty|title=This Charming Man: An Interview with Pete Doherty|year=2004}}</ref>\n\nDoherty is also a supporter of English football team [[Queens Park Rangers]].\n\n==Musical equipment==\nDoherty prefers vintage equipment. Many of his vintage guitars and amplifiers have been destroyed in various domestic incidents.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/guitars/pete-doherty-on-gear-203176?cpn=RSS&source=MRNEWS |title=Pete Doherty on gear... |first=Chris |last=Vinnicombe |date=14 April 2009 |publisher=Musicradar.com |accessdate=30 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Guitars===\n*[[Epiphone Coronet]] \u2013 Doherty often used the rare one pick-up model (\u2018New York Coronet\u2019 made in 1957) in the early years of the Libertines, as well as in some later gigs. It is affectionately known as \u2018heavy horse\u2019 also Doherty\u2019s username in online band related forums. His father held the guitar \u2018hostage\u2019 during 8 years of Doherty\u2019s chaos and carnage, allowing it to be used in recent Puta Madres album recording sessions. \n*[[Gibson ES-330]] \u2013 One of Doherty's first known guitars. Used throughout the early Libertines gigs.\n*[[Epiphone Casino]] \u2013 Used with Babyshambles at recent concerts.\n*[[Rickenbacker 360]] \u2013 Used a lot in Babyshambles, live and in the studio.\n*[[Gibson ES-335]] \u2013 Used during the later years of the Libertines.\n*Epiphone Olympic \u2013 Another rare one pick-up Epiphone. Seen on the cover of the \"I Get Along\" single (The Libertines).\n\n===Amplifiers===\n*[[Vox AC30]]\n*[[Matchless Amplifiers|Matchless amplifier]]{{Which|date=August 2009}}\n*[[Marshall amplification|Marshall amplifier]]{{Which|date=August 2009}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{See also|The Libertines discography|Babyshambles discography}}\n\n;Solo albums\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Details\n!colspan=\"13\"| Peak chart positions\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=\"150\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<br /><small>([[List of music recording sales certifications|sales thresholds]])</small>\n|-\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[UK Albums Chart|UK]]</small><br /><ref name=\"UK charts\">{{cite web|url=https://acharts.co/album/42443|title=Pete Doherty|publisher=aCharts|accessdate=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[France|FRA]]</small><br /><ref name=aus>Australian ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]]) peaks:\n*Top 50 peaks: {{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Tricky|title=australian-charts.com > Tricky in Australian Charts|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=12 September 2016}}\n*Top 100 peaks to December 2010: {{cite book|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|title=Australia's Music Charts 1988\u20132010|year=2011|publisher=Moonlight Publishing|location=Mt. Martha, VIC, Australia}}\n*\"Aftermath\", \"Black Steel\", \"The Hell E.P.\", \"Christiansands\" and \"Makes Me Wanna Die\": {{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/11R0bwv.gif|title=Response from ARIA re: chart inquiry, received 12 September 2016|accessdate=12 September 2016|publisher=Imgur.com}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[ARIA Charts|AUS]]</small><br /><ref name=\"Pete Doherty\">{{cite web| url=https://acharts.co/album/42443|title=Pete Doherty|publisher=aCharts|accessdate=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Switzerland|SWI]]</small><br /><ref name=\"Pete Doherty\"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.7782&volume=61&issue=2&issue_dt=February%2013%201995&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=0t22h9dmaasqufav51q9mj5l21| title=''Second Coming'' Canadian position| publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]| accessdate=2009-02-11| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007022628/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.7782&volume=61&issue=2&issue_dt=February%2013%201995&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=0t22h9dmaasqufav51q9mj5l21| archive-date=7 October 2012| url-status=dead| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Media Control Charts|GER]]<br /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/STONE+ROSES%2CTHE/?type=longplay |title=German album positions |publisher=musicline.de |accessdate=2010-02-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525103001/http://musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/STONE+ROSES,THE/?type=longplay |archive-date=25 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref></small>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Irish Albums Chart|IRL]]<br /><ref name=\"IRL\">{{cite web| url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=The+Stone+Roses |title=Irish chart positions |publisher=irish-charts.com |accessdate=2010-02-18}}</ref></small>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Oricon|AUT]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/artists/h/95351/| title=Search for: Stone Roses| publisher=oricon.co.jp| accessdate=2009-02-16}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Megacharts|NLD]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://dutchcharts.nl/search.asp?search=Stone+Roses&cat=a| title=Search for: The Stone Roses| publisher=DutchCharts.nl| accessdate=2007-08-22}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"|<small>[[Belgium|BEL]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web | url=https://charts.nz/search.asp?search=Stone+Roses&cat=a | title=New Zealand album positions | publisher = charts.nz |accessdate=11 February 2009 }}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Norway|NOR]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://norwegiancharts.com/search.asp?search=Stone+Roses&cat=a| title=Search for: The Stone Roses| publisher=NorwegianCharts.com| accessdate=2007-08-22}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Swedish Singles Chart|SWE]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/search.asp?search=Stone+Roses&cat=a| title=Search for: The Stone Roses| publisher=SwedishCharts.com| accessdate=2007-08-25}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[RPM (magazine)|CAN]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web| url=http://hitparade.ch/search.asp?search=Stone+Roses&cat=a| title=Suche nach: The Stone Roses| publisher=HitParade.ch| accessdate=2007-08-22}}</ref>\n! width=\"25\"| <small>[[Billboard 200|US]]</small><br /><ref>{{cite web| url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=the stone roses|chart=all}}  | title=The Stone Roses Artist Chart History: Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| accessdate=2007-07-26}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Grace/Wastelands]]'\n* Label: [[Silvertone Records (1980)|Silvertone]] <small>(#502)</small>\n* Released: 16 March 2009\n* Format: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Compact Cassette|cassette]], [[LP record|LP]], [[Minidisc|MD]]\n| align=\"center\"| 17\n| align=\"center\"| 7\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n| align=\"center\"| 20\n| align=\"center\"| 28\n| align=\"center\"| 11\n| align=\"center\"| 83\n| align=\"center\"| 7\n| align=\"center\"| 38\n| align=\"center\"| 13\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Hamburg Demonstrations]]''\n* Label: Clouds Hill <small>(#24503)</small>\n* Released: 2 December 2016\n* Format: CD, cassette, LP, digital\n| align=\"center\"| 61\n| align=\"center\"| 96\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| 48\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| 67\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"| -\n| align=\"center\"|\n|-\n|2019\n|Peter Doherty & The Puta Madres\n|25\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| 36\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n;Singles\n* \"[[Last of the English Roses]]\" (9 March 2009) UK No. 67\n* \"[[Broken Love Song]]\" (3 August 2009)\n* \"Flags of the Old Regime\" (9 March 2015)\n* \"I Don't Love Anyone (But You're Not Just Anyone)\" (27 September 2016)\n\n;As featured artist\n\n* \"[[For Lovers]]\" ([[Peter Wolfe (musician)|Wolfman]] featuring Pete Doherty) (12 April 2004) UK No. 7\n* \"[[Their Way (song)|Their Way]]\" ([[Littl'ans]] featuring Pete Doherty) (17 October 2005) UK No. 22\n* \"[[Prangin' Out]]\" ([[The Streets]] featuring Pete Doherty) (25 September 2006) UK No. 25\n\n;Other appearances\n* ''Down to the Underground'' ([[Client (band)|Client]], featuring Pete Doherty). Taken from the ''[[City (Client album)|City]]'' album.\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Confession of a Child of the Century]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Amy (2015 film)|Amy]]'' (2015)\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|title=[[Books of Albion|The Books of Albion: The Collected Writings of Peter Doherty]]|date=2007|publisher= [[Orion Books]]|isbn= 0-7528-8591-X}}\n*{{cite book|date=2014|author=Doherty, Peter|title=From Albion to Shangri-La: Journals and Tour Diaries 2008 - 2013'|editor= [[Nina Antonia|Antonia, Nina]]|publisher= Thin Man Press|location= London|isbn= 978-0-9562473-9-1}}\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* ''2004'': Doherty was voted to be joint No. 1 in [[NME's Cool List|''NME''{{'}}s 2004 Cool List]], along with fellow Libertine Carl Bar\u00e2t. The following year he was placed at No. 6,<ref name=\"NMECoolList2005\">{{cite news|title=Who made it into the NME Cool List 2005?|date=22 November 2005|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=NME|url=http://www.nme.com/news/arctic-monkeys/21580}}</ref> and on 10 May 2006 was voted No. 2 in their poll depicting 50 of rock's greatest heroes.<ref name=\"50 Greatest Heroes\">{{cite news|title=Your biggest rock 'n' roll hero revealed|date=10 May 2006|accessdate=12 May 2007|work=NME|url=http://www.nme.com/news/nirvana/23019}}</ref>\n* ''2008'': On 28 February 2008, Doherty won the \"Hero of the Year\" award at the 2008 [[Shockwave NME Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/nme-awards/34780|title=Shockwaves NME Awards 2008: Pete Doherty named Hero of the Year|date=28 February 2008|work=NME|accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref>\n* ''2009'': On 25 February 2009, Doherty won the \"Best Solo Artist\" award at the 2009 Shockwave NME Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/pete-doherty/43035|title=Pete Doherty voted Best Solo Artist at Shockwaves NME Awards|date=25 February 2009|work=NME|accessdate=12 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|En-Pete_Doherty.ogg|2007-06-15}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{official website|http://albionrooms.com/}}\n* [http://lyricsmusic.name/pete-doherty-lyrics/ Pete Doherty lyrics]\n* [https://www.discogs.com/artist/219403-Pete-Doherty Pete Doherty on Discogs]\n\n{{The Libertines}}\n{{Babyshambles}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Doherty, Pete}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queen Mary University of London]]\n[[Category:British socialists]]\n[[Category:British people convicted of burglary]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Northumberland]]\n[[Category:English guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male guitarists]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English people convicted of drug offences]]\n[[Category:People of French-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English rock singers]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Parlophone artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Northumberland]]\n[[Category:NME Awards winners]]\n[[Category:People from Hexham]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:Rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:The Libertines members]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Babyshambles members]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pete_Doherty"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Motion", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[Sir]]\n| name          = Andrew Motion\n| honorific-suffix =  [[Royal Society of Literature|FRSL]]\n| image         = Andrew Motion, April 2009.jpg\n| imagesize     = 210px\n| alt           =\n| office        = [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom]]\n| monarch            = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| term_start         = 1 May 1999\n| term_end           = 1 May 2009\n| predecessor        = [[Ted Hughes]]\n| successor          = [[Carol Ann Duffy]]\n| caption       = Motion, reading poetry in 2009\n| pseudonym     =\n| birth_name     =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1952|10|26}}\n| birth_place    = [[London]], England\n| residence      = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], U.S.\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| occupation    = Poet\n| language      = English\n| nationality   = British\n| citizenship   =\n| education     = B.A. (Hons)\n| alma_mater    = [[University College, Oxford]]\n| period        = 1972-present\n| genre         =\n| subject       = \n| movement      =\n| notableworks  =\n| spouse        = {{unbulleted list|Joanna Powell {{font|size=95%|text=({{abbr|div.|divorced}} 1983)}}|{{marriage|Jan Dalley|1985|2009|end=div}}|{{marriage|Kyeong-Soo Kim|2009}}}}\n| children      = \n| relatives     =\n| influences    =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n| signature     =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       =\n| portaldisp    =\n}}\n\n'''Sir Andrew Motion''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL}} (born 26 October 1952) is an English poet, novelist, and biographer, who was [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom]] from 1999 to 2009. During the period of his laureateship, Motion founded the [[Poetry Archive]], an online resource of poems and audio recordings of poets reading their own work. In 2012, he became President of the [[Campaign to Protect Rural England]], taking over from [[Bill Bryson]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Chapel, Radley College, 22-05-2007.jpg|thumb|left|Radley College]]\nMotion was born on 26 October 1952<ref name=Debretts2005>{{cite book|title=Debrett's People of Today 2005|edition=18th|isbn=1-870520-10-6|publisher=[[Debrett's]]|page=1176}}</ref> in London, to (Andrew) Richard Michael Motion (1921-2006),<ref name=\"Essex Clay 2018\">Essex Clay, Andrew Motion, Faber and Faber, 2018, dedication page</ref> a brewer at [[Allied Breweries|Ind Coope]],<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/a-plea-to-the-poet-laureate-743020.html</ref> and (Catherine) Gillian (n\u00e9e Bakewell; 1928-1978).<ref name=\"Essex Clay 2018\"/><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/authorinterviews/9217384/World-of-Andrew-Motion-poet-novelist-and-biographer.html</ref><ref>Philip Larkin: A Writer's Life, Andrew Motion, Faber and Faber, 2018, p. xv, Introduction to the Second Edition</ref><ref name=Ramblings/> Richard Motion was from a brewing dynasty; his grandfather founded [[Allied Breweries|Taylor Walker]], but this had been absorbed by Ind Coope by Richard Motion's time.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/> The Motion family were wealthy [[armigers]] who lived at Upton House, [[Banbury]], [[Oxfordshire]], and were prominent in the local area; Richard Motion's grandfather Andrew Richard Motion was a [[Magistrate (England and Wales)|Justice of the Peace]] for [[Essex]], Oxfordshire and [[Warwickshire]].<ref>Armorial Families: A Directory of Gentlemen of coat armour, seventh edition, A. C. Fox-Davies, Hurst & Blackett Ltd, 1929, vol. II, pp. 1400-1401</ref>\n\nThe family moved to [[Stisted]], near [[Braintree, Essex|Braintree]] in Essex, when Motion was 12 years old.<ref name=Ramblings/> Motion went to [[boarding school]] from the age of seven<ref name=\"poetrymatters\"/> joined by his younger brother.<ref name=Ramblings/> Most of his friends were from the school and so when Motion was in the village he spent a lot of time on his own.<ref name=Ramblings/> He began to have an interest and affection for the countryside and he went for walks with a pet dog.<ref name=Ramblings/> Later he went to [[Radley College]], where, in the [[sixth form]], he encountered Peter Way, an inspiring English teacher who introduced him to poetry \u2013 first [[Thomas Hardy|Hardy]], then [[Philip Larkin]], [[W. H. Auden]], [[Seamus Heaney|Heaney]], [[Ted Hughes|Hughes]], [[Wordsworth]] and [[Keats]].<ref name=\"poetrymatters\"/><ref Name=\"Profile\">[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article4748531.ece \"Profile: Andrew Motion, the poet laureate\"]. ''The Sunday Times''. 14 September 2008.</ref>\n\nWhen Motion was 17 years old, his mother had a horse riding accident and suffered a serious head injury requiring a life-saving [[neurosurgery]] operation. She regained some speech, but she was severely paralysed and remained in and out of coma for nine years.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/5056194/Interview-with-Andrew-Motion.html \"Interview with Andrew Motion\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 30 March 2009</ref> She died in 1978 and her husband died of cancer in 2006.<ref name=Ramblings>{{cite episode|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01d2qf6 |title =Ramblings: Inspirational Walks: Sir Andrew Motion |series = Ramblings |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] |airdate=2012-03-17}}</ref> Motion has said that he wrote to keep his memory of his mother alive and that she was a muse of his work.<ref Name= \"AM\">[http://www.uktouring.org.uk/andrewmotion/books.htm Andrew Motion Official website] Accessed 12 July 2010</ref> When Motion was about 18 years old he moved away from the village to study English at [[University College, Oxford]];<ref Name= \"AM\"/> however, since then he has remained in contact with the village to visit the church graveyard, where his parents are buried, and also to see his brother, who lives nearby. At University he studied at weekly sessions with [[W. H. Auden]], whom he greatly admired.<ref Name=\"Profile\"/> Motion won the university's [[Newdigate Prize]] and graduated with a [[British undergraduate degree classification|first class honours degree]].<ref name=Ramblings/> This was followed by an MLitt on the poetry of [[Edward Thomas (poet)|Edward Thomas]].\n\n==Career==\nBetween 1976 and 1980, Motion taught English at the [[University of Hull]]<ref Name= \"AM\"/> and while there, at age 24, he had his first volume of poetry published. At Hull he met university librarian and poet [[Philip Larkin]]. Motion was later appointed as one of Larkin's literary executors, which would privilege Motion's role as his biographer following Larkin's death in 1985. In ''Philip Larkin: A Writer's Life'', Motion says that at no time during their nine-year friendship did they discuss writing his biography and it was Larkin's longtime companion [[Relationships that influenced Philip Larkin#Monica Jones|Monica Jones]] who requested it. He reports how, as executor, he rescued many of Larkin's papers from imminent destruction following his friend's death.<ref>Benton, Michael, Benton ''Literary Biography: An Introduction'' Wiley-Blackwell pp&nbsp;192\u2013200 {{ISBN|1-4051-9446-4}}</ref> His 1993 biography of Larkin, which won the [[1994 Whitbread Awards|Whitbread Prize for Biography]], was responsible for bringing about a substantial revision of Larkin's reputation.\n\nMotion was Editorial Director and Poetry Editor at [[Chatto & Windus]] (1983\u201389), he edited the [[Poetry Society]]'s ''[[Poetry Review]]'' from 1980\u20131982 and succeeded [[Malcolm Bradbury]] as Professor of Creative Writing at the [[University of East Anglia]].<ref Name= \"AM\"/>  He is now on the faculty at the [[Johns Hopkins Writing Seminars]].\n\n===Laureateship===\nMotion was appointed Poet Laureate on 1 May 1999, following the death of [[Ted Hughes]], the previous incumbent. The Nobel Prize-winning Northern Irish poet and translator [[Seamus Heaney]] had ruled himself out for the post. Breaking with the tradition of the laureate retaining the post for life, Motion stipulated that he would stay for only ten years. The yearly stipend of \u00a3200 was increased to \u00a35,000 and he received the customary [[butt (volume)|butt]] of [[Sack (wine)|sack]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.poetrysociety.org.uk/content/duffy09/poetlaureate/ | title=Carol Ann Duffy was officially declared as Britain's first female Poet Laureate on May&nbsp;1st 2009. | accessdate=21 May 2009 | publisher=The Poetry Society | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510115038/http://www.poetrysociety.org.uk/content/duffy09/poetlaureate/ | archivedate=10 May 2009 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nHe wanted to write \"poems about things in the news, and commissions from people or organisations involved with ordinary life,\" rather than be seen a 'courtier'. So, he wrote \"for the [[Trades Union Congress|TUC]] about liberty, about homelessness for [[the Salvation Army]], about bullying for [[ChildLine]], about the [[2001 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth outbreak|foot and mouth outbreak]] for the [[Today (BBC Radio 4)|''Today'' programme]], about the [[Ladbroke Grove rail crash|Paddington rail disaster]], the [[11 September attacks]] and [[Harry Patch]] for the BBC, and more recently about [[Combat stress reaction|shell shock]] for the charity [[Combat Stress]], and climate change for the song cycle he finished for Cambridge University with [[Peter Maxwell Davies]].\"<ref name=\"Lau rels\" />\n\nOn 14 March 2002, as part of the 'Re-weaving Rainbows' event of [[National Science Week]] 2002, Motion unveiled a blue plaque on the front wall of 28 St Thomas Street, [[Southwark]], to commemorate the sharing of lodgings there by [[John Keats]] and [[Henry Stephens (doctor)|Henry Stephens]] while they were medical students at [[Guy's Hospital|Guy's]] and [[St Thomas' Hospital]] in 1815\u201316.\n\nIn 2003, Motion wrote ''Regime change'', a poem in protest at the [[Invasion of Iraq]] from the point of view of Death walking the streets during the conflict,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/arts/2912557.stm|title=BBC News: \"Poet laureate writes Iraq lament\"|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.rice.edu/~ssiyer/minstrels/poems/1215.html |title=Regime Change |accessdate=12 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015005834/http://www.cs.rice.edu/~ssiyer/minstrels/poems/1215.html |archivedate=15 October 2009 }}</ref> and in 2005, ''Spring Wedding'' in honour of the wedding of the [[Prince of Wales]] to [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Camilla Parker Bowles]]. Commissioned to write in the honour of 109-year-old [[Harry Patch]], the last surviving \"[[Tommy Atkins|Tommy]]\" to have fought in [[World War I]], Motion composed a five-part poem, read and received by Patch at the [[Bishop's Palace, Wells|Bishop's Palace in Wells]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Poem honours WWI veteran aged 109|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/somerset/7279861.stm|work=BBC News Online|date=7 March 2008|accessdate=7 March 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080311005302/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/somerset/7279861.stm| archivedate= 11 March 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAs laureate, he also founded the [[Poetry Archive]], an on-line library of historic and contemporary recordings of poets reciting their own work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poetryarchive.org/poetryarchive/home.do|title=The Poetry Archive|accessdate=12 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140519101308/http://www.poetryarchive.org/poetryarchive/home.do|archivedate=19 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMotion remarked that he found some of the duties attendant to the post of poet laureate difficult and onerous and that the appointment had been \"very, very damaging to [his] work\".<ref>{{cite news|title= Laureate bemoans 'thankless' job|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7607897.stm|work=BBC News Online|date=10 September 2008|accessdate=10 September 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080910173623/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7607897.stm| archivedate= 10 September 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> The appointment of Motion met with criticism from some quarters.<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrew Motion to be Poet Laureate|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/1999/may/19/fiachragibbons.michaelwhite|work=The Guardian |date=19 May 1999|accessdate=10 September 2008 | location=London | first=Michael | last=White}}</ref> As he prepared to stand down from the job, Motion published an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'' that concluded, \"To have had 10 years working as laureate has been remarkable. Sometimes it's been remarkably difficult, the laureate has to take a lot of flak, one way or another. More often it has been remarkably fulfilling. I'm glad I did it, and I'm glad I'm giving it up \u2013 especially since I mean to continue working for poetry.\"\n<ref name=\"Lau rels\">Motion, Andrew (21 March 2009). [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/mar/21/andrew-motion-poet-laureate \"Yet once more, O ye laurels\"]. ''The Guardian'', Access date  2009-03-21.</ref><ref>Harper and Sullivan (2009), ''The Creative Environments: Authors at Work''. Woodbridge: Boydell and Brewer.</ref>\n\nMotion spent his last day as Poet Laureate holding a creative writing class at his alma mater, [[Radley College]], before giving a poetry reading and thanking Peter Way, the man who taught him English at Radley, for making him who he was. [[Carol Ann Duffy]] succeeded him as Poet Laureate on 1 May 2009.\n\n===Post-laureateship===\nMotion is Chairman of the Arts Council of England's Literature Panel (appointed 1996) and is also a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]].<ref Name= \"AM\"/> In 2003, he became Professor of Creative Writing at [[Royal Holloway]], [[University of London]].<ref>[http://www.rhul.ac.uk/english/studying/Postgraduate-Study/MA/CreativeWriting.htm Royal Holloway University site] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609174350/http://www.rhul.ac.uk/english/studying/Postgraduate-Study/MA/CreativeWriting.htm |date=9 June 2010 }}. Accessed 2010-08-17</ref> Since July 2009, Motion has been Chairman of the [[Museums, Libraries and Archives Council]] (MLA) appointed by the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]].<ref Name= \"AM\"/><ref>[http://www.culture.gov.uk/reference_library/media_releases/5237.aspx]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214233100/http://www.culture.gov.uk/reference_library/media_releases/5237.aspx |date=14 February 2009 }}</ref> He is also a Vice-President of the [[Friends of the British Library]], a charity which provides funding support to the [[British Library]].<ref name=\"ar0607\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bl.uk/supportus/pdf/friendsannrep0607.pdf|title=Friends of the British Library Annual Report 2006/07| accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> He was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the 2009 Queen's Birthday Honours list.<ref Name= \"AM\"/> He has been a member of [[English Heritage]]'s Blue Plaques Panel since 2008.\n\nMotion was selected as jury chair for the [[Man Booker Prize]] 2010<ref>[http://www.themanbookerprize.com/prize/thisyear/judges]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103002735/http://www.themanbookerprize.com/prize/thisyear/judges |date=3 January 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=59090 |date=13 June 2009 |page=1 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8097237.stm|title=BBC News|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> and in March 2010, he announced that he was working with publishers [[Jonathan Cape]] on a sequel to [[Robert Louis Stevenson]]'s ''[[Treasure Island]]''. Entitled ''Silver'', the story is set a generation on from the original book and was published in March 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/arts_and_culture/8588371.stm|title=Sir Andrew Motion to write Treasure Island sequel |date=26 March 2010|work=BBC News|accessdate=26 March 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100329135349/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/arts_and_culture/8588371.stm| archivedate= 29 March 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In July 2010, Motion returned to [[Kingston-upon-Hull]] for the annual ''Humber Mouth'' literature festival and taking part in the [[Larkin 25]] festival commemorating the 25th anniversary of [[Philip Larkin]]'s death. In his capacity as Larkin's biographer and as a former lecturer in English at the [[University of Hull]], Motion named an [[East Yorkshire Motor Services]] bus ''Philip Larkin''.<ref>''Yorkshire Evening Post'' 6 July 2010 [http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/localnews/Buses-are-fare-way-to.6403079.jp \"Buses are fare way to celebrate city poet\"] (Retrieved 7 July 2010)</ref><ref>[http://www.larkin25.co.uk/news.php Larkin 25. 7 July 2010. ''Welcome aboard the Philip Larkin bus!'' ](Retrieved 12 July 2010)</ref> Motion's debut play ''[[Incoming (play)|Incoming]]'', about the war in Afghanistan, premi\u00e8red at the High Tides Festival in [[Halesworth]], Suffolk in May 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-news/8335508/Andrew-Motion-to-debut-as-playwright-with-work-about-Afghanistan.html |title=Andrew Motion to debut as playwright with work about Afghanistan - Telegraph |first=Roya |last=Nikkhah |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=20 February 2010 |location=[[London, UK|London]] |issn=0307-1235 |oclc=49632006 |accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref> Motion also featured in ''[[Jamie's Dream School]]'' in 2011 as the poetry teacher.\n\nIn June 2012, he became the President of the [[Campaign to Protect Rural England]]. In March 2014 he was elected an Honorary Fellow at [[Homerton College, Cambridge]].\n\nMotion won the 2015 [[Ted Hughes Award]] for new work in poetry for the radio programme ''Coming Home''. The production featured poetry by Motion based on recordings he made of British soldiers returning from the wars in [[Iraq]] and [[Afghanistan]].<ref>Mark Brown, [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/apr/02/andrew-motion-wins-ted-hughes-award-poetry-returning-soldiers Andrew Motion wins Ted Hughes award for poetry work about returning soldiers], The Guardian, 2 April 2015.</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Motion moved to Baltimore, Maryland to take up a post at the [[Johns Hopkins Writing Seminars|Writing Seminars]] as a Homewood Professor of the Arts at [[Johns Hopkins University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://hub.jhu.edu/at-work/2016/01/11/andrew-motion|title= British poet Andrew Motion settles into life in America as a professor at Johns Hopkins|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\nMotion has said of himself: \"My wish to write a poem is inseparable from my wish to explain something to myself.\" His work combines lyrical and narrative aspects in a \"postmodern-romantic sensibility\".<ref Name=\"BC\"/> Motion says that he aims to write in clear language without tricks.<ref Name=\"BC\"/>\n\n''[[The Independent]]'' describes the stalwart poet as the \"charming and tireless defender of the art form\".<ref name=\"poetrymatters\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/andrew-motion-poetry-needs-us-to-say-that-it-matters-1669470.html \"Andrew Motion: 'Poetry needs us to say that it matters'\"]. ''The Independent'', 17 April 2009. Accessed 18 July 2010</ref> Motion has won the [[Arvon Foundation|Arvon]] Prize, the [[John Llewellyn Rhys Prize]], [[Eric Gregory Award]], [[1994 Whitbread Awards|Whitbread Prize for Biography]] and the [[Dylan Thomas Prize]].<ref Name= \"AM\"/><ref Name=\"BC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth76 |title=British Council Biography |accessdate=12 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001130129/http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth76 |archivedate=1 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nMotion took part in the [[Bush Theatre]]'s 2011 project ''[[Sixty-Six Books]]'', writing and performing a piece based upon a book of the ''[[King James Version|King James Bible]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |title=Bush Theatre |accessdate=12 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704090950/http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |archivedate=4 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMotion's marriage to Joanna Powell ended in 1983.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/andrew-motion-poetic-licence-to-thrill-413487.html \"Andrew Motion: Poetic licence to thrill\"]. ''The Independent'', 27 August 2006.</ref> He was married to Jan Dalley from 1985 to 2009, divorcing after a seven-year separation. They had one son born in 1986 and twins, a son and a daughter, born in 1988. In 2009 he married Kyeong-Soo Kim. He currently lives part of the year in Baltimore, Maryland.\n\n==Selected honours and awards==\n* 1975: won the [[Newdigate prize]] for Oxford undergraduate poetry\n* 1976: [[Eric Gregory Award]]\n* 1981: wins [[Arvon Foundation]]'s International Poetry Competition with ''The Letter''\n* 1984:  [[John Llewellyn Rhys Prize]] for ''Dangerous Play: Poems 1974\u20131984''\n* 1987: [[Somerset Maugham Award]] for ''The Lamberts''\n* 1987:  [[Dylan Thomas Prize]] for ''Natural Causes''\n* 1999: appointed [[Poet Laureate]] for ten years\n* 1994: ''Philip Larkin: A Writer\u2019s Life'', [[1994 Whitbread Awards|Whitbread Prize for Biography]]\n* 2009:  [[Knight Bachelor]]\n* 2014:  Wilfred Owen Poetry Award\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=July 2018}}\n\n=== Poetry ===\n;Collections\n*{{cite book |author=Motion, Andrew |authormask=  |title=Goodnestone : a sequence |location= |publisher=Workshop Press |year=1972 |<!--isbn=-->}}\n*{{cite book |author=Motion, Andrew |authormask=1 |title=Inland |location= |publisher=Cygnet Press |year=1976 |<!--isbn=-->}}\n* 1977: ''The Pleasure Steamers''. Carcanet\n* 1981: ''Independence''. Salamander Press\n* 1983: ''Secret Narratives''. Salamander Press\n* 1984: ''Dangerous Play: Poems 1974\u20131984.'' Salamander Press / Penguin\n* 1987: ''Natural Causes''. Chatto & Windus\n* 1988: ''Two Poems''. Words Ltd\n* 1991: ''Love in a Life''. Faber and Faber\n* 1994: ''The Price of Everything.'' Faber and Faber\n* 1997: ''Salt Water'' Faber and Faber\n* 1998: ''Selected Poems 1976\u20131997''. Faber and Faber\n* 2001: ''A Long Story''. The Old School Press\n* 2002: ''Public Property''. Faber and Faber\n* 2009: ''The Cinder Path''. Faber and Faber\n* 2012: ''The Customs House''. Faber and Faber\n* 2015: ''Peace Talks''. Faber and Faber\n* 2015: ''Coming Home''. Published by Andrew J Moorhouse at Fine Press Poetry http://www.finepresspoetry.com\n* Coming in to Land: Selected Poems, 1975\u20132015\n*2018: ''Essex Clay''. Faber and Faber\n\n;List of poems\n{|class='wikitable sortable' width='90%'\n|-\n!width=25%|Title\n!|Year\n!|First published\n!|Reprinted/collected\n|-\n|A Cabbage White\n|2018\n|{{cite journal |author=Motion, Andrew |authormask= |date=February 22, 2018 |title=A Cabbage White |department= |journal=The New York Review of Books |volume=65 |issue=3 |pages=18}}\n|\n|-\n|Chincoteague\n|2018\n|{{cite journal |author=Motion, Andrew |authormask= |date=February 22, 2018 |title=Chincoteague |department= |journal=The New York Review of Books |volume=65 |issue=3 |pages=24}}\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Criticism===\n* 1980: ''The Poetry of [[Edward Thomas (poet)|Edward Thomas]]''.   Routledge & Kegan Paul\n* 1982: ''[[Philip Larkin]]''. (Contemporary Writers series) Methuen\n* 1986: ''[[Elizabeth Bishop]]. (Chatterton Lectures on an English Poet)''\n* 1998: ''Sarah Raphael: Strip!''. Marlborough Fine Art (London)\n* 2008: ''Ways of Life: On Places, Painters and Poets''. Faber and Faber\n\n===Biography===\n* 1986: ''The Lamberts: [[George Washington Lambert|George]], [[Constant Lambert|Constant]] and [[Kit Lambert|Kit]]''. Chatto & Windus\n* 1993: ''[[Philip Larkin]]: A Writer's Life''. Faber and Faber\n* 1997: ''[[John Keats|Keats]]: A Biography''. Faber and Faber\n\n===Memoirs===\n* 2006: ''In the Blood: A Memoir of my Childhood''. Faber and Faber\n\n===Fiction===\n* 1989: ''The Pale Companion''. Penguin\n* 1991: ''Famous for the Creatures''. Viking\n* 2003: ''The Invention of Dr Cake''. Faber and Faber\n* 2000: ''Wainewright the Poisoner: The Confessions of [[Thomas Griffiths Wainewright]]'' ([[biographical novel]])\n* 2012: ''[[Silver (Andrew Motion novel)|Silver]]''. Jonathan Cape\n* 2015: ''The New World''. Crown\n\n===Edited works, introductions, and forewords===\n* 1981: ''Selected Poems: [[William Barnes]]''. Penguin Classics\n* 1982: ''The Penguin Book of Contemporary British Poetry'' with [[Blake Morrison]]. Penguin\n* 1994: ''[[Thomas Hardy]]: Selected Poems''. Dent\n* 1993: ''New Writing 2'' (With [[Malcolm Bradbury]]). Minerva in association with the British Council\n* 1994: ''New Writing 3'' (With Candice Rodd). Minerva in association with the British Council\n* 1997: ''Penguin Modern Poets: Volume 11''  with [[Michael Donaghy]] and [[Hugo Williams]]. Penguin\n* 1998: ''Take 20: New Writing''. University of East Anglia\n* 1999: ''Verses of the Poets Laureate: From [[John Dryden]] to Andrew Motion''. With Hilary Laurie. Orion.\n* 1999: ''Babel: New Writing by the University of East Anglia's MA Writers''. University of East Anglia.\n* 2001: ''Firsthand: The New Anthology of Creative Writing from the University of East Anglia''. University of East Anglia\n* 2002: ''Paper Scissors Stone: New Writing from the MA in Creative Writing at [[University of East Anglia|UEA]]''. University of East Anglia.\n* 2001: ''The Creative Writing Coursebook: Forty Authors Share Advice and Exercises for Fiction & Poetry''. With Julia Bell. Macmillan\n* 2000: ''[[John Keats]]: Poems Selected by Andrew Motion''. Faber and Faber\n* 2001: ''Here to Eternity: An Anthology of Poetry''. Faber and Faber\n* 2002: ''[[May Anthologies|The Mays Literary Anthology]]''; Guest editor. Varsity Publications\n* 2003: ''101 Poems Against War ''. Faber and Faber (Afterword)\n* 2003: ''First World War Poems''. Faber and Faber\n* 2006: ''Collins Rhyming Dictionary''. Collins\n* 2007: ''Bedford Square 2: New Writing from the Royal Holloway Creative Writing Programme''. John Murray Ltd.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Andrew Motion}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.poetryarchive.org/poetryarchive/singlePoet.do?poetId=212 Profile and poems written and audio] at the Poetry Archive\n* [http://www.poets.org/poet.php/prmPID/2096 Profile at Poets.org]\n* [http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/saction.php?search=ss&firstRun=true&sText=%22andrew+motion%22 National Portrait Gallery portraits]\n* {{British council|id=andrew-motion|name=Professor Andrew Motion}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/education/2005/dec/13/highereducationprofile.highereducation?INTCMP=SRCH ''Guardian''] profile 13 December 2005 \"Andrew Motion: Mr Speaker\".  [https://www.theguardian.com/books/video/2009/apr/27/andrew-motion-poetry?INTCMP=SRCH ''Guardian''] \"Andrew Motion on war poetry\". Interview and reading. 27 July 2009 (Video, 8 mins)\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/audiointerviews/profilepages/motiona1.shtml BBC] profile. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/learningzone/clips/andrew-motion-on-being-poet-laureate/6957.html BBC interview] \"Andrew Motion on being Poet Laureate\" (Video, 4 mins). [https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/1DxnakmMR96M_jQOhA_BJw BBC interview] \"Andrew Motion's Hindu Wood Carving\" (Video 4 mins)\n* [http://www.press.uchicago.edu/Misc/Chicago/542409.html A chapter] from ''Keats,'' about John Keats, Fanny Brawne, and his poem for her, \"Bright Star\"\n* {{YouTube|id=w54DO8PHzSw|title=Bonfire of the Humanities}}, Andrew Motion's Romanes Lecture (2011) at Oxford University (video)\n\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n\n{{Poets Laureate of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Motion, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century biographers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century biographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:Academics of Royal Holloway, University of London]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of East Anglia]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Hull]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Poets Laureate]]\n[[Category:English biographers]]\n[[Category:English book editors]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:People educated at Radley College]]\n[[Category:People from Braintree, Essex]]\n[[Category:The New York Review of Books people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = [[Sir]]\n| name          = Andrew Motion\n| honorific-suffix =  [[Royal Society of Literature|FRSL]]\n| image         = Andrew Motion, April 2009.jpg\n| imagesize     = 210px\n| alt           =\n| office        = [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom]]\n| monarch            = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| term_start         = 1 May 1999\n| term_end           = 1 May 2009\n| predecessor        = [[Ted Hughes]]\n| successor          = [[Carol Ann Duffy]]\n| caption       = Motion, reading poetry in 2009\n| pseudonym     =\n| birth_name     =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1952|10|26}}\n| birth_place    = [[London]], England\n| residence      = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], U.S.\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| occupation    = Poet\n| language      = English\n| nationality   = British\n| citizenship   =\n| education     = B.A. (Hons)\n| alma_mater    = [[University College, Oxford]]\n| period        = 1972-present\n| genre         =\n| subject       = \n| movement      =\n| notableworks  =\n| spouse        = {{unbulleted list|Joanna Powell {{font|size=95%|text=({{abbr|div.|divorced}} 1983)}}|{{marriage|Jan Dalley|1985|2009|end=div}}|{{marriage|Kyeong-Soo Kim|2009}}}}\n| children      = \n| relatives     =\n| influences    =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n| signature     =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       =\n| portaldisp    =\n}}\n\n'''Sir Andrew Motion''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL}} (born 26 October 1952) is an English poet, novelist, and biographer, who was [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom]] from 1999 to 2009. During the period of his laureateship, Motion founded the [[Poetry Archive]], an online resource of poems and audio recordings of poets reading their own work. In 2012, he became President of the [[Campaign to Protect Rural England]], taking over from [[Bill Bryson]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Chapel, Radley College, 22-05-2007.jpg|thumb|left|Radley College]]\nMotion was born on 26 October 1952<ref name=Debretts2005>{{cite book|title=Debrett's People of Today 2005|edition=18th|isbn=1-870520-10-6|publisher=[[Debrett's]]|page=1176}}</ref> in London, to (Andrew) Richard Michael Motion (1921-2006),<ref>Essex Clay, Andrew Motion, Faber and Faber, 2018, dedication page</ref> a brewer at [[Allied Breweries|Ind Coope]],<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/a-plea-to-the-poet-laureate-743020.html</ref> and (Catherine) Gillian (n\u00e9e Bakewell; 1928-1978).<ref>Essex Clay, Andrew Motion, Faber and Faber, 2018, dedication page</ref><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/authorinterviews/9217384/World-of-Andrew-Motion-poet-novelist-and-biographer.html</ref><ref>Philip Larkin: A Writer's Life, Andrew Motion, Faber and Faber, 2018, p. xv, Introduction to the Second Edition</ref><ref name=Ramblings/> Richard Motion was from a brewing dynasty; his grandfather founded [[Allied Breweries|Taylor Walker]], but this had been absorbed by Ind Coope by Richard Motion's time.<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/a-plea-to-the-poet-laureate-743020.html</ref> The Motion family were wealthy [[armigers]] who lived at Upton House, [[Banbury]], [[Oxfordshire]], and were prominent in the local area; Richard Motion's grandfather Andrew Richard Motion was a [[Magistrate (England and Wales)|Justice of the Peace]] for [[Essex]], Oxfordshire and [[Warwickshire]].<ref>Armorial Families: A Directory of Gentlemen of coat armour, seventh edition, A. C. Fox-Davies, Hurst & Blackett Ltd, 1929, vol. II, pp. 1400-1401</ref> \n\nThe family moved to [[Stisted]], near [[Braintree, Essex|Braintree]] in Essex, when Motion was 12 years old.<ref name=Ramblings/> Motion went to [[boarding school]] from the age of seven<ref name=\"poetrymatters\"/> joined by his younger brother.<ref name=Ramblings/> Most of his friends were from the school and so when Motion was in the village he spent a lot of time on his own.<ref name=Ramblings/> He began to have an interest and affection for the countryside and he went for walks with a pet dog.<ref name=Ramblings/> Later he went to [[Radley College]], where, in the [[sixth form]], he encountered Peter Way, an inspiring English teacher who introduced him to poetry \u2013 first [[Thomas Hardy|Hardy]], then [[Philip Larkin]], [[W. H. Auden]], [[Seamus Heaney|Heaney]], [[Ted Hughes|Hughes]], [[Wordsworth]] and [[Keats]].<ref name=\"poetrymatters\"/><ref Name=\"Profile\">[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article4748531.ece \"Profile: Andrew Motion, the poet laureate\"]. ''The Sunday Times''. 14 September 2008.</ref>\n\nWhen Motion was 17 years old, his mother had a horse riding accident and suffered a serious head injury requiring a life-saving [[neurosurgery]] operation. She regained some speech, but she was severely paralysed and remained in and out of coma for nine years.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/5056194/Interview-with-Andrew-Motion.html \"Interview with Andrew Motion\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 30 March 2009</ref> She died in 1978 and her husband died of cancer in 2006.<ref name=Ramblings>{{cite episode|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01d2qf6 |title =Ramblings: Inspirational Walks: Sir Andrew Motion |series = Ramblings |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] |airdate=2012-03-17}}</ref> Motion has said that he wrote to keep his memory of his mother alive and that she was a muse of his work.<ref Name= \"AM\">[http://www.uktouring.org.uk/andrewmotion/books.htm Andrew Motion Official website] Accessed 12 July 2010</ref> When Motion was about 18 years old he moved away from the village to study English at [[University College, Oxford]];<ref Name= \"AM\"/> however, since then he has remained in contact with the village to visit the church graveyard, where his parents are buried, and also to see his brother, who lives nearby. At University he studied at weekly sessions with [[W. H. Auden]], whom he greatly admired.<ref Name=\"Profile\"/> Motion won the university's [[Newdigate Prize]] and graduated with a [[British undergraduate degree classification|first class honours degree]].<ref name=Ramblings/> This was followed by an MLitt on the poetry of [[Edward Thomas (poet)|Edward Thomas]].\n\n==Career==\nBetween 1976 and 1980, Motion taught English at the [[University of Hull]]<ref Name= \"AM\"/> and while there, at age 24, he had his first volume of poetry published. At Hull he met university librarian and poet [[Philip Larkin]]. Motion was later appointed as one of Larkin's literary executors, which would privilege Motion's role as his biographer following Larkin's death in 1985. In ''Philip Larkin: A Writer's Life'', Motion says that at no time during their nine-year friendship did they discuss writing his biography and it was Larkin's longtime companion [[Relationships that influenced Philip Larkin#Monica Jones|Monica Jones]] who requested it. He reports how, as executor, he rescued many of Larkin's papers from imminent destruction following his friend's death.<ref>Benton, Michael, Benton ''Literary Biography: An Introduction'' Wiley-Blackwell pp&nbsp;192\u2013200 {{ISBN|1-4051-9446-4}}</ref> His 1993 biography of Larkin, which won the [[1994 Whitbread Awards|Whitbread Prize for Biography]], was responsible for bringing about a substantial revision of Larkin's reputation.\n\nMotion was Editorial Director and Poetry Editor at [[Chatto & Windus]] (1983\u201389), he edited the [[Poetry Society]]'s ''[[Poetry Review]]'' from 1980\u20131982 and succeeded [[Malcolm Bradbury]] as Professor of Creative Writing at the [[University of East Anglia]].<ref Name= \"AM\"/>  He is now on the faculty at the [[Johns Hopkins Writing Seminars]].\n\n===Laureateship===\nMotion was appointed Poet Laureate on 1 May 1999, following the death of [[Ted Hughes]], the previous incumbent. The Nobel Prize-winning Northern Irish poet and translator [[Seamus Heaney]] had ruled himself out for the post. Breaking with the tradition of the laureate retaining the post for life, Motion stipulated that he would stay for only ten years. The yearly stipend of \u00a3200 was increased to \u00a35,000 and he received the customary [[butt (volume)|butt]] of [[Sack (wine)|sack]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.poetrysociety.org.uk/content/duffy09/poetlaureate/ | title=Carol Ann Duffy was officially declared as Britain's first female Poet Laureate on May&nbsp;1st 2009. | accessdate=21 May 2009 | publisher=The Poetry Society | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510115038/http://www.poetrysociety.org.uk/content/duffy09/poetlaureate/ | archivedate=10 May 2009 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nHe wanted to write \"poems about things in the news, and commissions from people or organisations involved with ordinary life,\" rather than be seen a 'courtier'. So, he wrote \"for the [[Trades Union Congress|TUC]] about liberty, about homelessness for [[the Salvation Army]], about bullying for [[ChildLine]], about the [[2001 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth outbreak|foot and mouth outbreak]] for the [[Today (BBC Radio 4)|''Today'' programme]], about the [[Ladbroke Grove rail crash|Paddington rail disaster]], the [[11 September attacks]] and [[Harry Patch]] for the BBC, and more recently about [[Combat stress reaction|shell shock]] for the charity [[Combat Stress]], and climate change for the song cycle he finished for Cambridge University with [[Peter Maxwell Davies]].\"<ref name=\"Lau rels\" />\n\nOn 14 March 2002, as part of the 'Re-weaving Rainbows' event of [[National Science Week]] 2002, Motion unveiled a blue plaque on the front wall of 28 St Thomas Street, [[Southwark]], to commemorate the sharing of lodgings there by [[John Keats]] and [[Henry Stephens (doctor)|Henry Stephens]] while they were medical students at [[Guy's Hospital|Guy's]] and [[St Thomas' Hospital]] in 1815\u201316.\n\nIn 2003, Motion wrote ''Regime change'', a poem in protest at the [[Invasion of Iraq]] from the point of view of Death walking the streets during the conflict,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/arts/2912557.stm|title=BBC News: \"Poet laureate writes Iraq lament\"|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.rice.edu/~ssiyer/minstrels/poems/1215.html |title=Regime Change |accessdate=12 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015005834/http://www.cs.rice.edu/~ssiyer/minstrels/poems/1215.html |archivedate=15 October 2009 }}</ref> and in 2005, ''Spring Wedding'' in honour of the wedding of the [[Prince of Wales]] to [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall|Camilla Parker Bowles]]. Commissioned to write in the honour of 109-year-old [[Harry Patch]], the last surviving \"[[Tommy Atkins|Tommy]]\" to have fought in [[World War I]], Motion composed a five-part poem, read and received by Patch at the [[Bishop's Palace, Wells|Bishop's Palace in Wells]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Poem honours WWI veteran aged 109|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/somerset/7279861.stm|work=BBC News Online|date=7 March 2008|accessdate=7 March 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080311005302/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/somerset/7279861.stm| archivedate= 11 March 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAs laureate, he also founded the [[Poetry Archive]], an on-line library of historic and contemporary recordings of poets reciting their own work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poetryarchive.org/poetryarchive/home.do|title=The Poetry Archive|accessdate=12 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140519101308/http://www.poetryarchive.org/poetryarchive/home.do|archivedate=19 May 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nMotion remarked that he found some of the duties attendant to the post of poet laureate difficult and onerous and that the appointment had been \"very, very damaging to [his] work\".<ref>{{cite news|title= Laureate bemoans 'thankless' job|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7607897.stm|work=BBC News Online|date=10 September 2008|accessdate=10 September 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080910173623/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7607897.stm| archivedate= 10 September 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> The appointment of Motion met with criticism from some quarters.<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrew Motion to be Poet Laureate|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/1999/may/19/fiachragibbons.michaelwhite|work=The Guardian |date=19 May 1999|accessdate=10 September 2008 | location=London | first=Michael | last=White}}</ref> As he prepared to stand down from the job, Motion published an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'' that concluded, \"To have had 10 years working as laureate has been remarkable. Sometimes it's been remarkably difficult, the laureate has to take a lot of flak, one way or another. More often it has been remarkably fulfilling. I'm glad I did it, and I'm glad I'm giving it up \u2013 especially since I mean to continue working for poetry.\"\n<ref name=\"Lau rels\">Motion, Andrew (21 March 2009). [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/mar/21/andrew-motion-poet-laureate \"Yet once more, O ye laurels\"]. ''The Guardian'', Access date  2009-03-21.</ref><ref>Harper and Sullivan (2009), ''The Creative Environments: Authors at Work''. Woodbridge: Boydell and Brewer.</ref>\n\nMotion spent his last day as Poet Laureate holding a creative writing class at his alma mater, [[Radley College]], before giving a poetry reading and thanking Peter Way, the man who taught him English at Radley, for making him who he was. [[Carol Ann Duffy]] succeeded him as Poet Laureate on 1 May 2009.\n\n===Post-laureateship===\nMotion is Chairman of the Arts Council of England's Literature Panel (appointed 1996) and is also a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]].<ref Name= \"AM\"/> In 2003, he became Professor of Creative Writing at [[Royal Holloway]], [[University of London]].<ref>[http://www.rhul.ac.uk/english/studying/Postgraduate-Study/MA/CreativeWriting.htm Royal Holloway University site] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609174350/http://www.rhul.ac.uk/english/studying/Postgraduate-Study/MA/CreativeWriting.htm |date=9 June 2010 }}. Accessed 2010-08-17</ref> Since July 2009, Motion has been Chairman of the [[Museums, Libraries and Archives Council]] (MLA) appointed by the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]].<ref Name= \"AM\"/><ref>[http://www.culture.gov.uk/reference_library/media_releases/5237.aspx]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214233100/http://www.culture.gov.uk/reference_library/media_releases/5237.aspx |date=14 February 2009 }}</ref> He is also a Vice-President of the [[Friends of the British Library]], a charity which provides funding support to the [[British Library]].<ref name=\"ar0607\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bl.uk/supportus/pdf/friendsannrep0607.pdf|title=Friends of the British Library Annual Report 2006/07| accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> He was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the 2009 Queen's Birthday Honours list.<ref Name= \"AM\"/> He has been a member of [[English Heritage]]'s Blue Plaques Panel since 2008.\n\nMotion was selected as jury chair for the [[Man Booker Prize]] 2010<ref>[http://www.themanbookerprize.com/prize/thisyear/judges]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103002735/http://www.themanbookerprize.com/prize/thisyear/judges |date=3 January 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=59090 |date=13 June 2009 |page=1 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8097237.stm|title=BBC News|publisher=|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> and in March 2010, he announced that he was working with publishers [[Jonathan Cape]] on a sequel to [[Robert Louis Stevenson]]'s ''[[Treasure Island]]''. Entitled ''Silver'', the story is set a generation on from the original book and was published in March 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/arts_and_culture/8588371.stm|title=Sir Andrew Motion to write Treasure Island sequel |date=26 March 2010|work=BBC News|accessdate=26 March 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100329135349/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/arts_and_culture/8588371.stm| archivedate= 29 March 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In July 2010, Motion returned to [[Kingston-upon-Hull]] for the annual ''Humber Mouth'' literature festival and taking part in the [[Larkin 25]] festival commemorating the 25th anniversary of [[Philip Larkin]]'s death. In his capacity as Larkin's biographer and as a former lecturer in English at the [[University of Hull]], Motion named an [[East Yorkshire Motor Services]] bus ''Philip Larkin''.<ref>''Yorkshire Evening Post'' 6 July 2010 [http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/localnews/Buses-are-fare-way-to.6403079.jp \"Buses are fare way to celebrate city poet\"] (Retrieved 7 July 2010)</ref><ref>[http://www.larkin25.co.uk/news.php Larkin 25. 7 July 2010. ''Welcome aboard the Philip Larkin bus!'' ](Retrieved 12 July 2010)</ref> Motion's debut play ''[[Incoming (play)|Incoming]]'', about the war in Afghanistan, premi\u00e8red at the High Tides Festival in [[Halesworth]], Suffolk in May 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-news/8335508/Andrew-Motion-to-debut-as-playwright-with-work-about-Afghanistan.html |title=Andrew Motion to debut as playwright with work about Afghanistan - Telegraph |first=Roya |last=Nikkhah |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=20 February 2010 |location=[[London, UK|London]] |issn=0307-1235 |oclc=49632006 |accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref> Motion also featured in ''[[Jamie's Dream School]]'' in 2011 as the poetry teacher.\n\nIn June 2012, he became the President of the [[Campaign to Protect Rural England]]. In March 2014 he was elected an Honorary Fellow at [[Homerton College, Cambridge]].\n\nMotion won the 2015 [[Ted Hughes Award]] for new work in poetry for the radio programme ''Coming Home''. The production featured poetry by Motion based on recordings he made of British soldiers returning from the wars in [[Iraq]] and [[Afghanistan]].<ref>Mark Brown, [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/apr/02/andrew-motion-wins-ted-hughes-award-poetry-returning-soldiers Andrew Motion wins Ted Hughes award for poetry work about returning soldiers], The Guardian, 2 April 2015.</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Motion moved to Baltimore, Maryland to take up a post at the [[Johns Hopkins Writing Seminars|Writing Seminars]] as a Homewood Professor of the Arts at [[Johns Hopkins University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://hub.jhu.edu/at-work/2016/01/11/andrew-motion|title= British poet Andrew Motion settles into life in America as a professor at Johns Hopkins|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Work==\nMotion has said of himself: \"My wish to write a poem is inseparable from my wish to explain something to myself.\" His work combines lyrical and narrative aspects in a \"postmodern-romantic sensibility\".<ref Name=\"BC\"/> Motion says that he aims to write in clear language without tricks.<ref Name=\"BC\"/>\n\n''[[The Independent]]'' describes the stalwart poet as the \"charming and tireless defender of the art form\".<ref name=\"poetrymatters\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/andrew-motion-poetry-needs-us-to-say-that-it-matters-1669470.html \"Andrew Motion: 'Poetry needs us to say that it matters'\"]. ''The Independent'', 17 April 2009. Accessed 18 July 2010</ref> Motion has won the [[Arvon Foundation|Arvon]] Prize, the [[John Llewellyn Rhys Prize]], [[Eric Gregory Award]], [[1994 Whitbread Awards|Whitbread Prize for Biography]] and the [[Dylan Thomas Prize]].<ref Name= \"AM\"/><ref Name=\"BC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth76 |title=British Council Biography |accessdate=12 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001130129/http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth76 |archivedate=1 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nMotion took part in the [[Bush Theatre]]'s 2011 project ''[[Sixty-Six Books]]'', writing and performing a piece based upon a book of the ''[[King James Version|King James Bible]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |title=Bush Theatre |accessdate=12 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704090950/http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |archivedate=4 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMotion's marriage to Joanna Powell ended in 1983.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/andrew-motion-poetic-licence-to-thrill-413487.html \"Andrew Motion: Poetic licence to thrill\"]. ''The Independent'', 27 August 2006.</ref> He was married to Jan Dalley from 1985 to 2009, divorcing after a seven-year separation. They had one son born in 1986 and twins, a son and a daughter, born in 1988. In 2009 he married Kyeong-Soo Kim. He currently lives part of the year in Baltimore, Maryland.\n\n==Selected honours and awards==\n* 1975: won the [[Newdigate prize]] for Oxford undergraduate poetry\n* 1976: [[Eric Gregory Award]]\n* 1981: wins [[Arvon Foundation]]'s International Poetry Competition with ''The Letter''\n* 1984:  [[John Llewellyn Rhys Prize]] for ''Dangerous Play: Poems 1974\u20131984''\n* 1987: [[Somerset Maugham Award]] for ''The Lamberts''\n* 1987:  [[Dylan Thomas Prize]] for ''Natural Causes''\n* 1999: appointed [[Poet Laureate]] for ten years\n* 1994: ''Philip Larkin: A Writer\u2019s Life'', [[1994 Whitbread Awards|Whitbread Prize for Biography]]\n* 2009:  [[Knight Bachelor]]\n* 2014:  Wilfred Owen Poetry Award\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=July 2018}}\n\n=== Poetry ===\n;Collections\n*{{cite book |author=Motion, Andrew |authormask=  |title=Goodnestone : a sequence |location= |publisher=Workshop Press |year=1972 |<!--isbn=-->}}\n*{{cite book |author=Motion, Andrew |authormask=1 |title=Inland |location= |publisher=Cygnet Press |year=1976 |<!--isbn=-->}}\n* 1977: ''The Pleasure Steamers''. Carcanet\n* 1981: ''Independence''. Salamander Press\n* 1983: ''Secret Narratives''. Salamander Press\n* 1984: ''Dangerous Play: Poems 1974\u20131984.'' Salamander Press / Penguin\n* 1987: ''Natural Causes''. Chatto & Windus\n* 1988: ''Two Poems''. Words Ltd\n* 1991: ''Love in a Life''. Faber and Faber\n* 1994: ''The Price of Everything.'' Faber and Faber\n* 1997: ''Salt Water'' Faber and Faber\n* 1998: ''Selected Poems 1976\u20131997''. Faber and Faber\n* 2001: ''A Long Story''. The Old School Press\n* 2002: ''Public Property''. Faber and Faber\n* 2009: ''The Cinder Path''. Faber and Faber\n* 2012: ''The Customs House''. Faber and Faber\n* 2015: ''Peace Talks''. Faber and Faber\n* 2015: ''Coming Home''. Published by Andrew J Moorhouse at Fine Press Poetry http://www.finepresspoetry.com\n* Coming in to Land: Selected Poems, 1975\u20132015\n*2018: ''Essex Clay''. Faber and Faber\n\n;List of poems\n{|class='wikitable sortable' width='90%'\n|-\n!width=25%|Title\n!|Year\n!|First published\n!|Reprinted/collected\n|-\n|A Cabbage White\n|2018\n|{{cite journal |author=Motion, Andrew |authormask= |date=February 22, 2018 |title=A Cabbage White |department= |journal=The New York Review of Books |volume=65 |issue=3 |pages=18}}\n|\n|-\n|Chincoteague\n|2018\n|{{cite journal |author=Motion, Andrew |authormask= |date=February 22, 2018 |title=Chincoteague |department= |journal=The New York Review of Books |volume=65 |issue=3 |pages=24}}\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Criticism===\n* 1980: ''The Poetry of [[Edward Thomas (poet)|Edward Thomas]]''.   Routledge & Kegan Paul\n* 1982: ''[[Philip Larkin]]''. (Contemporary Writers series) Methuen\n* 1986: ''[[Elizabeth Bishop]]. (Chatterton Lectures on an English Poet)''\n* 1998: ''Sarah Raphael: Strip!''. Marlborough Fine Art (London)\n* 2008: ''Ways of Life: On Places, Painters and Poets''. Faber and Faber\n\n===Biography===\n* 1986: ''The Lamberts: [[George Washington Lambert|George]], [[Constant Lambert|Constant]] and [[Kit Lambert|Kit]]''. Chatto & Windus\n* 1993: ''[[Philip Larkin]]: A Writer's Life''. Faber and Faber\n* 1997: ''[[John Keats|Keats]]: A Biography''. Faber and Faber\n\n===Memoirs===\n* 2006: ''In the Blood: A Memoir of my Childhood''. Faber and Faber\n\n===Fiction===\n* 1989: ''The Pale Companion''. Penguin\n* 1991: ''Famous for the Creatures''. Viking\n* 2003: ''The Invention of Dr Cake''. Faber and Faber\n* 2000: ''Wainewright the Poisoner: The Confessions of [[Thomas Griffiths Wainewright]]'' ([[biographical novel]])\n* 2012: ''[[Silver (Andrew Motion novel)|Silver]]''. Jonathan Cape\n* 2015: ''The New World''. Crown\n\n===Edited works, introductions, and forewords===\n* 1981: ''Selected Poems: [[William Barnes]]''. Penguin Classics\n* 1982: ''The Penguin Book of Contemporary British Poetry'' with [[Blake Morrison]]. Penguin\n* 1994: ''[[Thomas Hardy]]: Selected Poems''. Dent\n* 1993: ''New Writing 2'' (With [[Malcolm Bradbury]]). Minerva in association with the British Council\n* 1994: ''New Writing 3'' (With Candice Rodd). Minerva in association with the British Council\n* 1997: ''Penguin Modern Poets: Volume 11''  with [[Michael Donaghy]] and [[Hugo Williams]]. Penguin\n* 1998: ''Take 20: New Writing''. University of East Anglia\n* 1999: ''Verses of the Poets Laureate: From [[John Dryden]] to Andrew Motion''. With Hilary Laurie. Orion.\n* 1999: ''Babel: New Writing by the University of East Anglia's MA Writers''. University of East Anglia.\n* 2001: ''Firsthand: The New Anthology of Creative Writing from the University of East Anglia''. University of East Anglia\n* 2002: ''Paper Scissors Stone: New Writing from the MA in Creative Writing at [[University of East Anglia|UEA]]''. University of East Anglia.\n* 2001: ''The Creative Writing Coursebook: Forty Authors Share Advice and Exercises for Fiction & Poetry''. With Julia Bell. Macmillan\n* 2000: ''[[John Keats]]: Poems Selected by Andrew Motion''. Faber and Faber\n* 2001: ''Here to Eternity: An Anthology of Poetry''. Faber and Faber\n* 2002: ''[[May Anthologies|The Mays Literary Anthology]]''; Guest editor. Varsity Publications\n* 2003: ''101 Poems Against War ''. Faber and Faber (Afterword)\n* 2003: ''First World War Poems''. Faber and Faber\n* 2006: ''Collins Rhyming Dictionary''. Collins\n* 2007: ''Bedford Square 2: New Writing from the Royal Holloway Creative Writing Programme''. John Murray Ltd.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Andrew Motion}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.poetryarchive.org/poetryarchive/singlePoet.do?poetId=212 Profile and poems written and audio] at the Poetry Archive\n* [http://www.poets.org/poet.php/prmPID/2096 Profile at Poets.org]\n* [http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/saction.php?search=ss&firstRun=true&sText=%22andrew+motion%22 National Portrait Gallery portraits]\n* {{British council|id=andrew-motion|name=Professor Andrew Motion}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/education/2005/dec/13/highereducationprofile.highereducation?INTCMP=SRCH ''Guardian''] profile 13 December 2005 \"Andrew Motion: Mr Speaker\".  [https://www.theguardian.com/books/video/2009/apr/27/andrew-motion-poetry?INTCMP=SRCH ''Guardian''] \"Andrew Motion on war poetry\". Interview and reading. 27 July 2009 (Video, 8 mins)\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/audiointerviews/profilepages/motiona1.shtml BBC] profile. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/learningzone/clips/andrew-motion-on-being-poet-laureate/6957.html BBC interview] \"Andrew Motion on being Poet Laureate\" (Video, 4 mins). [https://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/1DxnakmMR96M_jQOhA_BJw BBC interview] \"Andrew Motion's Hindu Wood Carving\" (Video 4 mins)\n* [http://www.press.uchicago.edu/Misc/Chicago/542409.html A chapter] from ''Keats,'' about John Keats, Fanny Brawne, and his poem for her, \"Bright Star\"\n* {{YouTube|id=w54DO8PHzSw|title=Bonfire of the Humanities}}, Andrew Motion's Romanes Lecture (2011) at Oxford University (video)\n\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n\n{{Poets Laureate of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Motion, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century biographers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century biographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Academics of Royal Holloway, University of London]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of East Anglia]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Hull]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British Poets Laureate]]\n[[Category:English biographers]]\n[[Category:English book editors]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:People educated at Radley College]]\n[[Category:People from Braintree, Essex]]\n[[Category:The New York Review of Books people]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Motion"}
{"title_page": "Howard Jacobson", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Howard Jacobson\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| pseudonym   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1942|8|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Manchester]], England\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Novelist, columnist, broadcaster\n| nationality = British\n| period      = 1983\u2013present\n| genre       = Biographical\n| subject     = [[Jewishness]], humour\n| movement    = \n| spouse      = Barbara Starr (m. 1964)<br />Rosalin Sadler (1978\u20132004)<br />Jenny De Yong (m. 2005)\n| awards      = [[Man Booker Prize]] (2010)\n| alma_mater  = [[Downing College, Cambridge]]\n| signature   = \n| website     = \n| imagesize   = \n}}\n'''Howard Eric Jacobson''' (born 25 August 1942) is a British novelist and journalist. He is known for writing [[comic novel]]s that often revolve around the dilemmas of [[British Jews|British Jewish]] characters.<ref name=Ragi>Ragi, K. R., \"Howard Jacobson's ''The Finkler Question'' as a Post-Holocaust Fiction\", in ''Labyrinth: An International Refereed Journal of Postmodern Studies''. July 2014, vol. 5, issue 3, pp. 50-55.</ref> He is a [[Man Booker Prize]] winner.\n\n==Early life==\nJacobson was born in [[Manchester]] and was brought up in [[Prestwich]]. He was educated at [[Philips High School|Stand Grammar School]] in [[Whitefield, Greater Manchester]]<ref name=\"Anon2010\">{{cite news|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1345492_howard_jacobson_wins_the_booker_prize__and_thanks_his_whitefield_school|title=Howard Jacobson wins the Booker Prize \u2013 and thanks his Whitefield school|last=Anon|date=13 October 2010|work=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=16 December 2010}}</ref> before going on to study English at [[Downing College, Cambridge]], under [[F. R. Leavis]].<ref name=\"Pearson\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3593433/Howard-Jacobson.html|title=Howard Jacobson|last=Pearson|first=Allison|date=27 April 2003|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=12 October 2010|location=London}}</ref> He graduated with a 2:2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/donald-trump-how-can-anyone-exist-and-be-so-dumb/|title=Donald Trump? How can anyone exist and be so dumb?|date=2017-04-15|website=The Spectator|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n\nHe lectured for three years at the [[University of Sydney]] before returning to Britain to teach at [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]]. His later teaching posts included a period at [[University of Wolverhampton|Wolverhampton Polytechnic]] from 1974 to 1980.<ref>''International who's who of authors and writers'', London: Europa Publications, 2003, p.271</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJacobson's time at Wolverhampton was to form the basis of his first novel, ''Coming from Behind'', a [[campus novel|campus comedy]] about a failing [[polytechnic (United Kingdom)|polytechnic]] that plans to merge facilities with a local [[football club]]. The episode of teaching in a football stadium in the novel is, according to Jacobson in a 1985 BBC interview, the only portion of the novel based on a true incident. He also wrote a travel book in 1987, titled ''In the Land of Oz'', which was researched during his time as a visiting academic in Sydney.\n\nJacobson's fiction, particularly in the six novels he has published since 1998, is characterised chiefly by a discursive and humorous style<ref name=Ragi/> Recurring subjects in his work include [[Intimate relationship|male\u2013female relations]] and the Jewish experience in Britain in the mid- to late-20th century. He has been compared to prominent Jewish-American novelists such as [[Philip Roth]], in particular for his habit of creating [[doppelg\u00e4nger]]s of himself in his fiction.\n\nHis 1999 novel ''The Mighty Walzer'', about a teenage [[table tennis]] champion, won the [[Bollinger Everyman Wodehouse Prize]] for comic writing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pgwodehousesociety.org.uk/clipboard_archive.htm |title=Clipboard Archive \u2013 The Everyman Launch |publisher=The P G Wodehouse Society (UK) |accessdate=20 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321145921/http://www.pgwodehousesociety.org.uk/clipboard_archive.htm |archive-date=21 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is set in the Manchester of the 1950s and Jacobson, himself a table tennis fan in his teenage years, admits that there is more than an element of autobiography in it.<ref name=somethingjewish/> His 2002 novel ''Who's Sorry Now?'' \u2013 the central character of which is a Jewish luggage [[business magnate|baron]] of [[South London]] \u2013 and his 2006 novel ''Kalooki Nights'' were longlisted for the [[Man Booker Prize]]. Jacobson described ''Kalooki Nights'' as \"the most Jewish novel that has ever been written by anybody, anywhere\".<ref name=\"Wides\">{{cite web|last=Wides|first=Cara|title=Something Jewish: \"Howard Jacobson Talking\"|url=http://www.somethingjewish.co.uk/articles/1730_howard_jacobson_talk.htm|accessdate=7 April 2009}}</ref> It won the 2007 [[JQ Wingate Prize]].<ref>[http://www.jewishquarterly.org/issuearchive/wingateprize4.shtml \"Winner of the 2007 Wingate Literary Prize\"]</ref>\n\nAs well as writing fiction, he also contributes a weekly column for ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper as an [[op-ed]] writer. In recent times, he has, on several occasions, attacked anti-Israel boycotts, and for this reason has been labelled a \"liberal Zionist\".<ref name=\"White\">{{cite web|last=White|first=Ben|title=The Electronic Intifada, \"Shoot and Cry: Liberal Zionism's Dilemma,\" (2007-09-20)|url=http://electronicintifada.net/v2/article8992.shtml|accessdate=7 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010 Jacobson won the Man Booker Prize for his novel ''[[The Finkler Question]]'', which was the first comic novel to win the prize since [[Kingsley Amis|Kingsley Amis's]] ''[[The Old Devils]]'' in 1986.<ref name=\"McKie2010\">{{cite news|url=http://caledonianmercury.com/2010/10/14/the-light-hearted-too-often-leave-award-ceremonies-light-handed/001083|title=The light-hearted too often leave award ceremonies light-handed|last=McKie|first=John|date=14 October 2010|work=[[Caledonian Mercury]]|accessdate=16 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602032411/http://caledonianmercury.com/2010/10/14/the-light-hearted-too-often-leave-award-ceremonies-light-handed/001083|archivedate=2 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The book, published by Bloomsbury, explores what it means to be Jewish today and is also about \"love, loss and male friendship\".<ref name=\"Booker\"/> [[Andrew Motion]], the chair of the judges, said: \"''The Finkler Question'' is a marvellous book: very funny, of course, but also very clever, very sad and very subtle. It is all that it seems to be and much more than it seems to be. A completely worthy winner of this great prize.\"<ref name=\"Booker\">{{cite news|url=http://www.themanbookerprize.com/press-releases/howard-jacobson-wins-man-booker-prize-fiction-2010|title=Howard Jacobson wins the Man Booker Prize for Fiction 2010|date=12 October 2010|publisher=[[Man Booker Prize]]|accessdate=31 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116104657/http://www.themanbookerprize.com/press-releases/howard-jacobson-wins-man-booker-prize-fiction-2010|archivedate=16 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His novel ''Zoo Time'' won the [[Bollinger Everyman Wodehouse Prize]] (2013), Jacobson's second time winning the prize (the first in 1999 for ''The Mighty Walzer'').<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/may/15/howard-jacobson-wins-second-wodehouse-prize |title=Howard Jacobson wins second Wodehouse prize for comic fiction |work=The Guardian |author=Alison Flood |date=15 May 2013 |accessdate=15 May 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Jacobson's novel ''[[J (novel)|J]]'' was shortlisted for the [[2014 Man Booker Prize]].<ref name=bbcshortlist>{{cite web|title=Man Booker Prize: Howard Jacobson makes shortlist|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29123941|website=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=9 September 2014|date=9 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nJacobson has argued that an education in science and technology is more conducive to [[terrorism]] than an education in the arts and social sciences. Commentators on the article suggested that theology was an even stronger motivating force.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/show-me-the-jihadist-with-a-well-thumbed-copy-of-middlemarch-in-his-back-pocket-a6770006.html|title=Show me the jihadist with a well\u2011thumbed copy of Middlemarch in his back pocket|author=Howard Jacobson|date=11 December 2015|website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\nAlthough Jacobson has described himself as \"a Jewish [[Jane Austen]]\" (in response to being described as \"the English Philip Roth\"),<ref name=\"Brown2010\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/oct/12/howard-jacobson-the-finkler-question-booker|title=Howard Jacobson wins Booker prize 2010 for ''The Finkler Question''|last=Brown|first=Mark|date=12 October 2010|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=12 October 2010|location=London}}</ref> he also states, \"I'm not by any means conventionally Jewish. I don't go to [[shul]]. What I feel is that I have a Jewish mind, I have a Jewish intelligence. I feel linked to previous Jewish minds of the past. I don't know what kind of trouble this gets somebody into, a disputatious mind. What a Jew is has been made by the experience of 5,000 years, that's what shapes the Jewish sense of humour, that's what shaped Jewish pugnacity or tenaciousness.\" He maintains that \"comedy is a very important part of what I do.\"<ref name=somethingjewish>{{cite web|last=Manus|first=Elizabeth|title=Something Jewish: \"Howard Jacobson Interview\"|url=http://www.somethingjewish.co.uk/articles/1185_howard_jacobson.htm|accessdate=7 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting==\nJacobson has scripted television programmes including [[Channel 4]]'s ''Howard Jacobson Takes on the Turner'', in 2000, and ''[[The South Bank Show]]'' in 2002, which featured an edition entitled \"Why the Novel Matters\". An earlier profile went out in the series in 1999 and a television documentary entitled \"My Son the Novelist\" preceded it as part of the ''[[Arena (UK TV series)|Arena]]'' series in 1985.<ref name=\"Ref_\">[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/136854 \"Arena: My Son the Novelist\"], BFI Film and TV Database</ref> His two non-fiction books \u2013 ''Roots Schmoots: Journeys Among Jews'' (1993) and ''Seriously Funny: From the Ridiculous to the Sublime'' (1997) \u2013 were turned into television series.\n\nJacobson presented \"Jesus The Jew\", episode one of ''Christianity, A History'', on the UK's [[Channel 4]] in January 2009<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jan/09/christianity-judaism \"Behold! The Jewish Jesus\"] by Howrd Jacobson, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 8 January 2009</ref> and in 2010 he presented \"Creation\", the first part of the [[Channel 4]] series ''The Bible: A History''.<ref name=\"Ref_a\">{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-bible-a-history/4od|title=The Bible: A History|publisher=[[Channel 4]]|accessdate=12 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301091903/http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-bible-a-history/4od |archivedate=2010-03-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 November 2010, Jacobson appeared in an Intelligence Squared debate (stop bashing Christians, Britain is becoming an anti-Christian country) in favour of the motion.<ref name=\"Ref_b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.intelligencesquared.com/events/stop-bashing-christians?SQ_PAINT_LAYOUT_NAME=chapter&start=1304&end=1992&sgmt=76985 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110108023646/http://www.intelligencesquared.com/events/stop-bashing-christians?SQ_PAINT_LAYOUT_NAME=chapter&start=1304&end=1992&sgmt=76985 |archivedate = 8 January 2011 |title=Christianity Is Imperfect \u2013 But Life Is Imperfect |publisher= [[Intelligence Squared]]|accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011 Jacobson appeared on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''. His musical choices included works by [[J. S. Bach]], [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]] and [[Louis Armstrong]] as well as the rare 1964 single \"Look at Me\" by the Whirlwinds. His favourite was \"You\u2019re a Sweetheart\" by [[Al Bowlly]] with [[Lew Stone|Lew Stone and His Band]].<ref name=\"DID\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/3d6310fd#b00y50qk|title=Desert Island Discs: Howard Jacobson|date=6 February 2011|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe wrote and presented the Australian biographical series ''[[Brilliant Creatures (2014 TV series)|Brilliant Creatures]]'' (2014) on four famous expatriate iconoclasts.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/tv/programs/brilliant-creatures-germaine-clive-barry-and-bob/ Brilliant Creatures: Germaine, Clive, Barry & Bob] Official website at [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJacobson has been married three times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/search/united-kingdom-records/birth-marriage-death-and-parish-records?firstname=howard%20e&firstname_variants=true&lastname=jacobson&lastname_variants=true&yearofbirth=1942&yearofbirth_offset=2|title=Find My Past |accessdate=24 Feb 2015}}</ref> Engaged at 21 whilst a student at [[Cambridge]], he married his first wife Barbara in 1964 after graduating, when he was 22. They have a son, Conrad Jacobson, born December 1968. During his time at Cambridge, Barbara attended some of Leavis' seminars with Jacobson. Before leaving Cambridge they attended a party where amongst the guests were the playwright [[Simon Gray]], and [[Germaine Greer]], whose job Jacobson was filling in Sydney.\n\nIn late 1964 Howard and Barbara emigrated to Australia, taking a six-week voyage on [[P&O (company)|P&O]]'s [[SS Oriana (1959)|SS ''Oriana'']]. On arrival, Jacobson took up a lectureship at Sydney University. They returned to Manchester in 1967, living there briefly before moving to London, where Conrad was born. This was followed by Howard teaching at Selwyn College, Cambridge, and running the family business on Cambridge Market selling handbags and leather goods. Jacobson returned to Australia when Conrad was 3 years old. He remained without a teaching post. Jacobson eventually returned to the UK after several years. Barbara divorced him in his absence. They share a granddaughter Ziva, born in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/10118957/Howard-Jacobsons-world-Jewishness-magic-and-wine.html|title=Howard Jacobson's world: Jewishness, magic and wine|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=14 June 2013 |accessdate=24 Feb 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jun/25/fiction.featuresl|title=Howard Jacobson's world: Jewishness, magic and wine |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=14 June 2013 |accessdate=24 Feb 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe married his second wife, Rosalin Sadler, in 1978; they divorced in 2004. In 2005, Jacobson was married for the third time, to radio and TV documentary maker Jenny De Yong. He stated, \"My last wife. I'm home, it's right\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Polly Vernon|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/sep/07/relationships.women|title=Love. Sex. Marriage. Affairs. \u2013 Novelist Howard Jacobson on why jealousy is at the dark heart of male sexual passion|work=[[The Observer]]|accessdate=11 August 2019|location=London|date=7 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n\nIn August 2014, Jacobson was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' urging Scots to vote against [[Scottish independence|independence]] in the run-up to the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text |title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories &#124; Politics |publisher=theguardian.com |date=2014-08-07 |accessdate=2014-08-26}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Jacobson joined [[Simon Sebag Montefiore]] and [[Simon Schama]] in writing a letter to the ''[[The Times]]'' about their concern over [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism in the Labour Party]] under [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s leadership, with particular reference to a growth in [[Anti-Zionism]] and its \"antisemitic characteristics\". Schama and Sebag Montefiore have both written historical works about Israel, while Jacobson has written regularly about Israel and the UK Jewish community in his newspaper columns.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/simon-schama-simon-sebag-montefiore-and-howard-jacobson-unite-to-condemn-labour-antisemitism-1.447432 |title=Schama, Sebag-Montefiore and Jacobson unite to condemn Labour antisemitism |work=The Jewish Chronicle | first=Daniel | last=Sugarman | date=6 November 2017 |accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref> Jacobson made a further criticism of the party in July 2019, when he joined other leading Jewish figures in saying, in a letter to ''The Guardian'', that the crisis was \"a taint of international and historic shame\" and that trust in the party was \"fractured beyond repair\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/14/jewish-intellectuals-express-outrage-over-labours-handling-of-antisemitism-crisis |title=Jewish figures rail against Labour\u2019s handling of antisemitism charges |work=The Guardian | first=Stefan | last=Boscia | date=14 July 2019 |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''Fiction'''\n* ''Coming From Behind'', Chatto & Windus, 1983\n* ''Peeping Tom'', Chatto & Windus, 1984\n* ''Redback'', Bantam, 1986\n* ''The Very Model of a Man'', Viking, 1992\n* ''No More Mister Nice Guy'', Cape, 1998\n* ''The Mighty Walzer'', Cape, 1999\n* ''Who's Sorry Now?'', Cape, 2002\n* ''The Making of Henry'', Cape, 2004\n* ''Kalooki Nights'', Cape, 2006\n* ''The Act of Love'', Cape, 2008\n* ''[[The Finkler Question]]'', Bloomsbury, 2010 (Winner of the 2010 [[Man Booker Prize]])\n* ''Zoo Time'', Bloomsbury, 2012\n* ''[[J (novel)|J]]'', Bloomsbury, 2014 (shortlisted for the [[2014 Man Booker Prize]])<ref name=bbcshortlist/>\n* ''Shylock Is My Name'': a novel, Hogarth 2016\n* ''Pussy'': a novel, Cape, April 13, 2017\n* ''Live a Little'', Cape, 2019<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/jul/08/live-a-little-howard-jacobson-review|title=''Live a Little'' by Howard Jacobson review \u2013 wonderful|author=Tim Adams|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n'''Non-fiction'''\n* ''Shakespeare's Magnanimity: Four Tragic Heroes, Their Friends and Families'' (co-author with Wilbur Sanders), Chatto & Windus, 1978\n* ''In the Land of Oz'', Hamish Hamilton, 1987\n* ''Roots Schmoots: Journeys Among Jews'', Viking, 1993\n* ''Seriously Funny: From the Ridiculous to the Sublime'', Viking, 1997\n* ''Whatever It Is, I Don't Like It'', Bloomsbury, 2011\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.open.edu/openlearn/history-the-arts/culture/literature-and-creative-writing/creative-writing/howard-jacobson-on-creating-characters Audio: Writing Lab interview with Howard Jacobson] from ''[[OpenLearn]]''\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1246_the_forum/page29.shtml Audio: Howard Jacobson in conversation] on the BBC World Service discussion show ''[[The Forum (radio programme)|The Forum]]''\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/06/opinion/labour-jeremy-corbym-anti-semitism.html \"The Phony Peace Between the Labour Party and Jews\"] from ''[[The New York Times]]''.\n\n{{Booker Prize|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacobson, Howard}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Wolverhampton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Downing College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Jewish novelists]]\n[[Category:British Jewish writers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Booker Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Prestwich]]\n[[Category:Writers from Manchester]]\n[[Category:The Independent people]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Stand Grammar School]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Howard Jacobson\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| pseudonym   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1942|8|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Manchester]], England\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Novelist, columnist, broadcaster\n| nationality = British\n| period      = 1983\u2013present\n| genre       = Biographical\n| subject     = [[Jewishness]], humour\n| movement    = \n| spouse      = Barbara Starr (m. 1964)<br />Rosalin Sadler (1978\u20132004)<br />Jenny De Yong (m. 2005)\n| awards      = [[Man Booker Prize]] (2010)\n| alma_mater  = [[Downing College, Cambridge]]\n| signature   = \n| website     = \n| imagesize   = \n}}\n'''Howard Eric Jacobson''' (born 25 August 1942) is a British novelist and journalist. He is known for writing [[comic novel]]s that often revolve around the dilemmas of [[British Jews|British Jewish]] characters.<ref name=Ragi>Ragi, K. R., \"Howard Jacobson's ''The Finkler Question'' as a Post-Holocaust Fiction\", in ''Labyrinth: An International Refereed Journal of Postmodern Studies''. July 2014, vol. 5, issue 3, pp. 50-55.</ref> He is a [[Man Booker Prize]] winner.\n\n==Early life==\nJacobson was born in [[Manchester]] and was brought up in [[Prestwich]]. He was educated at [[Philips High School|Stand Grammar School]] in [[Whitefield, Greater Manchester]]<ref name=\"Anon2010\">{{cite news|url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/s/1345492_howard_jacobson_wins_the_booker_prize__and_thanks_his_whitefield_school|title=Howard Jacobson wins the Booker Prize \u2013 and thanks his Whitefield school|last=Anon|date=13 October 2010|work=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=16 December 2010}}</ref> before going on to study English at [[Downing College, Cambridge]], under [[F. R. Leavis]].<ref name=\"Pearson\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3593433/Howard-Jacobson.html|title=Howard Jacobson|last=Pearson|first=Allison|date=27 April 2003|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=12 October 2010|location=London}}</ref> He graduated with a 2:2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/04/donald-trump-how-can-anyone-exist-and-be-so-dumb/|title=Donald Trump? How can anyone exist and be so dumb?|date=2017-04-15|website=The Spectator|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n\nHe lectured for three years at the [[University of Sydney]] before returning to Britain to teach at [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]]. His later teaching posts included a period at [[University of Wolverhampton|Wolverhampton Polytechnic]] from 1974 to 1980.<ref>''International who's who of authors and writers'', London: Europa Publications, 2003, p.271</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJacobson's time at Wolverhampton was to form the basis of his first novel, ''Coming from Behind'', a [[campus novel|campus comedy]] about a failing [[polytechnic (United Kingdom)|polytechnic]] that plans to merge facilities with a local [[football club]]. The episode of teaching in a football stadium in the novel is, according to Jacobson in a 1985 BBC interview, the only portion of the novel based on a true incident. He also wrote a travel book in 1987, titled ''In the Land of Oz'', which was researched during his time as a visiting academic in Sydney.\n\nJacobson's fiction, particularly in the six novels he has published since 1998, is characterised chiefly by a discursive and humorous style<ref name=Ragi/> Recurring subjects in his work include [[Intimate relationship|male\u2013female relations]] and the Jewish experience in Britain in the mid- to late-20th century. He has been compared to prominent Jewish-American novelists such as [[Philip Roth]], in particular for his habit of creating [[doppelg\u00e4nger]]s of himself in his fiction.\n\nHis 1999 novel ''The Mighty Walzer'', about a teenage [[table tennis]] champion, won the [[Bollinger Everyman Wodehouse Prize]] for comic writing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pgwodehousesociety.org.uk/clipboard_archive.htm |title=Clipboard Archive \u2013 The Everyman Launch |publisher=The P G Wodehouse Society (UK) |accessdate=20 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321145921/http://www.pgwodehousesociety.org.uk/clipboard_archive.htm |archive-date=21 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is set in the Manchester of the 1950s and Jacobson, himself a table tennis fan in his teenage years, admits that there is more than an element of autobiography in it.<ref name=somethingjewish/> His 2002 novel ''Who's Sorry Now?'' \u2013 the central character of which is a Jewish luggage [[business magnate|baron]] of [[South London]] \u2013 and his 2006 novel ''Kalooki Nights'' were longlisted for the [[Man Booker Prize]]. Jacobson described ''Kalooki Nights'' as \"the most Jewish novel that has ever been written by anybody, anywhere\".<ref name=\"Wides\">{{cite web|last=Wides|first=Cara|title=Something Jewish: \"Howard Jacobson Talking\"|url=http://www.somethingjewish.co.uk/articles/1730_howard_jacobson_talk.htm|accessdate=7 April 2009}}</ref> It won the 2007 [[JQ Wingate Prize]].<ref>[http://www.jewishquarterly.org/issuearchive/wingateprize4.shtml \"Winner of the 2007 Wingate Literary Prize\"]</ref>\n\nAs well as writing fiction, he also contributes a weekly column for ''[[The Independent]]'' newspaper as an [[op-ed]] writer. In recent times, he has, on several occasions, attacked anti-Israel boycotts, and for this reason has been labelled a \"liberal Zionist\".<ref name=\"White\">{{cite web|last=White|first=Ben|title=The Electronic Intifada, \"Shoot and Cry: Liberal Zionism's Dilemma,\" (2007-09-20)|url=http://electronicintifada.net/v2/article8992.shtml|accessdate=7 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010 Jacobson won the Man Booker Prize for his novel ''[[The Finkler Question]]'', which was the first comic novel to win the prize since [[Kingsley Amis|Kingsley Amis's]] ''[[The Old Devils]]'' in 1986.<ref name=\"McKie2010\">{{cite news|url=http://caledonianmercury.com/2010/10/14/the-light-hearted-too-often-leave-award-ceremonies-light-handed/001083|title=The light-hearted too often leave award ceremonies light-handed|last=McKie|first=John|date=14 October 2010|work=[[Caledonian Mercury]]|accessdate=16 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602032411/http://caledonianmercury.com/2010/10/14/the-light-hearted-too-often-leave-award-ceremonies-light-handed/001083|archivedate=2 June 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The book, published by Bloomsbury, explores what it means to be Jewish today and is also about \"love, loss and male friendship\".<ref name=\"Booker\"/> [[Andrew Motion]], the chair of the judges, said: \"''The Finkler Question'' is a marvellous book: very funny, of course, but also very clever, very sad and very subtle. It is all that it seems to be and much more than it seems to be. A completely worthy winner of this great prize.\"<ref name=\"Booker\">{{cite news|url=http://www.themanbookerprize.com/press-releases/howard-jacobson-wins-man-booker-prize-fiction-2010|title=Howard Jacobson wins the Man Booker Prize for Fiction 2010|date=12 October 2010|publisher=[[Man Booker Prize]]|accessdate=31 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116104657/http://www.themanbookerprize.com/press-releases/howard-jacobson-wins-man-booker-prize-fiction-2010|archivedate=16 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His novel ''Zoo Time'' won the [[Bollinger Everyman Wodehouse Prize]] (2013), Jacobson's second time winning the prize (the first in 1999 for ''The Mighty Walzer'').<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/may/15/howard-jacobson-wins-second-wodehouse-prize |title=Howard Jacobson wins second Wodehouse prize for comic fiction |work=The Guardian |author=Alison Flood |date=15 May 2013 |accessdate=15 May 2013 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Jacobson's novel ''[[J (novel)|J]]'' was shortlisted for the [[2014 Man Booker Prize]].<ref name=bbcshortlist>{{cite web|title=Man Booker Prize: Howard Jacobson makes shortlist|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29123941|website=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=9 September 2014|date=9 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nJacobson has argued that an education in science and technology is more conducive to [[terrorism]] than an education in the arts and social sciences. Commentators on the article suggested that theology was an even stronger motivating force.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/show-me-the-jihadist-with-a-well-thumbed-copy-of-middlemarch-in-his-back-pocket-a6770006.html|title=Show me the jihadist with a well\u2011thumbed copy of Middlemarch in his back pocket|author=Howard Jacobson|date=11 December 2015|website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\nAlthough Jacobson has described himself as \"a Jewish [[Jane Austen]]\" (in response to being described as \"the English Philip Roth\"),<ref name=\"Brown2010\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/oct/12/howard-jacobson-the-finkler-question-booker|title=Howard Jacobson wins Booker prize 2010 for ''The Finkler Question''|last=Brown|first=Mark|date=12 October 2010|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=12 October 2010|location=London}}</ref> he also states, \"I'm not by any means conventionally Jewish. I don't go to [[shul]]. What I feel is that I have a Jewish mind, I have a Jewish intelligence. I feel linked to previous Jewish minds of the past. I don't know what kind of trouble this gets somebody into, a disputatious mind. What a Jew is has been made by the experience of 5,000 years, that's what shapes the Jewish sense of humour, that's what shaped Jewish pugnacity or tenaciousness.\" He maintains that \"comedy is a very important part of what I do.\"<ref name=somethingjewish>{{cite web|last=Manus|first=Elizabeth|title=Something Jewish: \"Howard Jacobson Interview\"|url=http://www.somethingjewish.co.uk/articles/1185_howard_jacobson.htm|accessdate=7 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting==\nJacobson has scripted television programmes including [[Channel 4]]'s ''Howard Jacobson Takes on the Turner'', in 2000, and ''[[The South Bank Show]]'' in 2002, which featured an edition entitled \"Why the Novel Matters\". An earlier profile went out in the series in 1999 and a television documentary entitled \"My Son the Novelist\" preceded it as part of the ''[[Arena (UK TV series)|Arena]]'' series in 1985.<ref name=\"Ref_\">[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/136854 \"Arena: My Son the Novelist\"], BFI Film and TV Database</ref> His two non-fiction books \u2013 ''Roots Schmoots: Journeys Among Jews'' (1993) and ''Seriously Funny: From the Ridiculous to the Sublime'' (1997) \u2013 were turned into television series.\n\nJacobson presented \"Jesus The Jew\", episode one of ''Christianity, A History'', on the UK's [[Channel 4]] in January 2009<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jan/09/christianity-judaism \"Behold! The Jewish Jesus\"] by Howrd Jacobson, ''[[The Guardian]]'', 8 January 2009</ref> and in 2010 he presented \"Creation\", the first part of the [[Channel 4]] series ''The Bible: A History''.<ref name=\"Ref_a\">{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-bible-a-history/4od|title=The Bible: A History|publisher=[[Channel 4]]|accessdate=12 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301091903/http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-bible-a-history/4od |archivedate=2010-03-01}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 November 2010, Jacobson appeared in an Intelligence Squared debate (stop bashing Christians, Britain is becoming an anti-Christian country) in favour of the motion.<ref name=\"Ref_b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.intelligencesquared.com/events/stop-bashing-christians?SQ_PAINT_LAYOUT_NAME=chapter&start=1304&end=1992&sgmt=76985 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110108023646/http://www.intelligencesquared.com/events/stop-bashing-christians?SQ_PAINT_LAYOUT_NAME=chapter&start=1304&end=1992&sgmt=76985 |archivedate = 8 January 2011 |title=Christianity Is Imperfect \u2013 But Life Is Imperfect |publisher= [[Intelligence Squared]]|accessdate=29 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011 Jacobson appeared on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''. His musical choices included works by [[J. S. Bach]], [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]] and [[Louis Armstrong]] as well as the rare 1964 single \"Look at Me\" by the Whirlwinds. His favourite was \"You\u2019re a Sweetheart\" by [[Al Bowlly]] with [[Lew Stone|Lew Stone and His Band]].<ref name=\"DID\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/3d6310fd#b00y50qk|title=Desert Island Discs: Howard Jacobson|date=6 February 2011|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=29 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe wrote and presented the Australian biographical series ''[[Brilliant Creatures (2014 TV series)|Brilliant Creatures]]'' (2014) on four famous expatriate iconoclasts.<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/tv/programs/brilliant-creatures-germaine-clive-barry-and-bob/ Brilliant Creatures: Germaine, Clive, Barry & Bob] Official website at [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nJacobson has been married three times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/search/united-kingdom-records/birth-marriage-death-and-parish-records?firstname=howard%20e&firstname_variants=true&lastname=jacobson&lastname_variants=true&yearofbirth=1942&yearofbirth_offset=2|title=Find My Past |accessdate=24 Feb 2015}}</ref> Engaged at 21 whilst a student at [[Cambridge]], he married his first wife Barbara in 1964 after graduating, when he was 22. They have a son, Conrad Jacobson, born December 1968. During his time at Cambridge, Barbara attended some of Leavis' seminars with Jacobson. Before leaving Cambridge they attended a party where amongst the guests were the playwright [[Simon Gray]], and [[Germaine Greer]], whose job Jacobson was filling in Sydney.\n\nIn late 1964 Howard and Barbara emigrated to Australia, taking a six-week voyage on [[P&O (company)|P&O]]'s [[SS Oriana (1959)|SS ''Oriana'']]. On arrival, Jacobson took up a lectureship at Sydney University. They returned to Manchester in 1967, living there briefly before moving to London, where Conrad was born. This was followed by Howard teaching at Selwyn College, Cambridge, and running the family business on Cambridge Market selling handbags and leather goods. Jacobson returned to Australia when Conrad was 3 years old. He remained without a teaching post. Jacobson eventually returned to the UK after several years. Barbara divorced him in his absence. They share a granddaughter Ziva, born in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/10118957/Howard-Jacobsons-world-Jewishness-magic-and-wine.html|title=Howard Jacobson's world: Jewishness, magic and wine|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=14 June 2013 |accessdate=24 Feb 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jun/25/fiction.featuresl|title=Howard Jacobson's world: Jewishness, magic and wine |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=14 June 2013 |accessdate=24 Feb 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe married his second wife, Rosalin Sadler, in 1978; they divorced in 2004. In 2005, Jacobson was married for the third time, to radio and TV documentary maker Jenny De Yong. He stated, \"My last wife. I'm home, it's right\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Polly Vernon|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/sep/07/relationships.women|title=Love. Sex. Marriage. Affairs. \u2013 Novelist Howard Jacobson on why jealousy is at the dark heart of male sexual passion|work=[[The Observer]]|accessdate=11 August 2019|location=London|date=7 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n\nIn August 2014, Jacobson was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' urging Scots to vote against [[Scottish independence|independence]] in the run-up to the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text |title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories &#124; Politics |publisher=theguardian.com |date=2014-08-07 |accessdate=2014-08-26}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Jacobson joined [[Simon Sebag Montefiore]] and [[Simon Schama]] in writing a letter to the ''[[The Times]]'' about their concern over [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism in the Labour Party]] under [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s leadership, with particular reference to a growth in [[Anti-Zionism]] and its \"antisemitic characteristics\". Schama and Sebag Montefiore have both written historical works about Israel, while Jacobson has written regularly about Israel and the UK Jewish community in his newspaper columns.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/simon-schama-simon-sebag-montefiore-and-howard-jacobson-unite-to-condemn-labour-antisemitism-1.447432 |title=Schama, Sebag-Montefiore and Jacobson unite to condemn Labour antisemitism |work=The Jewish Chronicle | first=Daniel | last=Sugarman | date=6 November 2017 |accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref> Jacobson made a further criticism of the party in July 2019, when he joined other leading Jewish figures in saying, in a letter to ''The Guardian'', that the crisis was \"a taint of international and historic shame\" and that trust in the party was \"fractured beyond repair\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/14/jewish-intellectuals-express-outrage-over-labours-handling-of-antisemitism-crisis |title=Jewish figures rail against Labour\u2019s handling of antisemitism charges |work=The Guardian | first=Stefan | last=Boscia | date=14 July 2019 |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''Fiction'''\n* ''Coming From Behind'', Chatto & Windus, 1983\n* ''Peeping Tom'', Chatto & Windus, 1984\n* ''Redback'', Bantam, 1986\n* ''The Very Model of a Man'', Viking, 1992\n* ''No More Mister Nice Guy'', Cape, 1998\n* ''The Mighty Walzer'', Cape, 1999\n* ''Who's Sorry Now?'', Cape, 2002\n* ''The Making of Henry'', Cape, 2004\n* ''Kalooki Nights'', Cape, 2006\n* ''The Act of Love'', Cape, 2008\n* ''[[The Finkler Question]]'', Bloomsbury, 2010 (Winner of the 2010 [[Man Booker Prize]])\n* ''Zoo Time'', Bloomsbury, 2012\n* ''[[J (novel)|J]]'', Bloomsbury, 2014 (shortlisted for the [[2014 Man Booker Prize]])<ref name=bbcshortlist/>\n* ''Shylock Is My Name'': a novel, Hogarth 2016\n* ''Pussy'': a novel, Cape, April 13, 2017\n* ''Live a Little'', Cape, 2019<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/jul/08/live-a-little-howard-jacobson-review|title=''Live a Little'' by Howard Jacobson review \u2013 wonderful|author=Tim Adams|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n'''Non-fiction'''\n* ''Shakespeare's Magnanimity: Four Tragic Heroes, Their Friends and Families'' (co-author with Wilbur Sanders), Chatto & Windus, 1978\n* ''In the Land of Oz'', Hamish Hamilton, 1987\n* ''Roots Schmoots: Journeys Among Jews'', Viking, 1993\n* ''Seriously Funny: From the Ridiculous to the Sublime'', Viking, 1997\n* ''Whatever It Is, I Don't Like It'', Bloomsbury, 2011\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.open.edu/openlearn/history-the-arts/culture/literature-and-creative-writing/creative-writing/howard-jacobson-on-creating-characters Audio: Writing Lab interview with Howard Jacobson] from ''[[OpenLearn]]''\n*[http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1246_the_forum/page29.shtml Audio: Howard Jacobson in conversation] on the BBC World Service discussion show ''[[The Forum (radio programme)|The Forum]]''\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/06/opinion/labour-jeremy-corbym-anti-semitism.html \"The Phony Peace Between the Labour Party and Jews\"] from ''[[The New York Times]]''.\n\n{{Booker Prize|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jacobson, Howard}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Wolverhampton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Downing College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Jewish novelists]]\n[[Category:British Jewish writers]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Booker Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Prestwich]]\n[[Category:Writers from Manchester]]\n[[Category:The Independent people]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Stand Grammar School]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howard_Jacobson"}
{"title_page": "Justin Cartwright", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n'''Justin James Cartwright''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|MBE|FRSL}} (20 May 1943 \u2013 3 December 2018)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kean|first1=Danuta|title=Justin Cartwright obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/dec/20/justin-cartwright-obituary|website=The Guardian|date=20 December 2018}}</ref> was a British novelist, originally from [[South Africa]].\n[[Image:Justin Cartwright.jpg|thumbnail|right|200px|Justin Cartwright]]\n\n==Biography==\nCartwright was born in [[Cape Town]], South Africa,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/south-africa-must-stay-true-to-mandelas-vision-6801563.html|title=South Africa must stay true to Mandela's vision |last=Cartwright |first=Justin|date=8 January 2010|work=London Evening Standard|accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> but grew up in [[Johannesburg]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bookslive.co.za/blog/2012/04/17/justin-cartwright-speaks-to-an-alarmingly-insubstantial-nadine-gordimer/|title=Justin Cartwright Speaks to an \"Alarmingly Insubstantial\" Nadine Gordimer |last=|first=|date=17 April 2012|work=Books Live|accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> where his father was the editor of the ''[[Rand Daily Mail]]'' newspaper. He was educated in South Africa, the United States and at [[Trinity College, Oxford]]. Cartwright worked in advertising and directed documentaries, films and television commercials. He managed election broadcasts, first for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] and then the [[SDP-Liberal Alliance]] during the 1979, 1983 and 1987 British general elections. For his work on election broadcasts, Cartwright was appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]].\n\n[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] presenter [[Ramona Koval]] described Cartwright's novels as being \"based in contemporary settings but he\u2019s able to suffuse them with the big questions that haunt us\". Three of Cartwright's early novels feature a character named Timothy Curtiz, named partly for Kurtz from [[Joseph Conrad]]'s ''[[Heart of Darkness]]'', and partly for Cartwright's own brother. In ''Interior'', Curtiz is in Africa investigating the disappearance of his father in 1959 while on a trip for ''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]''. In ''Look At It This Way'', Curtiz is a columnist for ''Manhattan'' magazine while he is living in [[London]], has a daughter named Gemma, and by the end of the novel has a partner named Victoria. In ''Masai Dreaming'', Curtiz is in Africa researching a film about Claudia Cohn-Casson, and his relationship with Victoria is having \"complications.\" ''Look At It This Way'' was made into a three-part, 180-minutes drama by the [[BBC]] in 1992, starring [[Kristin Scott Thomas]]; Cartwright wrote the screenplay.\n\n''In Every Face I Meet'' was shortlisted for both the [[Booker Prize]] and the [[Whitbread Book Awards|Whitbread Novel Award]] in 1995, and won a [[Commonwealth Writers Prize]]; ''Leading the Cheers'' won the Whitbread Novel Award in 1998; ''White Lightning'' was shortlisted for the Whitbread Novel Award in 2002. ''Masai Dreaming'' won the South African [[M-Net Literary Awards]].\n''The Promise of Happiness'' was chosen as one of ''[[Richard & Judy|Richard and Judy's]]'' Book Club's titles for 2005 and was the winner of the 2005 [[Hawthornden Prize]] and the [[Sunday Times Literary Awards|''Sunday Times'' Fiction Prize]] of South Africa.\n\nCartwright lived in London with his wife, Penny, and two sons.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n* ''Deep Six'' (1972)\n* ''Fighting Men'' (1977)\n* ''Horse of Darius'' (1980) {{ISBN|0-440-13761-6}}\n* ''Freedom for the Wolves'' (1983)\n* ''Interior'' (1988) {{ISBN|0-679-40866-5}}\n* ''Look at it This Way'' (1990) {{ISBN|0-333-54831-0}}\n* ''Masai Dreaming'' (1993) {{ISBN|0-333-59281-6}}\n* ''In Every Face I Meet'' (1995) {{ISBN|0-340-63782-X}}\n* ''Leading the cheers'' (1998) {{ISBN|0-340-63784-6}}\n* ''Half in Love'' (2001) {{ISBN|0-340-76629-8}}\n* ''White Lightning'' (2002) {{ISBN|0-340-82174-4}}\n* ''The Promise of Happiness'' (2005) {{ISBN|0-312-34880-0}}\n* ''The Song Before it is Sung'' (2007)\n* ''To Heaven by Water'' Bloomsbury (2009)\n* [[Other People's Money (novel)|''Other People's Money'']] Bloomsbury (2011) {{ISBN|1-408-81413-7}}\n* ''Lion Heart'' (2013) {{ISBN|9781408839799}}\n* ''Up Against the Night'' (2015, Bloomsbury)\n\n===Non-fiction===\n* ''Not Yet Home'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-85702-526-1}}\n* ''This Secret Garden'' (2008) {{ISBN|0-7475-7961-X}}\n* ''Oxford Revisited'' (2008) {{ISBN|1-59691-093-3}}\n\n===Films===\n* ''[[Rosie Dixon \u2013 Night Nurse]]'' (1978) sex comedy [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0078180/]\n* ''Look at It This Way'' (1992) TV mini-series (novel and adaptation) [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0103479/]\n* ''Q.E.D.'' (producer) (1 episode, 1983) [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1287866/]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bloomsbury.com/uk/search?q=Justin+Cartwright&Gid=1 Justin Cartwright: Bloomsbury publishers page.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091112112508/http://www.theinterviewonline.co.uk/library/books/justin-cartwright-interview.aspx Audio slideshow interview with Justin Cartwright] talking about ''To Heaven by Water'' on The Interview Online\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cartwright, Justin}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:South African male novelists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:People from Johannesburg]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n'''Justin James Cartwright''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|MBE|FRSL}} (20 May 1943 \u2013 3 December 2018)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kean|first1=Danuta|title=Justin Cartwright obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2018/dec/20/justin-cartwright-obituary|website=The Guardian|date=20 December 2018}}</ref> was a British novelist, originally from [[South Africa]].\n[[Image:Justin Cartwright.jpg|thumbnail|right|200px|Justin Cartwright]]\n\n==Biography==\nCartwright was born in [[Cape Town]], South Africa,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/south-africa-must-stay-true-to-mandelas-vision-6801563.html|title=South Africa must stay true to Mandela's vision |last=Cartwright |first=Justin|date=8 January 2010|work=London Evening Standard|accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> but grew up in [[Johannesburg]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bookslive.co.za/blog/2012/04/17/justin-cartwright-speaks-to-an-alarmingly-insubstantial-nadine-gordimer/|title=Justin Cartwright Speaks to an \"Alarmingly Insubstantial\" Nadine Gordimer |last=|first=|date=17 April 2012|work=Books Live|accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> where his father was the editor of the ''[[Rand Daily Mail]]'' newspaper. He was educated in South Africa, the United States and at [[Trinity College, Oxford]]. Cartwright worked in advertising and directed documentaries, films and television commercials. He managed election broadcasts, first for the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] and then the [[SDP-Liberal Alliance]] during the 1979, 1983 and 1987 British general elections. For his work on election broadcasts, Cartwright was appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]].\n\n[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] presenter [[Ramona Koval]] described Cartwright's novels as being \"based in contemporary settings but he\u2019s able to suffuse them with the big questions that haunt us\". Three of Cartwright's early novels feature a character named Timothy Curtiz, named partly for Kurtz from [[Joseph Conrad]]'s ''[[Heart of Darkness]]'', and partly for Cartwright's own brother. In ''Interior'', Curtiz is in Africa investigating the disappearance of his father in 1959 while on a trip for ''[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]]''. In ''Look At It This Way'', Curtiz is a columnist for ''Manhattan'' magazine while he is living in [[London]], has a daughter named Gemma, and by the end of the novel has a partner named Victoria. In ''Masai Dreaming'', Curtiz is in Africa researching a film about Claudia Cohn-Casson, and his relationship with Victoria is having \"complications.\" ''Look At It This Way'' was made into a three-part, 180-minutes drama by the [[BBC]] in 1992, starring [[Kristin Scott Thomas]]; Cartwright wrote the screenplay.\n\n''In Every Face I Meet'' was shortlisted for both the [[Booker Prize]] and the [[Whitbread Book Awards|Whitbread Novel Award]] in 1995, and won a [[Commonwealth Writers Prize]]; ''Leading the Cheers'' won the Whitbread Novel Award in 1998; ''White Lightning'' was shortlisted for the Whitbread Novel Award in 2002. ''Masai Dreaming'' won the South African [[M-Net Literary Awards]].\n''The Promise of Happiness'' was chosen as one of ''[[Richard & Judy|Richard and Judy's]]'' Book Club's titles for 2005 and was the winner of the 2005 [[Hawthornden Prize]] and the [[Sunday Times Literary Awards|''Sunday Times'' Fiction Prize]] of South Africa.\n\nCartwright lived in London with his wife, Penny, and two sons.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Novels===\n* ''Deep Six'' (1972)\n* ''Fighting Men'' (1977)\n* ''Horse of Darius'' (1980) {{ISBN|0-440-13761-6}}\n* ''Freedom for the Wolves'' (1983)\n* ''Interior'' (1988) {{ISBN|0-679-40866-5}}\n* ''Look at it This Way'' (1990) {{ISBN|0-333-54831-0}}\n* ''Masai Dreaming'' (1993) {{ISBN|0-333-59281-6}}\n* ''In Every Face I Meet'' (1995) {{ISBN|0-340-63782-X}}\n* ''Leading the cheers'' (1998) {{ISBN|0-340-63784-6}}\n* ''Half in Love'' (2001) {{ISBN|0-340-76629-8}}\n* ''White Lightning'' (2002) {{ISBN|0-340-82174-4}}\n* ''The Promise of Happiness'' (2005) {{ISBN|0-312-34880-0}}\n* ''The Song Before it is Sung'' (2007)\n* ''To Heaven by Water'' Bloomsbury (2009)\n* [[Other People's Money (novel)|''Other People's Money'']] Bloomsbury (2011) {{ISBN|1-408-81413-7}}\n* ''Lion Heart'' (2013) {{ISBN|9781408839799}}\n* ''Up Against the Night'' (2015, Bloomsbury)\n\n===Non-fiction===\n* ''Not Yet Home'' (1997) {{ISBN|1-85702-526-1}}\n* ''This Secret Garden'' (2008) {{ISBN|0-7475-7961-X}}\n* ''Oxford Revisited'' (2008) {{ISBN|1-59691-093-3}}\n\n===Films===\n* ''[[Rosie Dixon \u2013 Night Nurse]]'' (1978) sex comedy [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0078180/]\n* ''Look at It This Way'' (1992) TV mini-series (novel and adaptation) [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0103479/]\n* ''Q.E.D.'' (producer) (1 episode, 1983) [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1287866/]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bloomsbury.com/uk/search?q=Justin+Cartwright&Gid=1 Justin Cartwright: Bloomsbury publishers page.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091112112508/http://www.theinterviewonline.co.uk/library/books/justin-cartwright-interview.aspx Audio slideshow interview with Justin Cartwright] talking about ''To Heaven by Water'' on The Interview Online\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cartwright, Justin}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:South African male novelists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:People from Johannesburg]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justin_Cartwright"}
{"title_page": "Owen Sheers", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| name = Owen Sheers\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Sheers in 2014\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1974|09|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Suva]], Fiji\n| occupation = Poet, author, playwright, TV presenter\n| language = English\n| nationality = Welsh\n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| period = 1999\u2013present\n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = {{Plainlist |\n* ''The Dust Diaries'' (2004)\n* ''Skirrid Hill'' (2005)\n* ''Pink Mist'' (2013)}}\n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Eric Gregory Award]], 1999\n* [[Wales Book of the Year]], 2005\n* [[Somerset Maugham Award]], 2006\n* [[Wales Book of the Year]], 2014}}\n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| module = \n| website = {{URL|www.owensheers.co.uk}}\n| portaldisp = \n}}\n\n'''Owen Sheers''' (born 20 September 1974) is a Welsh poet, author, playwright and TV presenter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.poetryarchive.org/poetryarchive/singlePoet.do?poetId=5918 |title=Owen Sheers b. 1974 |website=[[Poetry Archive]] |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> He was the first writer in residence to be appointed by any national rugby union team.\n\n==Early life==\nOwen Sheers was born in [[Suva|Suva, Fiji]] in 1974, and brought up in [[Abergavenny]], south Wales. He went to school at [[King Henry VIII School Abergavenny|King Henry VIII School]] in Abergavenny, before studying at [[New College, Oxford]] and the [[University of East Anglia]], at which point he completed an MA in Creative Writing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/owen-sheers/ |title=Owen Sheers |website=BBC Wales Arts |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> During his time at New College, Sheers captained the Oxford University Modern Pentathlon team.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1999, Sheers received an [[Eric Gregory Award]] from the [[Society of Authors]]. His first collection of poetry, ''The Blue Book'', was published by [[Seren Books|Seren]] in 2000. A collection of poems about family, first love and farming life, it was shortlisted for the [[Wales Book of the Year]] and the [[Forward Prizes for Poetry|Forward Prize]] for 'Best First Collection'. Following this first publication, Sheers worked on the light entertainment television show ''[[The Big Breakfast]]'' as a researcher.<ref Name=\"Resist\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/a-writer-whos-hard-to-resist-6267092.html |title=A writer who's hard to resist |first=Alice |last=Jones |date=24 November 2011 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> His debut prose work, ''The Dust Diaries'',  was published by [[Faber & Faber|Faber]] in 2004. A non-fiction narrative set in [[Zimbabwe]] following the travels of Sheers' great-great-uncle, [[Arthur Shearly Cripps]], it won the Wales Book of the Year in 2005, and was also shortlisted for the [[Royal Society of Literature]]'s [[Ondaatje Prize]].\n\nIn 2004 Sheers was Writer in Residence at [[The Wordsworth Trust]] and was selected as one of the [[Poetry Book Society]]\u2019s 20 [[Next Generation Poets]]. Sheers' second collection of poetry, ''Skirrid Hill'' (Seren, 2005) won a 2006 [[Somerset Maugham Award]]. ''Unicorns, almost'' his one man play based on the life and poetry of the [[WWII]] poet [[Keith Douglas]] was developed by [[Old Vic]], New Voices, and performed by [[Joseph Fiennes]].\n\nSheers' first novel, ''[[Resistance (Owen Sheers novel)|Resistance]]'', has been translated into ten languages and was short listed for the [[Writer's Guild of Great Britain]] Best Book Award 2008 and won a 2008 [[Hospital Club]] Creative Award. The novel imagines that the [[D-day]] landings have failed and Wales been occupied by the [[Nazis]]. Whilst working as a tiler in the South Wales valleys one summer, Sheers had heard about the [[Auxiliary Units]]-secret civilian networks that, in the event of an invasion, would have formed a British resistance, but the novel focuses not on fighting \"but on the uneasy means of survival open to the women who are left behind\". The [[Resistance (2011 film)|film of the novel]], which Sheers co-wrote, was released in autumn 2011 and starred [[Andrea Riseborough]]. Sheers insisted that the film be shot in and around the [[Black Mountains, Wales|Black Mountains]].<ref Name=\"Resist\"/>\n\nIn 2007, Sheers collaborated with composer [[Rachel Portman]] on ''The Water Diviner\u2019s Tale'', an oratorio for children which was premi\u00e8red at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] for the [[BBC Proms]]. In 2007/8 Sheers was a Dorothy and Lewis B. Cullman Fellow at the [[New York Public Library]].\n\nIn 2009, Sheers published the novella 'White Ravens', a contemporary response to the myth of [[Branwen Daughter of Llyr]], written as part of Seren's series of ''New Stories from the [[Mabinogion]]''. He published an anthology of British landscape poetry to accompany his TV series of the same title, ''A Poet's Guide to Britain''.\n\nSheers has also written journalism and reportage for a variety of publications including ''[[Granta]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''[[GQ]]'', ''[[The Times]]'' and ''[[The Financial Times]]''. He wrote a play for [[BBC Radio 4]] about the World War II poet [[Alun Lewis (poet)|Alun Lewis]]: ''If I Should Go Away''. In 2011, Sheers wrote the script and novelisation (''The Gospel of Us'') of ''The Passion'' for [[National Theatre Wales]] and [[WildWorks]]. ''The Gospel of Us'' has been re-published by [[Seren Press]]. Sheers worked with [[Michael Sheen]] co-creating the three-day passion play which unfolded over the Easter weekend of 2011 in Sheen's hometown of [[Port Talbot]]. \"In Sheers's [[Neath]]-flavoured take on the Bible, [[The Last Supper]] became pork pies and beer at the Social Club (with music from the [[Manic Street Preachers]]), while the [[Garden of Gethsemane]] was a scrubby patch of grass on a council estate. \" <ref Name=\"Resist\"/> He participated in the [[Bush Theatre]]'s 2011 project ''[[Sixty Six Books]]'' where he wrote a short play ''The Fair & Tender'' based upon the [[Book of Ezekiel]] in the ''[[King James Bible]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |title=Sixty-Six writers |website=Bush Theatre |accessdate=12 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704090950/http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |archivedate=4 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, Sheers wrote ''The Two Worlds of Charlie F'', a play based on the experiences of wounded soldiers, many of whom also made up the cast of the production, directed by Stephen Rayne and performed at the [[Theatre Royal Haymarket]]. The play has toured the UK and Canada and won the [[Amnesty International]] Freedom of Expression Award at the [[Edinburgh Festival]]. In 2014 his site-specific [[World War I]] play 'Mametz' was produced by National Theatre of Wales.\n\nHis verse drama ''Pink Mist'' was first broadcast on Radio 4 and presents an elegy about camaraderie and loss in modern warfare as seen through the stories of serving soldiers in [[Afghanistan]] and their families. Pink Mist won the 2014 Welsh Book of the Year and was produced as a stage play by the [[Bristol Old Vic]] theatre in 2015, winning mentions as a top ten pick of the year in ''[[The Guardian]]'' and ''[[The Observer]]''. In April 2015 Owen's libretto for Mark Bowden's oratorio 'A Violence of Gifts' was premiered at St David's Hall, Cardiff. The oratorio was devised as a contemporary response to Hayden's Creation oratorio, and was informed by three days research at CERN.\n\nIn 2014 Owen presented a one-hour BBC documentary about the poetry of [[Dylan Thomas]], for which he was shortlisted for a BAFTA Cymru for Best Presenter.\n\nHis novel ''I Saw A Man'' was published in 2015 in the UK, US and several countries across Europe. The French translation was shortlisted for the Prix Femina Etranger. The film rights for the novel have been bought by FilmFour.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nHis play, 'Pink Mist', was first staged at the Bristol Old Vic in 2015. It tells the story of three young Bristolians deployed to Afghanistan. It is their return home to the women in their lives that presents them with their bigger challenges as they all learn to cope with the physical and psychological after effects of war.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thereviewshub.com/pink-mist-bristol-old-vic-bristol-2/ |title=Pink Mist \u2013 Bristol Old Vic |date=18 February 2016 |website=The Reviews Hub |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOwen is currently Professor of Creativity at [[Swansea University]].\n\n==Rugby union==\nIn December 2011, Owen Sheers became the first writer in residence at the [[Welsh Rugby Union]].<ref name=WalOL>{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/need-to-read/2011/12/12/writer-owen-sheers-appointed-wru-s-first-poet-in-residence-91466-29941035/ |title=Writer Owen Sheers appointed WRU's first poet-in-residence |date=12 December 2011 |website=[[Wales Online]] |access-date=21 September 2018}}</ref> Sheers played [[rugby union]], representing Gwent County at scrum half.<ref name=WalOL/>\n\n==Actor & TV presenter==\nSheers has played [[Wilfred Owen]] on stage and has presented arts programmes for [[BBC Wales]].\n\nIn 2009, he wrote and presented the BBC 4 series about poetry and the British landscape, ''A Poet's Guide to Britain''. He has also presented ''The Art of the Sea'' for BBC 4 and documentaries on the poets Keith Douglas and Dylan Thomas. He has presented several programmes for BBC Radio 3 and 4. In 2008 he presented two episodes of BBC Radio 4's ''Open Book'' programme.\n\nIn October 2016, his \"film-poem\", ''[[The Green Hollow]]'', was broadcast by the BBC to commemorate fifty years since the [[Aberfan disaster]] of 1966.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2016/oct/09/the-green-hollow-owen-sheers-extract-aberfan |title=The Green Hollow by Owen Sheers \u2013 extract |first=Owen |last=Sheers |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=9 October 2016 |access-date=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* 1999 Vogue Young Writer\u2019s Award\n* 1999 [[Eric Gregory Award]]\n* 2000 short-listed for the [[Wales Book of the Year]]  (for ''The Blue Book'')\n* 2001 short-listed for [[Forward Poetry Prize]] Best 1st Collection\n* 2005 [[Wales Book of the Year]] (for ''The Dust Diaries'')\n* 2006 [[Somerset Maugham Award]]  (for ''Skirrid Hill'')\n* 2008 Hospital Club Creative Award (for ''[[Resistance (Owen Sheers novel)|Resistance]]'')\n* 2008 short-listed for Writers' Guild Best Book Award for ''Resistance''\n* 2012 Winner Amnesty International Freedom of Expression Award (for 'The Two Worlds of Charlie F')\n* 2013 Hay Medal for Poetry\n* 2014 Wales Book of the Year (for Pink Mist)\n* 2015 Nominated for a BAFTA Cymru for Best Presenter (for A Poet's Guide to Dylan Thomas, BBC 4)\n* 2015 short-listed for Prix Femina Etranger for French translation of 'I Saw A Man'\n* 2018 [[Wilfred Owen]] Poetry Award<ref>{{cite web|title=Wilfred Owen Poetry Award|url=http://www.wilfredowen.org.uk/wilfred-owen-association/poetry-award|work=Wilfred Owen Association|date=1 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.owensheers.co.uk Owen Sheers' Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheers, Owen}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of East Anglia]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Welsh dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Welsh novelists]]\n[[Category:Welsh rugby union players]]\n[[Category:People from Abergavenny]]\n[[Category:People from Suva]]\n[[Category:Fijian people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:Fijian emigrants to Wales]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| name = Owen Sheers\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Sheers in 2014\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1974|09|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Suva]], Fiji\n| occupation = Poet, author, playwright, TV presenter\n| language = English\n| nationality = Welsh\n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| period = 1999\u2013present\n| genre = \n| subject = \n| movement = \n| notableworks = {{Plainlist |\n* ''The Dust Diaries'' (2004)\n* ''Skirrid Hill'' (2005)\n* ''Pink Mist'' (2013)}}\n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Eric Gregory Award]], 1999\n* [[Wales Book of the Year]], 2005\n* [[Somerset Maugham Award]], 2006\n* [[Wales Book of the Year]], 2014}}\n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| module = \n| website = {{URL|www.owensheers.co.uk}}\n| portaldisp = \n}}\n\n'''Owen Sheers''' (born 20 September 1974) is a Welsh poet, author, playwright and TV presenter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.poetryarchive.org/poetryarchive/singlePoet.do?poetId=5918 |title=Owen Sheers b. 1974 |website=[[Poetry Archive]] |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> He was the first writer in residence to be appointed by any national rugby union team.\n\n==Early life==\nOwen Sheers was born in [[Suva|Suva, Fiji]] in 1974, and brought up in [[Abergavenny]], south Wales. He went to school at [[King Henry VIII School Abergavenny|King Henry VIII School]] in Abergavenny, before studying at [[New College, Oxford]] and the [[University of East Anglia]], at which point he completed an MA in Creative Writing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/owen-sheers/ |title=Owen Sheers |website=BBC Wales Arts |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> During his time at New College, Sheers captained the Oxford University Modern Pentathlon team.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1999, Sheers received an [[Eric Gregory Award]] from the [[Society of Authors]]. His first collection of poetry, ''The Blue Book'', was published by [[Seren Books|Seren]] in 2000. A collection of poems about family, first love and farming life, it was shortlisted for the [[Wales Book of the Year]] and the [[Forward Prizes for Poetry|Forward Prize]] for 'Best First Collection'. Following this first publication, Sheers worked on the light entertainment television show ''[[The Big Breakfast]]'' as a researcher.<ref Name=\"Resist\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/a-writer-whos-hard-to-resist-6267092.html |title=A writer who's hard to resist |first=Alice |last=Jones |date=24 November 2011 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> His debut prose work, ''The Dust Diaries'',  was published by [[Faber & Faber|Faber]] in 2004. A non-fiction narrative set in [[Zimbabwe]] following the travels of Sheers' great-great-uncle, [[Arthur Shearly Cripps]], it won the Wales Book of the Year in 2005, and was also shortlisted for the [[Royal Society of Literature]]'s [[Ondaatje Prize]].\n\nIn 2004 Sheers was Writer in Residence at [[The Wordsworth Trust]] and was selected as one of the [[Poetry Book Society]]\u2019s 20 [[Next Generation Poets]]. Sheers' second collection of poetry, ''Skirrid Hill'' (Seren, 2005) won a 2006 [[Somerset Maugham Award]]. ''Unicorns, almost'' his one man play based on the life and poetry of the [[WWII]] poet [[Keith Douglas]] was developed by [[Old Vic]], New Voices, and performed by [[Joseph Fiennes]].\n\nSheers' first novel, ''[[Resistance (Owen Sheers novel)|Resistance]]'', has been translated into ten languages and was short listed for the [[Writer's Guild of Great Britain]] Best Book Award 2008 and won a 2008 [[Hospital Club]] Creative Award. The novel imagines that the [[D-day]] landings have failed and Wales been occupied by the [[Nazis]]. Whilst working as a tiler in the South Wales valleys one summer, Sheers had heard about the [[Auxiliary Units]]-secret civilian networks that, in the event of an invasion, would have formed a British resistance, but the novel focuses not on fighting \"but on the uneasy means of survival open to the women who are left behind\". The [[Resistance (2011 film)|film of the novel]], which Sheers co-wrote, was released in autumn 2011 and starred [[Andrea Riseborough]]. Sheers insisted that the film be shot in and around the [[Black Mountains, Wales|Black Mountains]].<ref Name=\"Resist\"/>\n\nIn 2007, Sheers collaborated with composer [[Rachel Portman]] on ''The Water Diviner\u2019s Tale'', an oratorio for children which was premi\u00e8red at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] for the [[BBC Proms]]. In 2007/8 Sheers was a Dorothy and Lewis B. Cullman Fellow at the [[New York Public Library]].\n\nIn 2009, Sheers published the novella 'White Ravens', a contemporary response to the myth of [[Branwen Daughter of Llyr]], written as part of Seren's series of ''New Stories from the [[Mabinogion]]''. He published an anthology of British landscape poetry to accompany his TV series of the same title, ''A Poet's Guide to Britain''.\n\nSheers has also written journalism and reportage for a variety of publications including ''[[Granta]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''[[GQ]]'', ''[[The Times]]'' and ''[[The Financial Times]]''. He wrote a play for [[BBC Radio 4]] about the World War II poet [[Alun Lewis (poet)|Alun Lewis]]: ''If I Should Go Away''. In 2011, Sheers wrote the script and novelisation (''The Gospel of Us'') of ''The Passion'' for [[National Theatre Wales]] and [[WildWorks]]. ''The Gospel of Us'' has been re-published by [[Seren Press]]. Sheers worked with [[Michael Sheen]] co-creating the three-day passion play which unfolded over the Easter weekend of 2011 in Sheen's hometown of [[Port Talbot]]. \"In Sheers's [[Neath]]-flavoured take on the Bible, [[The Last Supper]] became pork pies and beer at the Social Club (with music from the [[Manic Street Preachers]]), while the [[Garden of Gethsemane]] was a scrubby patch of grass on a council estate. \" <ref Name=\"Resist\"/> He participated in the [[Bush Theatre]]'s 2011 project ''[[Sixty Six Books]]'' where he wrote a short play ''The Fair & Tender'' based upon the [[Book of Ezekiel]] in the ''[[King James Bible]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |title=Sixty-Six writers |website=Bush Theatre |accessdate=12 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704090950/http://www.bushtheatre.co.uk/biography/writers/ |archivedate=4 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, Sheers wrote ''The Two Worlds of Charlie F'', a play based on the experiences of wounded soldiers, many of whom also made up the cast of the production, directed by Stephen Rayne and performed at the [[Theatre Royal Haymarket]]. The play has toured the UK and Canada and won the [[Amnesty International]] Freedom of Expression Award at the [[Edinburgh Festival]]. In 2014 his site-specific [[World War I]] play 'Mametz' was produced by National Theatre of Wales. \n\nHis verse drama ''Pink Mist'' was first broadcast on Radio 4 and presents an elegy about camaraderie and loss in modern warfare as seen through the stories of serving soldiers in [[Afghanistan]] and their families. Pink Mist won the 2014 Welsh Book of the Year and was produced as a stage play by the [[Bristol Old Vic]] theatre in 2015, winning mentions as a top ten pick of the year in ''[[The Guardian]]'' and ''[[The Observer]]''. In April 2015 Owen's libretto for Mark Bowden's oratorio 'A Violence of Gifts' was premiered at St David's Hall, Cardiff. The oratorio was devised as a contemporary response to Hayden's Creation oratorio, and was informed by three days research at CERN.\n\nIn 2014 Owen presented a one-hour BBC documentary about the poetry of [[Dylan Thomas]], for which he was shortlisted for a BAFTA Cymru for Best Presenter.\n\nHis novel ''I Saw A Man'' was published in 2015 in the UK, US and several countries across Europe. The French translation was shortlisted for the Prix Femina Etranger. The film rights for the novel have been bought by FilmFour.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nHis play, 'Pink Mist', was first staged at the Bristol Old Vic in 2015. It tells the story of three young Bristolians deployed to Afghanistan. It is their return home to the women in their lives that presents them with their bigger challenges as they all learn to cope with the physical and psychological after effects of war.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thereviewshub.com/pink-mist-bristol-old-vic-bristol-2/ |title=Pink Mist \u2013 Bristol Old Vic |date=18 February 2016 |website=The Reviews Hub |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOwen is currently Professor of Creativity at [[Swansea University]].\n\n==Rugby union==\nIn December 2011, Owen Sheers became the first writer in residence at the [[Welsh Rugby Union]].<ref name=WalOL>{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/need-to-read/2011/12/12/writer-owen-sheers-appointed-wru-s-first-poet-in-residence-91466-29941035/ |title=Writer Owen Sheers appointed WRU's first poet-in-residence |date=12 December 2011 |website=[[Wales Online]] |access-date=21 September 2018}}</ref> Sheers played [[rugby union]], representing Gwent County at scrum half.<ref name=WalOL/>\n\n==Actor & TV presenter==\nSheers has played [[Wilfred Owen]] on stage and has presented arts programmes for [[BBC Wales]].\n\nIn 2009, he wrote and presented the BBC 4 series about poetry and the British landscape, ''A Poet's Guide to Britain''. He has also presented ''The Art of the Sea'' for BBC 4 and documentaries on the poets Keith Douglas and Dylan Thomas. He has presented several programmes for BBC Radio 3 and 4. In 2008 he presented two episodes of BBC Radio 4's ''Open Book'' programme.\n\nIn October 2016, his \"film-poem\", ''[[The Green Hollow]]'', was broadcast by the BBC to commemorate fifty years since the [[Aberfan disaster]] of 1966.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2016/oct/09/the-green-hollow-owen-sheers-extract-aberfan |title=The Green Hollow by Owen Sheers \u2013 extract |first=Owen |last=Sheers |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=9 October 2016 |access-date=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* 1999 Vogue Young Writer\u2019s Award\n* 1999 [[Eric Gregory Award]]\n* 2000 short-listed for the [[Wales Book of the Year]]  (for ''The Blue Book'')\n* 2001 short-listed for [[Forward Poetry Prize]] Best 1st Collection\n* 2005 [[Wales Book of the Year]] (for ''The Dust Diaries'')\n* 2006 [[Somerset Maugham Award]]  (for ''Skirrid Hill'')\n* 2008 Hospital Club Creative Award (for ''[[Resistance (Owen Sheers novel)|Resistance]]'')\n* 2008 short-listed for Writers' Guild Best Book Award for ''Resistance''\n* 2012 Winner Amnesty International Freedom of Expression Award (for 'The Two Worlds of Charlie F')\n* 2013 Hay Medal for Poetry\n* 2014 Wales Book of the Year (for Pink Mist)\n* 2015 Nominated for a BAFTA Cymru for Best Presenter (for A Poet's Guide to Dylan Thomas, BBC 4)\n* 2015 short-listed for Prix Femina Etranger for French translation of 'I Saw A Man'\n* 2018 [[Wilfred Owen]] Poetry Award<ref>{{cite web|title=Wilfred Owen Poetry Award|url=http://www.wilfredowen.org.uk/wilfred-owen-association/poetry-award|work=Wilfred Owen Association|date=1 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.owensheers.co.uk Owen Sheers' Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheers, Owen}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of East Anglia]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Welsh dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Welsh novelists]]\n[[Category:Welsh rugby union players]]\n[[Category:People from Abergavenny]]\n[[Category:People from Suva]]\n[[Category:Fijian people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:Fijian emigrants to Wales]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Owen_Sheers"}
{"title_page": "Emrys Roberts (poet)", "text_new": "'''Emrys Roberts''' (1929 &ndash; 30 March 2012) was a [[Welsh language]] poet and author, who was [[Archdruid]] of the [[National Eisteddfod of Wales]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-17565600 |title=Former Archdruid of Wales Emrys Roberts dies at 82|accessdate=1 April 2012|date=30 March 2012 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Liverpool]], Roberts grew up in [[Penrhyndeudraeth]] and studied at the Bangor Normal College before becoming a teacher.<ref>John Rowlands, ''The Bloodaxe Book of Modern Welsh Poetry'', p.221</ref>  He twice won the chair at the [[National Eisteddfod of Wales]], in 1967 and 1971. In 1987 he was made [[Archdruid]] and led the [[Gorsedd of Bards]] at the National Eisteddfod between 1987 and 1990 under the bardic name '''Emrys Deudraeth'''.<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = Archdruid of the National Eisteddfod of Wales\n | years  = 1987-1990 | before = [[W. J. Gruffydd (Elerydd)]]\n | after  = [[William R. P. George]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberts, Emrys}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bards of the Gorsedd]]\n[[Category:Chaired bards]]\n[[Category:Welsh-language writers]]\n[[Category:Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Welsh Eisteddfod archdruids]]\n[[Category:Welsh Eisteddfod winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Emrys Roberts''' (1929 &ndash; 30 March 2012) was a [[Welsh language]] poet and author, who was [[Archdruid]] of the [[National Eisteddfod of Wales]].<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-17565600 |title=Former Archdruid of Wales Emrys Roberts dies at 82|accessdate=1 April 2012|date=30 March 2012 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Liverpool]], Roberts grew up in [[Penrhyndeudraeth]] and studied at the Bangor Normal College before becoming a teacher.<ref>John Rowlands, ''The Bloodaxe Book of Modern Welsh Poetry'', p.221</ref>  He twice won the chair at the [[National Eisteddfod of Wales]], in 1967 and 1971. In 1987 he was made [[Archdruid]] and led the [[Gorsedd of Bards]] at the National Eisteddfod between 1987 and 1990 under the bardic name '''Emrys Deudraeth'''.<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = Archdruid of the National Eisteddfod of Wales\n | years  = 1987-1990 | before = [[W. J. Gruffydd (Elerydd)]]\n | after  = [[William R. P. George]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberts, Emrys}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Bards of the Gorsedd]]\n[[Category:Chaired bards]]\n[[Category:Welsh-language writers]]\n[[Category:Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Welsh Eisteddfod archdruids]]\n[[Category:Welsh Eisteddfod winners]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emrys_Roberts_(poet)"}
{"title_page": "Jack Jones (Welsh musician)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Jack Jones\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Jack Jones.jpeg\n| caption          = Jack Jones in 2016\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|1992|02|14}}\n| birth_place      = [[Swansea]], Wales\n| genre            = [[Alternative rock]], [[Garage rock#Revivals|garage rock]], [[indie rock]], poetry, [[spoken word]]\n| instrument       = Vocals, guitar, [[spoken word]]\n| years_active     = \n| associated_acts  = [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]], [[Pete Doherty|Peter Doherty]], [[The Libertines]], [[Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres]]\n}}\n'''Jack Jones''' (born 14 February 1992) is a Welsh musician, songwriter and poet. He is the lead singer and guitarist in the [[alternative rock]] band [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]], and lead guitarist in [[Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres]]. He also performs music and spoken word poetry as a solo artist, being the subject of a BBC Radio 4 documentary titled \"Another Swansea Poet\" broadcast in 2019.<ref name=\":1\" /> He was born in [[Swansea]] and currently lives between London, Berlin and Swansea.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Interview with Trampolene|url = http://www.radsound.co.uk/interview-with-trampolene/|website = Radsound|access-date = 21 February 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140306222541/http://www.radsound.co.uk/interview-with-trampolene/|archive-date = 6 March 2014|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\n{{Main|Trampolene (band)}}\nJones is songwriter, guitarist and lead singer in the band [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]].\n\nHe was asked to be Chrissie Hynde's guitarist, but turned it down due to band commitments with [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]].{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nJones was [[Drew McConnell]] Helsinki's special guest at Servant Jazz Quarters in [[Dalston]], London on 19 April 2016, where he played a solo set of poems and songs.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nDuring May 2016, Jack supported [[Pete Doherty|Peter Doherty]] on his UK \"Eudaimonia\" tour<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://albionrooms.com/eudaimonia-tour-details-a-night-of-music-poetry-and-spoken-word/|title=EUDAIMONIA TOUR \u2013 Details \u2013 A Night of Music, Poetry and Spoken Word \u2013 Albion Rooms|date=4 May 2016|website=Albion Rooms|access-date=4 May 2016}}</ref> and also played guitar for him. Venues included Glasgow [[Barrowland Ballroom]] and two nights at [[Hackney Empire]] in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/features/107143/pete-doherty-2016-tour-diary-by-trampolene-jack-jones-libertines-poet|title=Gigwise|website=}}</ref> He also performed at The Libertines secret show at The Boogaloo, London in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theboogaloo.co.uk/libertines-secret-show-boogaloo/|title=The Libertines \u2013 Secret Show at the Boogaloo \u2013 The Boogaloo|date=29 July 2016|access-date=9 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920213442/http://theboogaloo.co.uk/libertines-secret-show-boogaloo/|archive-date=20 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 he performed solo at [[Latitude Festival]], whose website describes him as a \"music icon\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latitudefestival.com/line-up/artist/keith-allens-establishment-club|title=Keith Allen's Establishment Club|last=admin|date=25 May 2016|access-date=11 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, the day after [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]] headlined at [[The Water Rats|Water Rats]] in London, Jones flew to Argentina to become [[Pete Doherty|Peter Doherty]]'s lead guitarist in his band the Puta Madres, for a November/December 2016 tour of Argentina, France and UK.<ref name=\":0\" />{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} They played two shows for the reopening of [[Bataclan (theatre)|Le Bataclan]] in Paris, followed by a week's tour across France and then Kentish Town Forum in London and Manchester Albert Hall. Jones opened the shows with a solo music and spoken word set, before rejoining the stage as Peter's lead guitarist.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/pete-doherty-bataclan-tour-diary-1860599|title=Pete Doherty at the Bataclan: The Story Of His Moving And Momentous Show \u2013 NME|date=17 November 2016|newspaper=NME|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> He was described in a five star review in [[The Independent]] newspaper as \"Swansea's finest\" and \"sickeningly talented\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/bataclan-anniversary-peter-doherty-carl-barat-libertines-review-sting-paris-attacks-a7422046.html|title=Peter Doherty at the Bataclan \u2013 review|date=17 November 2016|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nJones played two solo shows at the end of 2016, Kazoopa Festival, Leeds in November <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thegryphon.co.uk/2016/12/03/festival-review-kazoopa-festival-261116/|title=Festival Review: Kazoopa Festival, 26/11/16 \u2013 The Gryphon|website=www.thegryphon.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref> and This Feeling's New Year's Eve night at Nambucca, London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nambucca.co.uk/event/this-feeling-nye-extravaganza-rick-witter-paul-banks-of-shed-seven-acoustic-plus-guests-tba/|title=This Feeling NYE extravaganza! Rick Witter & Paul Banks of SHED SEVEN (acoustic) Jack Jones (Trampolene) The Black Roses & much more!|website=www.nambucca.co.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\nHe played two solo shows at [[Russell Brand]]'s charity [[Trew Era Cafe]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://heyevent.uk/event/2zfs5nk4exb4oa/jack-jones-intimate-acoustic-set|title=Jack Jones ~ intimate acoustic set *SOLD OUT* \u2013 Heyevent.uk|website=heyevent.uk|access-date=6 February 2017}}</ref> toured European and South American festivals across Europe in the summer as [[Pete Doherty|Peter Doherty]]'s guitarist and a performed a solo acoustic and spoken word set and a DJ set at Glastonbury festival.\n\nIn November 2017 Jones was interviewed by Janice Long and played acoustic songs live on her BBC Radio Wales show. He was also featured on the promotional video for Swansea's bid for City of Culture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.swansea2021.co.uk|title=Swansea 2021 \u2013 2021 UK City of Culture Bid|website=swansea2021.co.uk|access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nJones was featured on \"Red Stripe Presents: This Feeling TV\" in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gigslutz.co.uk/liam-gallagher-favourites-trampolene-perform-two-tracks-talk-influences-inspiration-behind-feeling-tv/|title=Liam Gallagher favourites Trampolene perform two tracks and talk about the influences and inspiration behind them for This Feeling TV - Gigslutz|date=2018-05-11|work=Gigslutz|access-date=2018-07-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nTo commemorate Trampolene's appearance at BBC Music's Biggest Weekend in Swansea in May 2018, Jones was featured in a \"Wonder Wall\" mural of Welsh musicians, by street artist Pure Evil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://welsh-music-wonder-wall.pilots.bbcconnectedstudio.co.uk/|title=BBC Biggest Weekend Welsh Music Wonder Wall with Huw Stephens|website=welsh-music-wonder-wall.pilots.bbcconnectedstudio.co.uk|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref>\n\nHis debut solo single, the AA side \"Swim Up\"/\"It's Not My Thing\" was released on 7 September 2018 and was played regularly on BBC Radio 1, Radio 6 and Radio X. The single was written with and features Mike Moore, who also plays guitar for [[Liam Gallagher]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://faroutmagazine.co.uk/trampolenes-jack-jones-shares-debut-solo-tracks-swim-up-and-its-not-my-thing/|title=Trampolene's Jack Jones shares debut solo tracks 'Swim Up' and 'It's Not My Thing'|date=2018-07-23|website=Far Out Magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref> It's Not My Thing contains the riff from the track DUST by Lions of Dissent who are also credited as the track's composers.\n\nIn October 2018 he played instore gigs and signing sessions on a short tour of Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://northern-exposure.co/interview-trampolene/|title=INTERVIEW: TRAMPOLENE|website=Northern Exposure|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Jones toured the UK with [[Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/peter-doherty-the-puta-madres-announce-debut-album-and-share-new-single-2439348|title=Peter Doherty & The Puta Madres announce debut album and share new single|last=Reilly|first=Nick|date=2019-01-28|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref> followed by a European tour and several festival appearances with them.\n\nHe played guitar and sang with Peter Doherty on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s \"[[Loose Ends (radio programme)|Loose Ends]]\", broadcast on 13 April <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m00045sv|title=BBC Radio 4 - Loose Ends, Emma Bunton, Toyah, Daisy Haggard, Peter Doherty, YolanDa Brown, Clive Anderson|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref> and on John Kennedy's Xposure show on Radio X, broadcast 30 April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiox.co.uk/artists/libertines/video-pete-doherty-pronounce-name/|title=VIDEO: You've probably been saying Pete Doherty's name wrong...|website=Radio X|language=en|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n===Spoken word===\nIn addition to his poems being an integral part of [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]] as a band, Jack Jones also performs spoken word poetry as a solo artist. [[John Cooper Clarke|Dr John Cooper Clarke]] has described his writing as \"...exceptional poetry, funny and depressing at the same time and how often can you say that.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pirate-treasures.com/trampolene.html|title=Trampolene \u2013 Stage Style {{!}} Pirate Treasures London|website=www.pirate-treasures.com|access-date=27 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.withguitars.com/trampolene-salute-tom-hardy-oscar-nomination-new-single-available-now/|title=TRAMPOLENE salute 'TOM HARDY' Oscar nomination with new single (AVAILABLE NOW)|website=WithGuitars|access-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe video for ''Health & Wellbeing (at Wood Green Job Centre)'' was premiered on [[The Guardian]] website,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2015/mar/04/trampolene-health-wellbeing-at-wood-green-job-centre-video-premiere|title=Trampolene \u2013 Health & Wellbeing (At Wood Green Job Centre): Video premiere|last=music|first=Guardian|date=4 March 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=21 February 2016|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> ''Ketamine'' was premiered on Vice Noisey on 21 October 2015,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/blog/trampolene-ketamine-premiere|title=Come Listen to Some Poetry About Ketamine, Courtesy of Trampolene {{!}} NOISEY|website=NOISEY|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> ''Pound Land'' was premiered on Gigwise on 18 December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/newmusic/104639/jack-jones-of-trampolene-releases-new-video-of-pound-land-poem|title=Premiere: Trampolene release stunning new video for 'Pound Land' {{!}} Gigwise|last=Trefor|first=Cai|website=gigwise.com|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> Gigwise said of Jack Jones \"indie has a new poster boy\" in their article \"Artists who are going to own 2016\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/photos/103571/best-new-bands-of-2016-hinds-blossoms-new-music|title=50 new artists that are going to own 2016 {{!}} Gigwise|last=Pollard|first=Will Butler, Andrew Trendell, Alexandra|website=gigwise.com|access-date=26 February 2016}}</ref> Music business legend and [[1965 Records]] owner James Endeacott described Trampolene as a \"great band and their singer Jack is a wonder\" when sharing the video for ''Artwork of Youth'' on his blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jamesendeacott.wordpress.com/2014/08/06/trampolene-artwork-of-youth/|title=Trampolene \u2013 Artwork of Youth|website=jamesendeacott|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Jones performed his poetry at [[The Great Escape Festival]] in [[Brighton]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://louderthanwar.com/trampoline-announce-minilp-and-single-garage-rock-band-deal-the-gutter-poetry/|title=Trampoline announce miniLP and single : garage rock band deal the gutter poetry \u2013 Louder Than War|website=Louder Than War|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> Stoke Newington Literary Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.withguitars.com/trampolene-new-free-download-spoken-word-single-pound-land/|title=TRAMPOLENE \u2013 New Free Download \u2013 Spoken word single \u2013 POUND LAND|website=WithGuitars|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> and \"Bring the Ruckus\" at The Albany in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wherevent.com/detail/The-Mayor-of-Bring-The-Ruckus|title=Bring The Ruckus|website=wherevent.com|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016 he was personally invited by [[Pete Doherty|Peter Doherty]] and [[Carl Bar\u00e2t]] of [[The Libertines]] to perform on their sell-out arena tour. He performed two poems and then welcomed the band to the stage in front of 20,000 fans. In his first feature in the [[NME]] he is introduced as \"Jack Jones, singer in Welsh indie rockers [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]], plucked from life living in the back of his broken-down van to follow in the proud pre-Libs poetry footsteps of none other than [[Russell Brand]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/the-libertines-secret-tour-poet-revealed#wzZZywywBm0YILeb.01|title=Meet The Libertines' Tour Poet {{!}} NME.COM|last=NME.COM|website=NME|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> On 7 September 2016 he reprised this role to perform his \"To Be A Libertine\" poem and introduce [[The Libertines]] at [[Brixton Academy]] for their Unity Rocks charity show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-libertines/96267|title=Watch The Libertines play first full British gig for nine months {{!}} NME.COM|last=NME.COM|website=NME|access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nJack Jones was the subject of a [[BBC Radio 4]] documentary called \"Another Swansea Poet\", broadcast on 31 March 2019.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p074q7g0/p074q7f2|title=BBC Radio 4 - Another Swansea Poet, The life of Jack Jones - Jack Jones in Swansea|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Writing and other media ===\nJones' first fashion shoot was for OutThere Style magazine, published February 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.outtherestyle.com/2016/02/03/jack-jonessimon-sarin/|title=Jack Jones/Simon Sarin + Nina Thompson OUT THERE STYLE \u2013 OutThere/Style {{!}}|access-date=22 February 2016}}</ref> and was featured wearing jewellery for Pirate Treasures \"Stage Style\" collection also in February 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pirate-treasures.com/stagestyle.html|title=Stage Style Jewellery {{!}} Pirate Treasures London|website=www.pirate-treasures.com|access-date=22 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nJones' first article for [[The Guardian]] was published on 18 March 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/mar/18/young-people-tribes-music-online-smartphones|title=Young people don't have tribes any more. We have smartphones instead|date=18 March 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=21 March 2016|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2016 the [[NME]] published a poem Jones wrote for them about the UK's EU Referendum, based on [[The Clash]] song \"Should I Stay or Should I Go?\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/trampolene-poet-brexit|title=The Libertines' Tour Poet Ponders Brexit in This New Poem|last=NME.COM|website=NME|access-date=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nJones' writing influences include [[Julian Cope]] and [[Dylan Thomas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigslutz.co.uk/gigslutz-interview-trampolene/|title=Gigslutz Interview: Trampolene \u2013 Gigslutz|website=Gigslutz|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> and according to The Musical Manual his spoken word poem ''Ketamine'' \"shares stark resemblance to workings of punk-poet legend, [[John Cooper Clarke]].\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.themusicmanual.co.uk/2015/08/trampolene.html|title=The Music Manual: Trampolene|website=themusicmanual.co.uk|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> Even the Stars music blog described ''\"Ketamine\"'' as \"laced with wit and humour and the other [''\"Pound Land\"''] a droll comical observation of modern life based around a visit to [[Poundland]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eventhestars.co.uk/2015/07/whiteboy-trampolene-bad-molly.html|title=Even The Stars: Whiteboy / Trampolene / Bad Molly \u2013 Manchester Night And Day \u2013 25th July 2015|website=eventhestars.co.uk|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> Jones has been described as a \"singer, guitarist and full-on enigma\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eventhestars.co.uk/2014/06/introducing-trampolene.html|title=Even The Stars: Introducing \u2013 Trampolene|website=eventhestars.co.uk|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> a \"fine poet...With a John Cooper Clarke-esque delivery of his sideways glance into the uglier corners of modern society...wistful and witty poems\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/features/103991/trampolene-band-perform-ketamine-poem-ahead-of-tour-london-shows|title=Gigwise Office Sessions: Trampolene performs 'Ketamine' {{!}} Gigwise|last=Trendell|first=Andrew|website=gigwise.com|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> and as having \"extraordinary stage presence\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subba-cultcha.com/reviews/34|title=NEW ARTIST OF THE DAY \u2013 Trampolene|website=subba-cultcha.com|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Jack}}\n[[Category:Welsh musicians]]\n[[Category:Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Jack Jones\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Jack Jones.jpeg\n| caption          = Jack Jones in 2016\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|1992|02|14}}\n| birth_place      = [[Swansea]], Wales\n| genre            = [[Alternative rock]], [[Garage rock#Revivals|garage rock]], [[indie rock]], poetry, [[spoken word]]\n| instrument       = Vocals, guitar, [[spoken word]]\n| years_active     = \n| associated_acts  = [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]], [[Pete Doherty|Peter Doherty]], [[The Libertines]], [[Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres]]\n}}\n'''Jack Jones''' (born 14 February 1992) is a Welsh musician, songwriter and poet. He is the lead singer and guitarist in the [[alternative rock]] band [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]], and lead guitarist in [[Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres]]. He also performs music and spoken word poetry as a solo artist, being the subject of a BBC Radio 4 documentary titled \"Another Swansea Poet\" broadcast in 2019<ref name=\":1\" />. He was born in [[Swansea]] and currently lives between London, Berlin and Swansea.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Interview with Trampolene|url = http://www.radsound.co.uk/interview-with-trampolene/|website = Radsound|access-date = 21 February 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140306222541/http://www.radsound.co.uk/interview-with-trampolene/|archive-date = 6 March 2014|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\n{{Main|Trampolene (band)}}\nJones is songwriter, guitarist and lead singer in the band [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]].\n\nHe was asked to be Chrissie Hynde's guitarist, but turned it down due to band commitments with [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]].{{cn|date=April 2018}}\n\nJones was [[Drew McConnell]] Helsinki's special guest at Servant Jazz Quarters in [[Dalston]], London on 19 April 2016, where he played a solo set of poems and songs.{{cn|date=April 2018}}\n\nDuring May 2016, Jack supported [[Pete Doherty|Peter Doherty]] on his UK \"Eudaimonia\" tour<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://albionrooms.com/eudaimonia-tour-details-a-night-of-music-poetry-and-spoken-word/|title=EUDAIMONIA TOUR \u2013 Details \u2013 A Night of Music, Poetry and Spoken Word \u2013 Albion Rooms|date=4 May 2016|website=Albion Rooms|access-date=4 May 2016}}</ref> and also played guitar for him. Venues included Glasgow [[Barrowland Ballroom]] and two nights at [[Hackney Empire]] in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/features/107143/pete-doherty-2016-tour-diary-by-trampolene-jack-jones-libertines-poet|title=Gigwise|website=}}</ref> He also performed at The Libertines secret show at The Boogaloo, London in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theboogaloo.co.uk/libertines-secret-show-boogaloo/|title=The Libertines \u2013 Secret Show at the Boogaloo \u2013 The Boogaloo|date=29 July 2016|access-date=9 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920213442/http://theboogaloo.co.uk/libertines-secret-show-boogaloo/|archive-date=20 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 he performed solo at [[Latitude Festival]], whose website describes him as a \"music icon\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latitudefestival.com/line-up/artist/keith-allens-establishment-club|title=Keith Allen's Establishment Club|last=admin|date=25 May 2016|access-date=11 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, the day after [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]] headlined at [[The Water Rats|Water Rats]] in London, Jones flew to Argentina to become [[Pete Doherty|Peter Doherty]]'s lead guitarist in his band the Puta Madres, for a November/December 2016 tour of Argentina, France and UK<ref name=\":0\" />.{{cn|date=April 2018}} They played two shows for the reopening of [[Bataclan (theatre)|Le Bataclan]] in Paris, followed by a week's tour across France and then Kentish Town Forum in London and Manchester Albert Hall. Jones opened the shows with a solo music and spoken word set, before rejoining the stage as Peter's lead guitarist.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/pete-doherty-bataclan-tour-diary-1860599|title=Pete Doherty at the Bataclan: The Story Of His Moving And Momentous Show \u2013 NME|date=17 November 2016|newspaper=NME|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> He was described in a five star review in [[The Independent]] newspaper as \"Swansea's finest\" and \"sickeningly talented\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/bataclan-anniversary-peter-doherty-carl-barat-libertines-review-sting-paris-attacks-a7422046.html|title=Peter Doherty at the Bataclan \u2013 review|date=17 November 2016|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nJones played two solo shows at the end of 2016, Kazoopa Festival, Leeds in November <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thegryphon.co.uk/2016/12/03/festival-review-kazoopa-festival-261116/|title=Festival Review: Kazoopa Festival, 26/11/16 \u2013 The Gryphon|website=www.thegryphon.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>and This Feeling's New Year's Eve night at Nambucca, London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nambucca.co.uk/event/this-feeling-nye-extravaganza-rick-witter-paul-banks-of-shed-seven-acoustic-plus-guests-tba/|title=This Feeling NYE extravaganza! Rick Witter & Paul Banks of SHED SEVEN (acoustic) Jack Jones (Trampolene) The Black Roses & much more!|website=www.nambucca.co.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-04}}</ref>\n\nHe played two solo shows at [[Russell Brand]]'s charity [[Trew Era Cafe]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://heyevent.uk/event/2zfs5nk4exb4oa/jack-jones-intimate-acoustic-set|title=Jack Jones ~ intimate acoustic set *SOLD OUT* \u2013 Heyevent.uk|website=heyevent.uk|access-date=6 February 2017}}</ref> toured European and South American festivals across Europe in the summer as [[Pete Doherty|Peter Doherty]]'s guitarist and a performed a solo acoustic and spoken word set and a DJ set at Glastonbury festival.\n\nIn November 2017 Jones was interviewed by Janice Long and played acoustic songs live on her BBC Radio Wales show. He was also featured on the promotional video for Swansea's bid for City of Culture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.swansea2021.co.uk|title=Swansea 2021 \u2013 2021 UK City of Culture Bid|website=swansea2021.co.uk|access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nJones was featured on \"Red Stripe Presents: This Feeling TV\" in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gigslutz.co.uk/liam-gallagher-favourites-trampolene-perform-two-tracks-talk-influences-inspiration-behind-feeling-tv/|title=Liam Gallagher favourites Trampolene perform two tracks and talk about the influences and inspiration behind them for This Feeling TV - Gigslutz|date=2018-05-11|work=Gigslutz|access-date=2018-07-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nTo commemorate Trampolene's appearance at BBC Music's Biggest Weekend in Swansea in May 2018, Jones was featured in a \"Wonder Wall\" mural of Welsh musicians, by street artist Pure Evil. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://welsh-music-wonder-wall.pilots.bbcconnectedstudio.co.uk/|title=BBC Biggest Weekend Welsh Music Wonder Wall with Huw Stephens|website=welsh-music-wonder-wall.pilots.bbcconnectedstudio.co.uk|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref>\n\nHis debut solo single, the AA side \"Swim Up\"/\"It's Not My Thing\" was released on 7 September 2018 and was played regularly on BBC Radio 1, Radio 6 and Radio X. The single was written with and features Mike Moore, who also plays guitar for [[Liam Gallagher]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://faroutmagazine.co.uk/trampolenes-jack-jones-shares-debut-solo-tracks-swim-up-and-its-not-my-thing/|title=Trampolene's Jack Jones shares debut solo tracks 'Swim Up' and 'It's Not My Thing'|date=2018-07-23|website=Far Out Magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-20}}</ref> It's Not My Thing contains the riff from the track DUST by Lions of Dissent who are also credited as the track's composers.\n\nIn October 2018 he played instore gigs and signing sessions on a short tour of Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://northern-exposure.co/interview-trampolene/|title=INTERVIEW: TRAMPOLENE|website=Northern Exposure|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Jones toured the UK with [[Peter Doherty and the Puta Madres]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/peter-doherty-the-puta-madres-announce-debut-album-and-share-new-single-2439348|title=Peter Doherty & The Puta Madres announce debut album and share new single|last=Reilly|first=Nick|date=2019-01-28|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref> followed by a European tour and several festival appearances with them.\n\nHe played guitar and sang with Peter Doherty on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s \"[[Loose Ends (radio programme)|Loose Ends]]\", broadcast on 13 April <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m00045sv|title=BBC Radio 4 - Loose Ends, Emma Bunton, Toyah, Daisy Haggard, Peter Doherty, YolanDa Brown, Clive Anderson|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-16}}</ref> and on John Kennedy's Xposure show on Radio X, broadcast 30 April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiox.co.uk/artists/libertines/video-pete-doherty-pronounce-name/|title=VIDEO: You've probably been saying Pete Doherty's name wrong...|website=Radio X|language=en|access-date=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n===Spoken word===\nIn addition to his poems being an integral part of [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]] as a band, Jack Jones also performs spoken word poetry as a solo artist. [[John Cooper Clarke|Dr John Cooper Clarke]] has described his writing as \"...exceptional poetry, funny and depressing at the same time and how often can you say that.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pirate-treasures.com/trampolene.html|title=Trampolene \u2013 Stage Style {{!}} Pirate Treasures London|website=www.pirate-treasures.com|access-date=27 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.withguitars.com/trampolene-salute-tom-hardy-oscar-nomination-new-single-available-now/|title=TRAMPOLENE salute 'TOM HARDY' Oscar nomination with new single (AVAILABLE NOW)|website=WithGuitars|access-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe video for ''Health & Wellbeing (at Wood Green Job Centre)'' was premiered on [[The Guardian]] website,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2015/mar/04/trampolene-health-wellbeing-at-wood-green-job-centre-video-premiere|title=Trampolene \u2013 Health & Wellbeing (At Wood Green Job Centre): Video premiere|last=music|first=Guardian|date=4 March 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=21 February 2016|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> ''Ketamine'' was premiered on Vice Noisey on 21 October 2015,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/blog/trampolene-ketamine-premiere|title=Come Listen to Some Poetry About Ketamine, Courtesy of Trampolene {{!}} NOISEY|website=NOISEY|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> ''Pound Land'' was premiered on Gigwise on 18 December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/newmusic/104639/jack-jones-of-trampolene-releases-new-video-of-pound-land-poem|title=Premiere: Trampolene release stunning new video for 'Pound Land' {{!}} Gigwise|last=Trefor|first=Cai|website=gigwise.com|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> Gigwise said of Jack Jones \"indie has a new poster boy\" in their article \"Artists who are going to own 2016\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/photos/103571/best-new-bands-of-2016-hinds-blossoms-new-music|title=50 new artists that are going to own 2016 {{!}} Gigwise|last=Pollard|first=Will Butler, Andrew Trendell, Alexandra|website=gigwise.com|access-date=26 February 2016}}</ref> Music business legend and [[1965 Records]] owner James Endeacott described Trampolene as a \"great band and their singer Jack is a wonder\" when sharing the video for ''Artwork of Youth'' on his blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jamesendeacott.wordpress.com/2014/08/06/trampolene-artwork-of-youth/|title=Trampolene \u2013 Artwork of Youth|website=jamesendeacott|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Jones performed his poetry at [[The Great Escape Festival]] in [[Brighton]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://louderthanwar.com/trampoline-announce-minilp-and-single-garage-rock-band-deal-the-gutter-poetry/|title=Trampoline announce miniLP and single : garage rock band deal the gutter poetry \u2013 Louder Than War|website=Louder Than War|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> Stoke Newington Literary Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.withguitars.com/trampolene-new-free-download-spoken-word-single-pound-land/|title=TRAMPOLENE \u2013 New Free Download \u2013 Spoken word single \u2013 POUND LAND|website=WithGuitars|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> and \"Bring the Ruckus\" at The Albany in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wherevent.com/detail/The-Mayor-of-Bring-The-Ruckus|title=Bring The Ruckus|website=wherevent.com|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016 he was personally invited by [[Pete Doherty|Peter Doherty]] and [[Carl Bar\u00e2t]] of [[The Libertines]] to perform on their sell-out arena tour. He performed two poems and then welcomed the band to the stage in front of 20,000 fans. In his first feature in the [[NME]] he is introduced as \"Jack Jones, singer in Welsh indie rockers [[Trampolene (band)|Trampolene]], plucked from life living in the back of his broken-down van to follow in the proud pre-Libs poetry footsteps of none other than [[Russell Brand]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/the-libertines-secret-tour-poet-revealed#wzZZywywBm0YILeb.01|title=Meet The Libertines' Tour Poet {{!}} NME.COM|last=NME.COM|website=NME|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> On 7 September 2016 he reprised this role to perform his \"To Be A Libertine\" poem and introduce [[The Libertines]] at [[Brixton Academy]] for their Unity Rocks charity show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-libertines/96267|title=Watch The Libertines play first full British gig for nine months {{!}} NME.COM|last=NME.COM|website=NME|access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nJack Jones was the subject of a [[BBC Radio 4]] documentary called \"Another Swansea Poet\", broadcast on 31 March 2019.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p074q7g0/p074q7f2|title=BBC Radio 4 - Another Swansea Poet, The life of Jack Jones - Jack Jones in Swansea|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Writing and other media ===\nJones' first fashion shoot was for OutThere Style magazine, published February 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.outtherestyle.com/2016/02/03/jack-jonessimon-sarin/|title=Jack Jones/Simon Sarin + Nina Thompson OUT THERE STYLE \u2013 OutThere/Style {{!}}|access-date=22 February 2016}}</ref> and was featured wearing jewellery for Pirate Treasures \"Stage Style\" collection also in February 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pirate-treasures.com/stagestyle.html|title=Stage Style Jewellery {{!}} Pirate Treasures London|website=www.pirate-treasures.com|access-date=22 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nJones' first article for [[The Guardian]] was published on 18 March 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/mar/18/young-people-tribes-music-online-smartphones|title=Young people don't have tribes any more. We have smartphones instead|date=18 March 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=21 March 2016|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2016 the [[NME]] published a poem Jones wrote for them about the UK's EU Referendum, based on [[The Clash]] song \"Should I Stay or Should I Go?\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/trampolene-poet-brexit|title=The Libertines' Tour Poet Ponders Brexit in This New Poem|last=NME.COM|website=NME|access-date=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nJones' writing influences include [[Julian Cope]] and [[Dylan Thomas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigslutz.co.uk/gigslutz-interview-trampolene/|title=Gigslutz Interview: Trampolene \u2013 Gigslutz|website=Gigslutz|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> and according to The Musical Manual his spoken word poem ''Ketamine'' \"shares stark resemblance to workings of punk-poet legend, [[John Cooper Clarke]].\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.themusicmanual.co.uk/2015/08/trampolene.html|title=The Music Manual: Trampolene|website=themusicmanual.co.uk|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> Even the Stars music blog described ''\"Ketamine\"'' as \"laced with wit and humour and the other [''\"Pound Land\"''] a droll comical observation of modern life based around a visit to [[Poundland]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eventhestars.co.uk/2015/07/whiteboy-trampolene-bad-molly.html|title=Even The Stars: Whiteboy / Trampolene / Bad Molly \u2013 Manchester Night And Day \u2013 25th July 2015|website=eventhestars.co.uk|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> Jones has been described as a \"singer, guitarist and full-on enigma\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eventhestars.co.uk/2014/06/introducing-trampolene.html|title=Even The Stars: Introducing \u2013 Trampolene|website=eventhestars.co.uk|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> a \"fine poet...With a John Cooper Clarke-esque delivery of his sideways glance into the uglier corners of modern society...wistful and witty poems\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/features/103991/trampolene-band-perform-ketamine-poem-ahead-of-tour-london-shows|title=Gigwise Office Sessions: Trampolene performs 'Ketamine' {{!}} Gigwise|last=Trendell|first=Andrew|website=gigwise.com|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref> and as having \"extraordinary stage presence\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.subba-cultcha.com/reviews/34|title=NEW ARTIST OF THE DAY \u2013 Trampolene|website=subba-cultcha.com|access-date=21 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Jack}}\n[[Category:Welsh musicians]]\n[[Category:Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Jones_(Welsh_musician)"}
{"title_page": "Meic Stephens", "text_new": "{{hatnote|For the singer, see [[Meic Stevens]].}}\n{{short description|Welsh literary editor, journalist (1938\u20132018)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Meic Stephens\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1938|07|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Treforest]], [[Glamorgan]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2018|07|02|1938|07|23|df=y}}\n| death_place        = [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]]\n| burial_place       = \n| occupation         = Literary editor, journalist, author, teacher, university professor\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = ''The Oxford Companion to the Literature of Wales'' (1986)\n}}\n'''Meic Stephens''' (23 July 1938 \u2013 2 July 2018)<ref name=\"guardian-obit\">{{cite news |last1=Adams |first1=Sam |title=Meic Stephens obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jul/05/meic-stephens-obituary |accessdate=6 July 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-44699274|title=Prolific Welsh journalist and scholar Meic Stephens dies|date=3 July 2018|work=|accessdate=3 July 2018|url-status=live|publisher=BBC Wales}}</ref> was a Welsh [[literary editor]], [[journalist]], translator, and poet.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shipton|first=Martin|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/tributes-great-welsh-writer-meic-14861356|title=Tributes to the great Welsh writer Meic Stephens, who has died aged 79|date=4 July 2018|work=WalesOnline|access-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Birth and education==\nStephens was born on 23 July 1938 in the village of [[Treforest]], near [[Pontypridd]], [[Glamorgan]]. He studied at the [[Aberystwyth University|University College of Wales]], [[Aberystwyth]], graduating in 1961, at the [[University of Rennes]], [[Brittany]], and the [[Bangor University|University College of North Wales]], [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]], [[Gwynedd]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00meic/page/562/mode/1up|title=Oxford Companion to the Literature of Wales|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1986|isbn=0-19-211586-3|editor-last=Stephens|editor-first=Meic|location=Oxford|page=562}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 1962\u20131966 he taught French at [[Ebbw Vale]], [[Monmouthshire]]. In [[Merthyr Tydfil]] he established the Triskel Press and in 1965 he began the periodical, ''[[Poetry Wales]]''. He learnt Welsh as an adult, and became a member of [[Welsh Language Society|Cymdeithas yr Iaith Cymraeg]] and of [[Plaid Cymru]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter working for the [[Western Mail (Wales)|''Western Mail'']] for almost a year, from 1967\u20131990 Stephens was literature director of the [[Welsh Arts Council]]. Before retiring he was professor of Welsh Writing in English at the [[University of Glamorgan]]. He was also a visiting professor in the English department of [[Brigham Young University]] (United States).<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nStephens is credited as the first person to create the ''[[Cofiwch Dryweryn]]'' graffiti near [[Llanrhystyd]], [[Ceredigion]].<ref name=\"online\">{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/vandals-deface-famous-cofiwch-dryweryn-6740008|title=Vandals deface famous Cofiwch Dryweryn memorial|last=Morgon|first=Sion|date=24 February 2014|publisher=Wales Online|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> This painted slogan has come to be regarded as an unofficial 'national landmark' commemorating [[Capel Celyn]], a Welsh speaking village near [[Bala, Gwynedd|Bala]], that was destroyed by the construction of the [[Llyn Celyn]] reservoir in the early 1960s.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/mid_/8652096.stm|title='National landmark' Cofiwch Dryweryn is defaced|date=29 April 2010|work=|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n== Writings ==\nStephens wrote many articles about literature in Wales for the ''Western Mail'', as well as obituaries of eminent Welsh people for ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> He took a particular interest in the life and work of [[Rhys Davies (writer)|Rhys Davies]], the novelist and short story writer, and founded and served as secretary of the Rhys Davies Trust, which promoted the writing of short fiction in Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesartsreview.org/remembering-meic-stephens/|title=Remembering Meic Stephens|author=Phil Morris|date=4 July 2018|website=Wales Arts Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhysdaviestrust.org/|title=About the Trust|date=2020|website='the' Rhys Davies Trust|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nStephens' works include:\n\n*''Linguistic Minorities in Western Europe'' (1976. J. D. Lewis {{ISBN|9780850883626}})\n*''Green Horse'' (1978. {{ISBN|9780715404867|}})\n* [ed.] ''The Oxford Companion to the Literature of Wales'' (1986; republished in 1998 as ''The New Companion to the Literature of Wales''. Oxford University Press {{ISBN|9780192115867}})\n*''Illuminations: An Anthology of Welsh Short Prose'' (1998. Welsh Academic Press {{ISBN|9781860570100}})\n*''A Most Peculiar People: Quotations About Wales and the Welsh'' (1992. University of Wales Press {{ISBN|9780708311684}})\n*''Little Book of Welsh Quotations'' (1997. Appletree Press {{ISBN|9780862817039}})\n*''A Pocket Guide Series: Wales in Quotation'' (1999. University of Wales Press {{ISBN|9780708315606}})\n*''Welsh Names for Your Children: The Complete Guide'' (2000. Y Lolfa {{ISBN|9781847714305}})\n*''The Literary Pilgrim in Wales: A Guide to the Places Associated with Writers in Wales'' (2000. Gwasg Carreg Gwalch {{ISBN|9780863816123}})\n*''A Semester in Zion: A Journal with Memoirs'' (2003. Gwasg Carreg Gwalch {{ISBN|9780863818493}})\n*''Yeah, Dai Dando'' (2008. Cinnamon ''{{ISBN|9781905614592}}'')<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/local-news/treforest-mans-new-book-2147564|title=Treforest man's new book|date=23 October 2008|work=WalesOnline|access-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*''A Bard for Highgrove: A Likely Story'' (2010. Cambria Books {{ISBN|9781844269341|}})\n*''Cofnodion - Hunangofiant''  (2012. Y Lolfa {{ISBN|9781847714305}})\n*''Welsh Lives - Gone but Not Forgotten'' (2012. Y Lolfa {{ISBN|9781847714879}})\n*''[[:cy:Rhys Davies - A Writer's Life|Rhys Davies - A Writer's Life]]'' (2013. Parthian Books {{ISBN|9781908946713}})\n*''Wilia - Cerddi 2003-2013'' (2014. Cyhoeddiadau Barddas {{ISBN|9781906396701}})\n*''My Shoulder to the Wheel'' (2015. Y Lolfa {{ISBN|9781784610746}})\n*''The Old Red Tongue: An Anthology of Welsh Literature'' (2017. Francis Boutle Publishers {{ISBN|9780995747319}})\n*''More Welsh Lives'' (2018. Y Lolfa {{ISBN|9781860570186|}})\n*[[Luis N\u00fa\u00f1ez Astrain]], ''The Basques: Their Struggle for Independence'' (translation) (1997. Welsh Academic Press {{ISBN|9781860570186|}})\n\n== Honours ==\nStephens was honoured as a [[Honorary fellow|Fellow]] of [[Aberystwyth University]] in 2018.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aber.ac.uk/en/news/archive/2018/05/title-213010-en.html|title=The author Meic Stephens honoured as Fellow|date=16 May 2018|website=University of Aberystwyth|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nStephens died in [[Cardiff]] on 2 July 2018.<ref name=\"guardian-obit\" /><ref>GRO Death Index. Stephens, Meic. DOR\u00a0 Q3/2018 in Cardiff \u00a0(890-1D). \u00a0Entry Number: 517558573.</ref> He had four children, his son [[Huw Stephens]] is a radio presenter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.rhysdaviestrust.org/ Rhys Davies Trust - official website]\n* [http://www.seren-books.com/authors/?author_id=1458 Meic Stephens, profile - ''Seren Books''] \n*[http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/news/2008/10/25/tributes-to-writer-meic-stephens-for-his-70th-birthday-91466-22112987 Tributes - ''WalesOnline'']\n*[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/meic-stephens-dead-obituary-welsh-language-literature-a8473246.html Obituary - ''The Independent'']\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/search?q=au%3AMeic+stephens Catalogue of publications - WorldCat]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephens, Meic}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Glamorgan]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Bangor University]]\n[[Category:Bards of the Gorsedd]]\n[[Category:Welsh-speaking academics]]\n[[Category:People from Pontypridd]]\n[[Category:Welsh historians]]\n[[Category:Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Welsh literary editor, journalist (1938\u20132018)}}\n{{hatnote|For the singer, see [[Meic Stevens]].}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Meic Stephens\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1938|07|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Treforest]], [[Glamorgan]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2018|07|02|1938|07|23|df=y}}\n| death_place        = [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]]\n| burial_place       = \n| occupation         = Literary editor, journalist, author, teacher, university professor\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = ''The Oxford Companion to the Literature of Wales'' (1986)\n}}\n'''Meic Stephens''' (23 July 1938 \u2013 2 July 2018)<ref name=\"guardian-obit\">{{cite news |last1=Adams |first1=Sam |title=Meic Stephens obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jul/05/meic-stephens-obituary |accessdate=6 July 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-44699274|title=Prolific Welsh journalist and scholar Meic Stephens dies|date=3 July 2018|work=|accessdate=3 July 2018|url-status=live|publisher=BBC Wales}}</ref> was a Welsh [[literary editor]], [[journalist]], translator, and poet.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shipton|first=Martin|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/tributes-great-welsh-writer-meic-14861356|title=Tributes to the great Welsh writer Meic Stephens, who has died aged 79|date=4 July 2018|work=WalesOnline|access-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Birth and education==\nStephens was born on 23 July 1938 in the village of [[Treforest]], near [[Pontypridd]], [[Glamorgan]]. He studied at the [[Aberystwyth University|University College of Wales]], [[Aberystwyth]], graduating in 1961, at the [[University of Rennes]], [[Brittany]], and the [[Bangor University|University College of North Wales]], [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]], [[Gwynedd]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00meic/page/562/mode/1up|title=Oxford Companion to the Literature of Wales|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1986|isbn=0-19-211586-3|editor-last=Stephens|editor-first=Meic|location=Oxford|page=562}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 1962\u20131966 he taught French at [[Ebbw Vale]], [[Monmouthshire]]. In [[Merthyr Tydfil]] he established the Triskel Press and in 1965 he began the periodical, ''[[Poetry Wales]]''. He learnt Welsh as an adult, and became a member of [[Welsh Language Society|Cymdeithas yr Iaith Cymraeg]] and of [[Plaid Cymru]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter working for the [[Western Mail (Wales)|''Western Mail'']] for almost a year, from 1967\u20131990 Stephens was literature director of the [[Welsh Arts Council]]. Before retiring he was professor of Welsh Writing in English at the [[University of Glamorgan]]. He was also a visiting professor in the English department of [[Brigham Young University]] (United States).<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nStephens is credited as the first person to create the ''[[Cofiwch Dryweryn]]'' graffiti near [[Llanrhystyd]], [[Ceredigion]].<ref name=\"online\">{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/vandals-deface-famous-cofiwch-dryweryn-6740008|title=Vandals deface famous Cofiwch Dryweryn memorial|last=Morgon|first=Sion|date=24 February 2014|publisher=Wales Online|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> This painted slogan has come to be regarded as an unofficial 'national landmark' commemorating [[Capel Celyn]], a Welsh speaking village near [[Bala, Gwynedd|Bala]], that was destroyed by the construction of the [[Llyn Celyn]] reservoir in the early 1960s.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/mid_/8652096.stm|title='National landmark' Cofiwch Dryweryn is defaced|date=29 April 2010|work=|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\n== Writings ==\nStephens wrote many articles about literature in Wales for the ''Western Mail'', as well as obituaries of eminent Welsh people for ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> He took a particular interest in the life and work of [[Rhys Davies (writer)|Rhys Davies]], the novelist and short story writer, and founded and served as secretary of the Rhys Davies Trust, which promoted the writing of short fiction in Wales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesartsreview.org/remembering-meic-stephens/|title=Remembering Meic Stephens|author=Phil Morris|date=4 July 2018|website=Wales Arts Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhysdaviestrust.org/|title=About the Trust|date=2020|website='the' Rhys Davies Trust|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nStephens' works include:\n\n*''Linguistic Minorities in Western Europe'' (1976. J. D. Lewis {{ISBN|9780850883626}})\n*''Green Horse'' (1978. {{ISBN|9780715404867|}})\n* [ed.] ''The Oxford Companion to the Literature of Wales'' (1986; republished in 1998 as ''The New Companion to the Literature of Wales''. Oxford University Press {{ISBN|9780192115867}})\n*''Illuminations: An Anthology of Welsh Short Prose'' (1998. Welsh Academic Press {{ISBN|9781860570100}})\n*''A Most Peculiar People: Quotations About Wales and the Welsh'' (1992. University of Wales Press {{ISBN|9780708311684}})\n*''Little Book of Welsh Quotations'' (1997. Appletree Press {{ISBN|9780862817039}})\n*''A Pocket Guide Series: Wales in Quotation'' (1999. University of Wales Press {{ISBN|9780708315606}})\n*''Welsh Names for Your Children: The Complete Guide'' (2000. Y Lolfa {{ISBN|9781847714305}})\n*''The Literary Pilgrim in Wales: A Guide to the Places Associated with Writers in Wales'' (2000. Gwasg Carreg Gwalch {{ISBN|9780863816123}})\n*''A Semester in Zion: A Journal with Memoirs'' (2003. Gwasg Carreg Gwalch {{ISBN|9780863818493}})\n*''Yeah, Dai Dando'' (2008. Cinnamon ''{{ISBN|9781905614592}}'')<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/local-news/treforest-mans-new-book-2147564|title=Treforest man's new book|date=23 October 2008|work=WalesOnline|access-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*''A Bard for Highgrove: A Likely Story'' (2010. Cambria Books {{ISBN|9781844269341|}})\n*''Cofnodion - Hunangofiant''  (2012. Y Lolfa {{ISBN|9781847714305}})\n*''Welsh Lives - Gone but Not Forgotten'' (2012. Y Lolfa {{ISBN|9781847714879}})\n*''[[:cy:Rhys_Davies_-_A_Writer's_Life|Rhys Davies - A Writer's Life]]'' (2013. Parthian Books {{ISBN|9781908946713}})\n*''Wilia - Cerddi 2003-2013'' (2014. Cyhoeddiadau Barddas {{ISBN|9781906396701}})\n*''My Shoulder to the Wheel'' (2015. Y Lolfa {{ISBN|9781784610746}})\n*''The Old Red Tongue: An Anthology of Welsh Literature'' (2017. Francis Boutle Publishers {{ISBN|9780995747319}})\n*''More Welsh Lives'' (2018. Y Lolfa {{ISBN|9781860570186|}})\n\n*[[Luis N\u00fa\u00f1ez Astrain]], ''The Basques: Their Struggle for Independence'' (translation) (1997. Welsh Academic Press {{ISBN|9781860570186|}})\n\n== Honours ==\nStephens was honoured as a [[Honorary fellow|Fellow]] of [[Aberystwyth University]] in 2018.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aber.ac.uk/en/news/archive/2018/05/title-213010-en.html|title=The author Meic Stephens honoured as Fellow|date=16 May 2018|website=University of Aberystwyth|access-date=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Death ==\nStephens died in [[Cardiff]] on 2 July 2018.<ref name=\"guardian-obit\" /><ref>GRO Death Index. Stephens, Meic. DOR\u00a0 Q3/2018 in Cardiff \u00a0(890-1D). \u00a0Entry Number: 517558573.</ref> He had four children, his son [[Huw Stephens]] is a radio presenter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.rhysdaviestrust.org/ Rhys Davies Trust - official website]\n* [http://www.seren-books.com/authors/?author_id=1458 Meic Stephens, profile - ''Seren Books''] \n*[http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/news/2008/10/25/tributes-to-writer-meic-stephens-for-his-70th-birthday-91466-22112987 Tributes - ''WalesOnline'']\n*[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/meic-stephens-dead-obituary-welsh-language-literature-a8473246.html Obituary - ''The Independent'']\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/search?q=au%3AMeic+stephens Catalogue of publications - WorldCat]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephens, Meic}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Glamorgan]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Bangor University]]\n[[Category:Bards of the Gorsedd]]\n[[Category:Welsh-speaking academics]]\n[[Category:People from Pontypridd]]\n[[Category:Welsh historians]]\n[[Category:Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meic_Stephens"}
